<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 00:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Driver of car that killed Stanford professor in coffee shop faces DWI </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ENGLEWOOD, N.J. (AP) - The driver of a car that killed a
Stanford University astrophysicist when it crashed into a coffee
shop here has been charged with driving while intoxicated.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Willick, 40, who had said his studies examined the
''large-scale structure of the universe,'' died while working on a
laptop computer while sitting in a Starbucks along Route 4. He had
been visiting family nearby.
</P>
<P>
   A 2000 Ford Mustang GT driven by Joseph A. Santiglia, 53, of
Wilkes-Barre, Pa., veered off the right lane of the busy highway at
2:49 p.m. Sunday into a parking lot and then slammed into the shop,
Assistant Bergen County Prosecutor John L. Higgins said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Willick was pinned between a wall and the vehicle, Higgins said.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's no indication that this was a deliberate attempt to
avoid traffic or cut through,'' said Higgins, chief of the
prosecutor's fatal accident investigation unit.
</P>
<P>
   Santiglia was given a summons for driving while intoxicated
based on observations made by officers, Higgins said. No breath or
mobility tests were administered because Santiglia was checked for
injuries at a hospital after being extricated from the car, Higgins
said.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities await the results in two to three weeks of a blood
test to determine if Santiglia's glassy eyes, slurred speech and
imbalance were due to alcohol, drugs or the crash, Higgins said.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of the crash has not been determined. The vehicle's
speed has yet to be calculated, and the Mustang is to be examined
for any mechanical defects, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Mustang had antilock brakes, which typically do not leave
skid marks if they are operating, but the parking lot is being
checked for marks the tires may have left.
</P>
<P>
   Willick is the son of Martin S. Willick of Teaneck, a prominent
psychiatrist and lecturer at Columbia University, according to The
Record of Hackensack.
</P>
<P>
   The younger Willick lived in Palo Alto, Calif., with his wife
and a son and daughter. The couple were expecting a third child.
</P>
<P>
   Santiglia was taking his parents back to their home in Fort Lee
from a family function, Higgins said. His mother Maria Fabie, 76,
and stepfather, Alfred Fabie, 78, were checked at a hospital but
had no major injuries and went home, Higgins said.
</P>
<P>
   Santiglia has an unlisted telephone number and could not be
reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Willick, an assistant professor of physics at Stanford since
1995, has said, ''My work addresses the 'big questions' facing
contemporary cosmology: Is the universe flat? Is there a nonzero
cosmological constant? Did structure in the contemporary universe
emerge from the very nearly uniform primordial distribution of
matter solely via the process of gravitational instability? What is
the nature of the 'dark matter' believed to constitute 90 percent
of the total mass of the universe?''
</P>
<P>
   Willick got his bachelor's degree in chemistry and physics in
1981 from Harvard University, his master's in physics at the
University of California, Berkeley in 1983, and his doctorate in
physics at Berkeley in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   He taught physics at Dwight Englewood High School in Englewood
from 1983-84, and at Berkeley from 1984-85, where he was a research
assistant from 1985-91. He did postdoctoral work at the Carnegie
Observatories from 1991-95.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Stanford University:
http://www.standford.edu/dept/physics
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-20-00 0002 </TRAILER>
