<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 00:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Military jet crashes during air show, pilot and crew member killed  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL RUBINKAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILLOW GROVE, Pa. (AP) - Investigators examined a wooded area
Monday as they attempted to piece together the cause of an air show
crash that left two naval aviators dead and horrified tens of
thousands of spectators.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy released few details of the investigation, refusing to
confirm whether the flight recorders were recovered or if the
pilots attempted to eject before crashing on private land about 100
yards from the Willow Grove Naval Air Station.
</P>
<P>
   The two men killed in the crash were pilot Lt. William Joseph
Dey, 30, of Hightstown, N.J., and radar intercept officer Lt. David
Erick Bergstrom, 31, of Annandale, Va. Both fliers were assigned to
Fighter Squadron 101 from the Oceana Naval Air Station in Oceana,
Va.
</P>
<P>
   The F-14A Tomcat fighter was taking part in the next-to-last
performance at the Willow Grove 2000 Sounds of Freedom air show
Sunday when it banked steeply, shook and plunged into the woods
across a busy highway.
</P>
<P>
   Both the pilot and radio officer were experienced flyers who had
been in the Navy eight years. Dey was an instructor pilot with more
than 1,400 total flight hours and more than 1,100 flight hours in
the F-14. Bergstrom had more than 1,200 total flight hours and more
than 1,000 flight hours in the F-14.
</P>
<P>
   The pilots were ''performing routine tactical maneuvers'' at the
time of the accident, Willow Grove spokeswoman Sherri Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said the Tomcat was displaying a ''wave-off''
maneuver, in which the plane comes in at slow speed to make a
landing, then circles for another attempt as if waved off from the
first.
</P>
<P>
   It is an easy maneuver, especially for an experienced pilot like
Dey, according to retired Navy Cmdr. Woody Woodward, who viewed an
amateur video of the crash.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is nothing dangerous or magic about a wave-off
maneuver,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward, who flew in F-14s for 23 years as a radar intercept
officer, said he could not determine from the video what went
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ''Unfortunately, the things you would like to be able to see are
indistinct in the tape,'' said Woodward, a volunteer coordinator at
the National Museum of Naval Aviation in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Gail Eldridge, Dey's aunt, called him ''the best guy there
was.''
</P>
<P>
   ''He was the top gun of our family,'' she said from Dey's
grandmother's house in Hightstown, N.J., Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Dey graduated from the U.S. Naval Academy, she said.
</P>
<P>
   He and his wife, Deb, and their 18-month-old daughter, Kamryn,
lived in Virginia. His wife traveled to Pennsylvania on Saturday to
watch the air show with Dey's family and celebrate their fifth
wedding anniversary. Eldridge said the family was not at the show
Sunday when his plane crashed.
</P>
<P>
   Dey also is survived by his parents and three sisters.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy permitted journalists a brief visit to the crash site
Monday, and the bulk of the wreckage was barely visible through a
thick stand of oak trees. About 100 feet away in plain site,
however, was a piece that appeared to be a seat.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators sealed off a two-block-square area around the
crash site, including several nearby homes and businesses. At least
one, a dental practice directly in front of the wreckage, was
expected to be closed until Wednesday, said a woman who answered
the phone there.
</P>
<P>
   The powerful, acrobatic Tomcat is one of the most highly sought
after attractions at air shows, said John B. Cudahy, president of
the International Council of Air Shows, an industry trade group.
There are only two Tomcat teams in the nation, and up to 450 air
shows a year, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''A show considers itself lucky indeed to have a Tomcat come in
and fly,'' Cudahy said. ''It's just a very dramatic plane that
represents all that is good about the Navy.''
</P>
<P>
   Pilots in the demonstration flights are instructors at Oceana
Naval Air Station, a training base for F-14 pilots and crew
members. They are chosen in a highly competitive selection process
and undergo additional training for the shows, said Mike Maus, a
spokesman for the Naval Air Force, U.S. Atlantic Fleet, in Norfolk,
Va.
</P>
<P>
   The status of the Willow Grove show is uncertain. The commanding
officer of the naval air station, Capt. Thomas Nagelin, will have
final say.
</P>
<P>
   ''An air show is for the community. He'll evaluate what the
community would like,'' said Jones, the air base spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation is being handled by the Federal Aviation
Administration, the National Transportation Safety Board, the Naval
Safety Center and the Military Mishap Board, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Jones confirmed the $38 million jet had some ''recording
systems,'' but would not specify whether data from them were
recovered. She also did not say how old the airplane was.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.nasjrbwillowgrove.navy.mil/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
