<HEADLINE> Billy Graham Hospitalized  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Evangelist Billy Graham was hospitalized at
the Mayo Clinic after undergoing a procedure to relieve fluid
buildup around his brain, aides said.
</P>
<P>
   The 81-year-old evangelist is doing well and is expected to
recover, according to A. Larry Ross, chief spokesman for Graham
Crusades in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Ross declined to discuss specifics about Graham's health but
said his condition is not life-threatening.
</P>
<P>
   Ross said Graham is undergoing ''a number of diagnostic
procedures and ongoing therapy to optimize his Parkinson's
condition and overall health.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham's condition ''is quite stable,'' Ross said Mayo officials
told him Monday evening. A spokesman for the Rochester clinic was
not available for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Ross said that after Graham's crusade in Nashville early this
month, doctors advised Graham to slow down because of fatigue. He
said they recommended rest in order to prepare for Amsterdam 2000,
a world gathering of 10,000 evangelists from July 29 through Aug.
6.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Graham has undergone treatment for Parkinson's
disease at the Mayo Clinic. He was diagnosed with the degenerative
brain condition about six years ago.
</P>
<P>
   His Billy Graham Evangelistic Association is based in
Minneapolis.
</P>
</TEXT>
