<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 00:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Magazine asks readers to vote in political cookie contest  </HEADLINE>
By DEEPTI HAJELA
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - If this is an election year, it must be time for
a cookie contest.
</P>
<P>
   And indeed it is. Family Circle magazine is asking readers to
decide which of the could-be first ladies, Laura Bush or Tipper
Gore, bakes the best cookies in its Third National Bipartisan
Cookie Cook-off.
</P>
<P>
   The current issue of the magazine, dated July 11, puts Bush's
Texas Governor's Mansion Cowboy Cookies up against Gore's Ginger
Snaps. Readers are asked to make a batch of each, and then send in
postcards by Aug. 1 to vote for which one they liked best.
</P>
<P>
   The cookie cook-off was started in 1992, after Hillary Rodham
Clinton stirred up some controversy for defending her legal career
by remarking that ''I suppose I could have stayed home and baked
cookies and had teas.''
</P>
<P>
   She apologized for the statement, and put up a recipe she used
against one used by Barbara Bush. Clinton's recipe won, and like
her husband, it ran successfully for re-election in 1996 against a
recipe for pecan roll cookies from Elizabeth Dole.
</P>
<P>
   But alas, since her husband is no longer eligible to run,
neither can Clinton's cookie recipe. And so the baton passes to
Gore, to see if she can continue the Democrat dominance in this
culinary contest.
</P>
<P>
   It could be a challenge - this year, it's the Republican spouse
who has the recipe for the cookie with the chips. And coconut, and
pecans, and rolled oats. Gore's ginger snaps are chip-less, and
contain ingredients like molasses and cinnamon. It remains to be
seen if that will be enough to wow the nation's sweet tooth.
</P>
<P>
   While there's no contest for Senate spouses - yet - a cook-off
in New York might show whether President Clinton has the culinary
skills to match his political abilities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
