<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 114 Said Killed in Jakarta Violence  </HEADLINE>
By GEOFF SPENCER
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- Christians and Muslims battled on a
remote eastern Indonesian island, killing at least 116 in the
latest chapter in a longrunning sectarian conflict, police and
witnesses said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Police said 108 Christians and eight Muslims died in Monday's
clash in the Maluku islands.
</P>
<P>
   The official Antara news agency said 70 people also were wounded
in the violence in the Christian village of Duma, on Halmahera
island about 1,600 miles northeast of Jakarta. The clash lasted for
about one hour.
</P>
<P>
   Antara said the dead were killed with homemade guns and bombs as
well as bows and arrows. However, a local Protestant clergy man,
Father Hadi, told The Associated Press by telephone that some
Muslim attackers were armed with military-style weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Antara said 292 homes and a church were burned.
</P>
<P>
   Military officials in the region were not immediately available
to confirm details of the fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's violence is the latest outbreak in an 18-month gang war
between Muslims and Christians in the Maluku islands, also known as
the Moluccas, where more than 2,500 people have been killed.
</P>
<P>
   wounded victims had been evacuated to Tobelo, about 20 miles
north of Duma village, army officer Maj. Puguh, who like many
Indonesians uses only one name, told Antara.
</P>
<P>
   He said soldiers and marines dispersed the warring gangs.
However, the situation on Halmahera remained tense Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   At least two soldiers had been wounded, witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
   Hadi, who is based in Tobelo, said fleeing villagers from Duma
told him that about 500 Muslims fighters in black and white
uniforms descended upon their homes.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a very quick attack. They had automatic rifles but the
Christians only had homemade weapons,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hadi said about 1,000 mainly Christians live permanently in
Duma, but its population had swelled by 2,000 from people who fled
violence in the surrounding countryside in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Hadi said there were only about 30 soldiers on duty in the
village and were unable to stop the violence until the military
reinforcements arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Local Muslim groups were not immediately available for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The violence continues to rage in the Maluku islands, known as
the Spice Islands in Dutch colonial times, despite repeated peace
efforts by Indonesian President Abdurrahman Wahid, a respected
Muslim cleric who espouses religious tolerance.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month Pope John Paul II urged Indonesia's leaders
to do more to stop the carnage.
</P>
<P>
   About 90 percent of Indonesia's 210 million people are Muslim,
making it the world most populous Islamic country. But Christians
are the majority in the Maluku islands, which had been renowned for
religious tolerance before violence broke out in January 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Some blame the conflict on economic and social pressure from an
increasing numbers of Muslims settlers from other parts of the
sprawling Southeast Asian nation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-20-00 0020 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
