<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Moderate Quake Hits Central Taiwan  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- A moderate earthquake shook central Taiwan
on Tuesday, the latest in a series of tremors rattling this island.
No damage or injuries were immediately reported.
</P>
<P>
   The 5.7-magnitude quake's epicenter was about 30 miles southeast
of Taichung, Taiwan's third-largest city, the Central Weather
Bureau said. Taichung is about 80 miles south of the capital,
Taipei.
</P>
<P>
   A 5-magnitude quake can cause considerable damage.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a 6.7-magnitude quake struck near Mount Yu in central
Taiwan 180 miles south of Taipei, triggering rock slides and
injuring 36 people.
</P>
<P>
   The tremors were among the thousands that have rattled this
island since a 7.6-magnitude quake struck in September, killing
2,400 people and destroying thousands of homes.
</P>
<P>
   Seismologists have said it is not unusual for aftershocks from a
major tremor to continue for a year or two.
</P>
<P>
   Located along the earthquake-prone Pacific Rim and crisscrossed
by 51 fault lines, Taiwan is hit by scores of earthquakes each
year, but few cause serious damage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
