<HEADLINE> Jury selection begins in trial of woman charged with manslaughter for supplying alcohol to minors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) - Jury selection is underway in the case of
a woman charged with manslaughter for supplying alcohol to minors
at her daughter's graduation party.
</P>
<P>
   Forty year-old Leslie Welsh of Avon 19 miles southwest of
Rochester is accused of supplying alcohol to minors at a graduation
party last year.
</P>
<P>
   A jury will decide whether Welsh can be held responsible for the
death of 20 year-old Joe Kingsbury, who died after drinking at the
party.
</P>
<P>
   Kingsbury was celebrating with friends on a night filled with
graduation parties. The celebration ended some time at the Welsh
home some time after 3 a.m. when he collapsed on a mattress in the
garage. Kingsbury never woke up; his blood alcohol level was four
times the legal limit.
</P>
<P>
   Felix Lapine, Welsh's attorney, said there might have been
negligence and carelessness involved, but not a criminal act.
</P>
<P>
   ''You don't send people to state prison for an accident,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Welsh has been charged with manslaughter, criminally negligent
homicide, and seven other counts of providing alcohol to minors.
Jury selection will continue Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
