<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 01:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jury undecided on Peeler sentence  </HEADLINE>
By DENISE LAVOIE
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) - A judge has asked a jury to continue
deliberating whether Russell Peeler Jr. should be executed for
ordering the murders of an 8-year-old witness and the boy's mother,
despite word that the panel was deadlocked.
</P>
<P>
   The jury had sent Judge G. Sarsfield Ford flurry of notes
Monday, saying they could not come to an agreement on either of the
two capital felony charges against Peeler, who faces either life in
prison or execution.
</P>
<P>
   One of the counts refers to Peeler's conviction on killing
8-year-old Leroy ''B.J.'' Brown Jr., who was scheduled to testify
against Peeler in an earlier murder case. The second count refers
to Peeler's conviction of killing two people at the same time -
B.J. and his mother, Karen Clarke. Mother and son were gunned down
in their Bridgeport home on Jan. 7, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say Peeler had his brother, Adrian, shoot the mother
and son to keep the boy from testifying. Adrian will tried later.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors told the judge they were confused by the wording of the
jury verdict form, which asked them to weigh mitigating factors
presented by Peeler's defense lawyers and aggravating factors
presented by prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   The judge said he would have a supplemental verdict form
submitted to them Tuesday so they can take a final vote.
</P>
<P>
   In its first note, the jury told the judge they could not agree
on whether mitigating factors outweighed aggravating factors on the
first capital felony count, the killing of B.J.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are divided and there is no room for movement on either
side,'' the jury's note said.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, the judge said he would be inclined to sentence
Peeler to life in prison, based on the jury's apparent deadlock.
</P>
<P>
   Bridgeport State's Attorney Jonathan Benedict, however, told the
judge he thought the law provided for the judge to instead declare
a mistrial and allows the state to then hold a new death penalty
hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, the jury sent the judge another note saying
they could not agree on whether the state had proven a single
aggravating factor on the second capital felony count -the killing
of B.J. and his mother at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are deadlocked and there will be no movement whatsoever,''
the note read.
</P>
<P>
   The judge then read the jury an amended version of the so-called
''Chip Smith'' instruction aimed at preventing a hung jury by
urging jurors to reach an agreement. Normally, the Chip Smith
charge instructs jurors in the minority to consider the majority
position, an instruction that some lawyers consider coeercive. But
Judge Ford simply asked each juror to consider the opinions of the
other jurors.
</P>
<P>
   When the jury came back again with a note saying they still
could not agree and were confused by the jury form, the judge sent
them home for the day and told them to return Tuesday, when they
will be given an amended form.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors had argued that Peeler committed the crimes in an
especially cruel, heinous or depraved manner, knowing that the
mother and son would experience psychological torture when they
were shot in front of each other.
</P>
<P>
   Other aggravating factors cited by the state were payments
Peeler made to co-conspirators in the murder plot: a handful of
crack cocaine to Lee and a bag full of cash to the alleged getaway
driver.
</P>
<P>
   For mitigating factors, Peeler's defense lawyers argued that
Peeler's participation in the crime was limited because he did not
actually pull the trigger. They also presented family members who
said Peeler was deeply affected by the death of his mother to
cancer when he was 21.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-20-00 0102 </TRAILER>
