<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 01:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Town Stunned by H.S. Hazing Arrests  </HEADLINE>
By MICHELLE RUSHLO
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINSLOW, Ariz. (AP) -- The pecking order on the Winslow High
School basketball team's bus was obvious -- freshmen in front, next
to the coach, junior varsity in the middle, varsity in back.
</P>
<P>
   But sometimes, on road trips that could last more than an hour
between this rural town and schools one or two towns away, younger
players were called or dragged to the back of the school bus.
</P>
<P>
   There, witnesses say, some athletes held down the younger
students and covered their mouths before sticking fingers in their
rectums. Sometimes, the athletes threw blankets over the victims'
heads and allegedly used a pencil or green Dry Erase marker to
sodomize them.
</P>
<P>
   A parent's complaint in March set off a school investigation,
which was then handed over to local authorities.
</P>
<P>
   In April, two star athletes -- one of them a police detective's
son -- and another player were suspended for the alleged sexual
assault, stunning this town of 11,000 where most everyone knows one
another by name. And last month, eight athletes were charged with
either sexually assaulting or helping other students assault about
a dozen basketball and track athletes over several months. The
basketball coach has also been indicted, accused of knowing about
some of the abuse and failing to stop it.
</P>
<P>
   ''We decided it wasn't horseplay. It crossed the line into
criminal conduct,'' said Navajo County Attorney Melvin Bowers Jr.
</P>
<P>
   All the defendants have denied the allegations, in some cases
saying the incidents were pranks. However, Bowers said ''it was
more of a power and control or dominance thing.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, few statistics are available on high school hazing.
An Alfred University study of NCAA athletes last year found that 42
percent of those who said they were hazed in college had been hazed
in high school. Five percent reported being hazed in middle school,
''which set off alarms for us,'' said Norman Pollard, director of
counseling at the Alfred, N.Y., university.
</P>
<P>
   The same researchers have begun a study of high school hazing,
but no data is yet available, Pollard said. He did say, however,
that reported hazing cases probably represent a very small
percentage of what actually takes place.
</P>
<P>
   ''A lot of this type of behavior is done secretly,'' he said.
''It never comes out unless someone is courageous enough to say
something or there is some tragic consequence.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Winslow case, interview transcripts and summaries
compiled by sheriff's investigators depict a pattern of alleged
abuse in which some varsity basketball and track athletes targeted
younger athletes. Many attacks occurred in the back of the bus on
the way home from basketball games, witnesses and victims told
investigators. Others occurred in the locker room and even in the
school's high jump pit.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's sad. It's terrible. You think you're in a small town.
It's like, Wow. ... It's a shock,'' said Bob Hall, who runs a salon
in Winslow, immortalized by the Eagles in ''Take It Easy,'' a song
for which it erected a commemorative park.
</P>
<P>
   These days in Winslow, the paint on the downtown storefronts
fades and peels, as most traffic whizzes past along Interstate 40,
bypassing the old Route 66 town 180 miles northeast of Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Residents pack the stands at Winslow High games even if they
don't have school-age children. They say they are stunned about the
abuse allegations -- and they are increasingly defensive over the
scrutiny the case has brought Winslow, which lives off the
Burlington-Northern Santa Fe rail line, a state prison and
nostalgic tourists who want to cruise the famed Mother Road.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a good town to raise kids in,'' said George Stegmeier,
president of the Chamber of Commerce and a lifelong Winslow
resident. ''We're not the sleepy hollow we were in the 1950s, but
we try to handle our problems discreetly. We try to be
supportive.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Of the students charged, Stephen Garnett Jr., 18, and Martin
Woods, 19, face the most counts. Garnett, a former student body
president and a basketball standout with a scholarship to Northern
Arizona University, faces 11 counts of kidnapping and five counts
each of sexual assault and attempted sexual assault. Woods, who had
been living with Garnett's family, faces 10 counts of kidnapping,
four counts of sexual assault and five of attempted sexual assault.
</P>
<P>
   The others charged in the case were Garnett's brother, Shane
Garnett, 16; Timothy Lewis, 16; William Shoupe, 16; Jason Black,
16; Brian Marquez, 17; and Logan Payne, 15.
</P>
<P>
   All declined to comment on the case, either personally or
through their attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   But in a letter to the school's principal before his indictment,
Stephen Garnett Jr. wrote, ''I never in my imagination in any way,
shape or form thought that the horsing around that we were doing
was a 'gang attack' on somebody. There were no intentions on
hurting, damaging or humiliating anybody. It was just supposed to
be horsing around.''
</P>
<P>
   During an interview with investigators, Garnett's father,
Winslow police detective Stephen Garnett Sr., told authorities he
thought people were trying to destroy his son because they were
jealous of him. The elder Garnett did not return a call placed to
his office.
</P>
<P>
   Basketball coach Daniel Gonzales, 36, faces three counts of
child abuse. Gonzales, who has denied knowing anything improper was
going on, declined to comment when contacted by phone and hung up
when asked for his attorney's name.
</P>
<P>
   Calls to school and district officials were all referred to the
district's attorney, Dale Patton, who didn't return messages.
</P>
<P>
   Hank Nuwer, an author of three books on hazing, said cases of
forced sodomy or alleged sodomy in high school hazing are rare -- he
tracked 16 since 1983 -- but that more surface each year.
</P>
<P>
   ''The mentality in athletics, there's this myth that (hazing)
builds unity,'' Nuwer said. ''But in sodomy cases, we don't what
the long-term consequences are.''
</P>
<P>
   One immediate consequence for the athletes charged at Winslow
High could be a loss of their peers' respect.
</P>
<P>
   ''They were cool,'' said sophomore Melissa Kabinto, ''and now
they're gross.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-20-00 0129 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
