<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 01:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Laker Fans Turn Violent After Win  </HEADLINE>
By TOM HARRIGAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Thousands of people celebrating the Los
Angeles Lakers' first NBA championship in 12 years turned violent
Monday night when revelers set a police car on fire and destroyed
two other vehicles, including a TV news van. Four bonfires also
were set. No injuries were immediately reported.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 10,000 people had gathered outside Staples Center by the
end of the Lakers' 116-111 victory over the Indiana Pacers, with
nearly 20,000 more still inside.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd was mostly peaceful until about an hour after the game
when several fans began jumping on top of a limousine trying to
leave the area, then began smashing the windows of a sport utility
vehicle and a television news van parked outside the arena.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't known who was inside the limousine.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of men were striking the SUV and news van with boards and
broken tree limbs while others looted fire extinguishers and other
items from the van.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes before, nearly a dozen police officers on motorcycles
forced the crowd away as several limousines tried to exit the
arena. Groups of men charged one limo, then another, hurling
traffic cones and other debris as they passed.
</P>
<P>
   City fire spokesman Brian Humphrey said a woman inside the arena
bumped her head and a man dislocated his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   He said the small bonfires some revelers built were in the
middle of the street and did not pose any threat to people or
property.
</P>
<P>
   ''The fires were fueled mostly by paper, trash and T-shirts from
the opposing team,'' Humphrey said. ''They quickly extinguished
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Groups of men formed conga lines around the fires and danced in
a circle, while some occasionally broke free and leaped over the
flames.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
