<DOCNO> APW20000620.0028 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 01:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> LA's Shaq: The Big Champion  </HEADLINE>
By KEN PETERS
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The Big Champion.
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal, who once made the rather curious boast that he
had won a championship on every level but college and the pros,
can't make that claim any more.
</P>
<P>
   Capping a season in which he won the scoring title, MVP of the
All-Star game and the regular season, O'Neal finally won the Big
One, the NBA championship, and earned the Finals MVP honor in the
process.
</P>
<P>
   After eight seasons, he also shed the stigma of being one of the
game's most dominant players, but one who could not take a team to
the title.
</P>
<P>
   As confetti rained down on the Staples Center court Monday night
after Los Angeles' 116-111 victory over Indiana in Game 6, tears
rolled down his face as the 7-foot-1, 315-pound O'Neal hugged his
mother and his father.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've held the emotion for about 11 years now, three years of
college and eight years here; I wanted to win,'' he said. ''It (the
emotion) just came up.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaq was simply Shaq in Los Angeles' clinching victory over the
Pacers that gave the Lakers their first NBA title since Magic
Johnson and ''Showtime'' in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Pounding the ball into the basket over the Pacers' Rik Smits and
any other Indiana defender trying to stop him, O'Neal mixed in a
few of his soft-touch, turnaround jumpers from 10 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Playing all but one minute of the game, O'Neal finished with 41
points and 12 rebounds. Also typically for him, he went just
3-of-12 from the free throw line.
</P>
<P>
   ''This year, Shaq's been attacking and he's just been great for
us all year long,'' teammate Kobe Bryant said.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers' Reggie Miller said O'Neal's all-around game has
improved.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think a lot of it has to do with (coach) Phil Jackson coming
in and giving Shaq and the others confidence,'' Miller said. ''I
know Phil told everybody right at first that this was Shaq's team
and the ball goes through Shaq.''
</P>
<P>
   Lakers owner Jerry Buss said O'Neal was confident -- and
determined -- this season.
</P>
<P>
   ''He just feels like he is the best player and he set out to
prove it,'' Buss said. ''I think he did it to everyone's
satisfaction.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal gleefully gave himself many nicknames in the past,
including ''The Big Aristotle'' when he won the 1999-2000
regular-season MVP and quoted the philosopher: ''Excellence is not
a singular act, it's a habit.''
</P>
<P>
   Others nicknames he came up with: ''The Big Maravich'' after he
made nine free throws in a row against Portland in the playoffs;
''The Big Felon,'' after he made a game-saving steal against
Orlando; and ''The Big Cordially,'' because, he said, ''I'm nice.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal was the unanimous choice in the NBA Finals MVP voting. He
was just one short of getting all the votes in the regular-season
MVP balloting.
</P>
<P>
   He becomes only the third player in NBA history to win all three
MVP awards in the same year, joining Michael Jordan, who did it
twice, and Willis Reed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-20-00 0135 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000620.0029 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 01:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lakers' Supporting Cast Helps Shaq  </HEADLINE>
By BOB BAUM
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- As great as he is, Shaquille O'Neal cannot
win an NBA championship by himself. Almost, but not quite.
</P>
<P>
   On O'Neal's magnificent 41-point night of thunderous dunks and
off-balance bank shots in Los Angeles' clinching 116-111 victory
over Indiana, those ''other'' Lakers came through.
</P>
<P>
   With Kobe Bryant an erratic 8-for-27 from the field, O'Neal
needed help elsewhere. The Lakers took turns providing it.
</P>
<P>
   At the head of the supporting cast was Glen Rice, who may have
played his last game in Lakers gold.
</P>
<P>
   Rice, the one-time all-star who has made the triangle offense
look like the Bermuda Triangle by disappearing frequently, was
5-for-7, including 3-of-3 on 3-pointers, and scored 16 points.
</P>
<P>
   Rice, a free agent after this game who supported his wife when
she complained loudly and at length about his limited role in coach
Phil Jackson's system, missed 3 of 4 free throws through three
quarters. But he made the two biggest of his career with 1:16 to
play to put Los Angeles ahead 112-109.
</P>
<P>
   When Reggie Miller missed a 3-pointer with 15 seconds to go,
Rice grabbed the rebound.
</P>
<P>
   As it ended, Rice's smile lit up the night as he hugged a
tearful O'Neal. For once, Rice was very much a part of everything.
</P>
<P>
   In the champagne-drenched locker room, Rice held his son G'mitri
in one arm as he talked about whether he will be back next year.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've had to endure all the trade rumors, the ups and downs and
the struggles that I've had,'' Rice said. ''To win the NBA
championship, it's really all worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice said he wants to come back to the Lakers because he feels
they will win more championships. But when a reporter asked G'mitri
where he wanted his dad to play, the youngster thought for a moment
and said, ''Miami.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice's smile grew bigger. ''You've got to edit that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was Robert Horry, who won a championship with the
Houston Rockets. All eight of his points came in the fourth
quarter. He came off the bench to sink two 3-pointers as Los
Angeles outscored Indiana 20-8 to start the fourth and take a 99-92
lead. Rick Fox also had a 3-pointer in the run.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana clawed back to a 103-103 tie, but there was Horry
sinking a jumper to put the Lakers up for good. Ron Harper, who
brought his NBA title experience to the team this season, knocked a
pass away for a turnover that set up one of O'Neal's big baskets in
his fourth quarter of 13 points.
</P>
<P>
   A.C. Green, who was a bit player on this team but a member of
the last Laker team to win a championship in 1988, had a critical
baseline jumper and steal in the third quarter when Indiana seemed
poised to pull away.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Green, a devout Christian non-drinker, was on the run
in the locker room as Horry chased him with champagne.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've stayed dry through all my championships,'' he said, ''and
I want to keep my streak alive.''
</P>
<P>
   All the Lakers wore their championship hats and smoked big
cigars in the crowded locker room. Plastic covered their lockers to
keep the champagne off.
</P>
<P>
   In a room next door, Magic Johnson held court.
</P>
<P>
   ''The first one is always the toughest,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For Jackson, it was seven championships in nine years, but his
first without Michael Jordan. Only Red Auerbach coached a team to
more titles.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's always sweet,'' Jackson said. ''This is for you L.A. What
a way to start a millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   For much of the night, it looked like another Lakers
disappointment. Six times the team failed to close out a series
when it had a chance. Los Angeles had just lost by 33 in
Indianapolis in Game 5.
</P>
<P>
   But O'Neal's relentless effort eventually became contagious.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was very proud of our team and how they held on under a lot
of criticism, a lot of pressure,'' Jackson said. ''Their confidence
just kind of oozed out.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, who came to Los Angeles and inherited a team with
big-time talent but a reputation for underachieving, said he
stopped his players 15 minutes into their first practice. He said
doubted if they could play with the kind of energy he demanded.
</P>
<P>
   At the end, they met his demands.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm very proud of that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When it was over, the often-placid crowd stormed the court and
erupted in cheers. So did thousands who crowded the streets outside
the downtown Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   It was the seventh championship for the Lakers, but with O'Neal
and the 21-year-old Bryant, who clinched the victory with four
straight free throws, it probably won't be the last.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'd like to thank the real coach of the year, Phil Jackson,''
O'Neal told the crowd at center court after the trophy
presentation. ''And we're going to win one next year, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
