<BODY>
<HEADLINE> North Korea's Economy Growing  </HEADLINE>
By PAUL SHIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- North Korea's economy expanded 6.2
percent in 1999, the first growth in nine years and a rate that
officials said was sustainable.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Seoul's central Bank of Korea said this week's
easing of U.S. economic sanctions against Pyongyang and the
expected increase in South Korean investment would positively
affect the North's economy.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's reasonable to predict that the worst is over for the
North Korean economy,'' said Park Suk-sam, a senior Bank of Korea
analyst. ''We believe that plus economic growth will continue in
the North.''
</P>
<P>
   In its preliminary report, the South Korean bank said that the
North's economy turned around in 1999 for the first time since
1990, helped by growth in almost all sectors.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the turnaround, the size of North Korea's economy in
1999 still remained at 75 percent of that 10 years ago in 1989, it
said.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea does not release any economic statistics. South
Korean officials said they calculated the figures with data
collected from North Korea's trading partners and U.N. and other
international groups helping the communist country.
</P>
<P>
   Growth in the North's construction sector was strongest at 24.3
percent, farming at 9.2 percent and mining and manufacturing at 9.9
percent, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The fall of communism in the Soviet Union and Eastern Europe
deprived North Korea of its traditional barter trading partners and
aid providers. That caused the North's economy to shrink 3.7
percent in 1990 and from between 1.1 percent to 6.3 percent through
1998, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The report estimated the North's 1999 gross national product at
$15.8 billion, less than 4 percent that of South Korea. The North's
per capita income of $714 was about 8 percent that of its southern
neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea's 1999 trade totaled $1.48 billion, compared with
$263.4 billion in South Korea, it said.
</P>
<P>
   Food and energy shortages were blamed for the North's economic
difficulty, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Famine hit North Korea in the early 1990s, forcing the reclusive
communist country to appeal for outside aid in 1995 to feed its 22
million people.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, food production increased with foreign fertilizer aid,
bank officials said. South Korea is currently shipping 200,000 tons
of free fertilizer to the North.
</P>
<P>
   Lifting a half-century economic embargo, the United States on
Monday allowed trade with North Korea in nonmilitary goods and
opened air travel and shipping routes between the two countries.
Washington also eased restrictions on investment by U.S. companies.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials said the action was heavy in symbolism and would
not spur large trade with North Korea in the immediate future,
given that the communist country is just trying to come out of long
and extreme isolation.
</P>
<P>
   Seoul officials said North Korea can expect quicker benefit from
economic aid and investment from South Korea, following a
successful inter-Korea summit last week.
</P>
<P>
   In a deal signed during the first-ever summit, South Korea
promised to help rebuild the North's shattered economy.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of footwear and other labor-intensive South Korean
companies hope to relocate their plants to North Korea where labor
costs are low.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-20-00 0200 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000620.0040 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 02:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New York's corporations close ranks with GE on PCBs  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - New York's corporate community closed ranks
Monday around General Electric Co. in its opposition to dredging
PCB-contaminated sediments from the Hudson River.
</P>
<P>
   The state's Business Council, the most powerful business
lobbying group in New York, argued that ''vengefulness'' on the
part of GE's critics must not be allowed to guide policy at the
federal Environmental Protection Agency.
</P>
<P>
   ''To them (GE critics), big corporations like GE are evil
polluters, who must be punished,'' Business Council President
Daniel Walsh said in a letter to EPA Administrator Carol Browner.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh added, ''We do not believe that EPA will make a decision
based on vengefulness. We believe that EPA will make the decision
that is driven by sound science, and by the facts at hand - and
reject dredging.''
</P>
<P>
   The EPA plans to announce in December its decision on how best
to deal with PCB ''hot spots'' in the Hudson River north of Albany.
GE discharged the chemicals legally into the Hudson until 1977,
when the substance was banned by the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   GE, with its own scientific studies and a television public
relations campaign, is trying to convince the EPA that dredging is
not the best solution to Hudson River PCBs. The company says the
river is getting cleaner, and that PCBs are not a cancer-causing
agent in humans, despite Browner's statements that it probably is.
</P>
<P>
   Dredging for contaminated sediments would only stir up chemicals
and cause them to be distributed more widely in the river, GE
argues.
</P>
<P>
   ''It seems clear that a dredging operation big enough to remove
the PCBs under the riverbed would take 10 years or more,'' Walsh
told Browner. ''For all that time, the scenic beauty, water quality
and recreational use of a 40-mile stretch along the upper river
would be severely disrupted.''
</P>
<P>
   General Electric is a member of the Business Council. The head
of one of its divisions, Robert Nardelli of GE Power Systems, sits
on the council's board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   The Business Council's letter is in keeping with the message of
GE's ad campaign, said Jeff Jones of the Albany-based Environmental
Advocates.
</P>
<P>
   ''The sedimentation strategy - just leaving the PCBs in the
river - is not a long-term strategy because there are any number of
natural occurrences that could take place over time to stir them up
- flood, droughts, ice floes, tornadoes,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   He said Walsh is overstating the extent of the dredging the EPA
may order. It is likely any dredging would be limited to the PCB
''hot spots'' where the most-contaminated sediments have
accumulated, Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Rychlenski, a spokeswoman for the EPA, disputed Walsh's
estimate that it would take a decade to dredge the river.
</P>
<P>
   ''We do not know what our decision is going to be,'' she said.
''However, we certainly do not anticipate that a remedy, should we
go to a remedy would take 10 years or shut down the river for 10
years.''
</P>
<P>
   She said scientists who have looked at the river for the EPA
agreed that contaminated sediments are not being covered over at
the rate GE says they are and that, in some cases, PCBs are
continuing to migrate southward in the river.
</P>
<P>
   PCBs, or polychlorinated biphenyls, were used as insulating
material in transformers and other electrical equipment.
</P>
<P>
   They have been linked to cancer in laboratory animals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-20-00 0209 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000620.0041 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 02:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Homesteader shuns amenities to live, extol the mountain life  </HEADLINE>
By SUZANNE SEAY
Glens Falls Post-Star
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHNSBURG, N.Y. (AP) - It's been 12 years now, and Susan M. Dean
is seriously considering getting a telephone.
</P>
<P>
   She's pretty sure a cellular phone would work at her home, which
sits on top of an unnamed Adirondack mountain in this
200-square-mile town, far from pavement and utilities.
</P>
<P>
   Her two oldest children are out of the house, and she thinks a
phone would allow her 14-year-old to keep in closer touch with
friends. It can get lonely on a mountaintop.
</P>
<P>
   But Dean wouldn't have it any other way.
</P>
<P>
   She and her husband, James, spent four years building their
substantial but simple home. They overcame the daunting task of
hauling materials up the mountainside by employing whichever of
their ancient cars, trucks and tractors was working at the time.
</P>
<P>
   The outside of the home is clad in rough-edged boards.
Old-timers call it hogpen siding, but now it's generally called
Adirondack wavy coat. Their water is pumped to a storage tank in a
second-floor closet by a gasoline-powered pump.
</P>
<P>
   As with most people, doing dishes is a chore Dean doesn't
relish. But the chore at her home includes the additional task of
heating up water on the propane stove. The same procedure is
required for a bath, but it's amazing how few pots of boiling water
it takes to heat up a tubful, she said.
</P>
<P>
   There are six propane lantern lights, mounted on walls
throughout the house, that provide plenty of light, she said. The
Deans also made sure when they built the house that the numerous
windows let in plenty of sunlight during the day.
</P>
<P>
   Their flat spot on the mountain offers sweeping views that can
be enjoyed almost in a full circle -- particularly in winter, when
the trees are bare.
</P>
<P>
   Dean chose this remote location because she wanted to be
surrounded by natural beauty on the outside and wanted her inner
life to reflect that peacefulness.
</P>
<P>
   She says it's working.
</P>
<P>
   The family bought their land in 1984, and it took four years to
build their home. They moved in 1988 and haven't regretted a
moment, she said. It's sometimes a pain having to run into town to
do laundry and make phone calls, she said, and she's left out of
conversations that involve the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   But Dean also doesn't participate in conversations when people
are complaining about the stress in their lives, the hectic pace,
the never-ending demands on their time.
</P>
<P>
   Dean says her lifestyle has pushed her stress level so far down
that it almost can't be felt.
</P>
<P>
   She's also found that being so isolated has actually made her
feel more sociable.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not surrounded by it all the time, and I can choose who I
want to be involved with,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Dean grew up in Amsterdam, N.Y., an old industrial city on the
Mohawk River 25 miles northwest of Albany.
</P>
<P>
   She'd never even been camping until she went to college. And she
never considered living ''off the grid'' until she met her husband
James.
</P>
<P>
   But he has been a woodsman at heart his whole life, she said. He
was inspired in junior high by a book he read by a woman who moved
to the backwoods of Maine.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Dean said she concentrated on raising good children,
which she believes she's accomplished to the best of her ability.
</P>
<P>
   James provides the family's modest income by working on
construction projects during the building season.
</P>
<P>
   ''No matter how much money you have, there could always be a
little more,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Dean said her only complaint is not being able to afford better
and more reliable vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   In the past few years, as her children became independent, Dean
turned to writing.
</P>
<P>
   ''The whole thing of my life is just a peace message, I guess,''
she said. ''And I wanted to put that out. I had to get peace myself
first; then I could write about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Her first book, printed in 1996, is ''Unplugged in the
Adirondacks,'' which she subtitled ''Book One of a Violet
Tapestry.'' She decided to make it the first part of a trilogy to
force herself to keep producing, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The second book, out two years later, is ''Plugged in to the
Mountain Sun.''
</P>
<P>
   After paying for the printing herself, she traveled in widening
circles to shops in the Adirondacks to distribute the books. Even
then, she said she only tried to sell them at stores where she got
''good vibes,'' because she didn't want to create stress with books
promoting personal peace.
</P>
<P>
   The books have sold fairly well and have paid for themselves,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   In the final book of the trilogy, Dean hopes to includes color
pictures of some of her artwork, such as drawings of traditional
quilt patterns. She also wants to include some of the more
interesting letters she's gotten from readers all over the country,
which have been a motivation to keep writing, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Serious writing, however, has been put on hold for the summer
while Dean leads a local effort to plan a series of events
celebrating women and Adirondack traditions. The series will
conclude in October with a major festival called Adirondack Women
2000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-20-00 0210 </TRAILER>
