<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 02:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Legislators reach agreement on pesticide notification  </HEADLINE>
By ANNY KUO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - The state Senate and Assembly on Monday
reached agreement to give counties and New York City the option of
governing how neighbors are to be notified when pesticides are in
use.
</P>
<P>
   In areas which opt to get into the program, neighbors must
receive two-day advance notice of commercial application of
pesticides. All properties within 150 feet of the application site
must be notified, the agreed-to bill stipulates.
</P>
<P>
   Homeowners who apply pesticides on their lawns would not have to
notify neighboring properties in advance, but must post warning
flags when pesticide application is complete.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the measure mandates that schools statewide give
parents the choice of getting 48-hour advance notice of impending
pesticide applications. Schools would also need to send out three
notices a year to parents, listing dates, locations and products
used in such applications.
</P>
<P>
   The two-day prior notification requirement would also apply to
daycare facilities, which must provide postings indicating prior
notice.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of schools and daycare centers, the measure would
apply to both indoor and outdoor application of pesticides.
</P>
<P>
   The state Assembly has passed a bill mandating municipalities
statewide adhere to notification laws, but that version has not
made it through the Senate. Earlier this month, the Senate passed a
measure allowing local governments to ''opt-in'' to a neighbor
notification program, but it did not include schools and daycare
facilities.
</P>
<P>
   State Assemblyman Thomas DiNapoli said his chamber would have
preferred a statewide mandate, but added that it was ''certainly
better to have opt-in than not having a bill at all.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It would be nice to have everyone starting on the same time,
but I think citizens would put pressure on counties that don't
opt-in immediately,'' the Nassau County Democrat said.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate's chief sponsor of the bill Carl Marcellino, R-
Nassau County, said he favored giving municipalities the choice
because some rural counties had said pesticide notification wasn't
necessary. Nevertheless, Marcellino was optimistic that most
counties would join in.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would not be surprised if well over 90 percent of the
counties would opt in immediately,'' he said. ''This bill is now
quite comprehensive ... to include both schools and daycare.''
</P>
<P>
   Environmental advocates, who had also pushed for a statewide
mandate, applauded the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Haight of the New York Public Interest Research Group,
said if the bill is passed, it would be the first of its kind in
the country.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a good first step even though we're disappointed about
the opt-in,'' Haight said. ''We're going to work in every county in
the state to make sure that everyone will opt in.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Audrey Thier, pesticide project director of Environmental
Advocates: ''This is a giant step forward. We consider this a
breakthrough.''
</P>
<P>
   Properties using integrated pest management techniques -
alternative pest management techniques that require little or no
pesticides - would not have to follow notification requirements.
Granular pesticides are also exempt from the advance notification
mandate because they are applied directly are don't drift,
lawmakers said.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement was announced at a news conference in Mineola on
Long Island Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Legislators are expected to vote on the measure when they return
to Albany Thursday to resolve unfinished businesses in their
regular 2000 session.
</P>
<P>
   Michael McKeon, a spokesman for Gov. George Pataki, said:
''We're encouraged that there seems to be progress made but we need
to see the final language'' before deciding if the governor would
sign the bill.
</P>
<P>
   If enacted, the bill would go into effect March 1, 2001.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
