<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 a.m EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Tuesday, June 20, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Taiwan Leader Offers Summit With China
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- President Chen Shui-bian offered Tuesday to hold
Taiwan's first-ever summit with China, saying he believed the two leaders could
''create history'' like their Korean counterparts. At his first news conference
since taking office one month ago, Chen said he hopes to shake hands with
President Jiang Zemin of China and to seek reconciliation during a summit held
in any location and under any format that Jiang chooses. China has long
considered Taiwan a renegade state and demanded that it be rejoined to the
Chinese mainland.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
North Korea's Economy Growing
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- North Korea's economy expanded 6.2 percent in
1999, the first growth in nine years and a rate that officials said was
sustainable. Officials at Seoul's central Bank of Korea said this week's easing
of U.S. economic sanctions against Pyongyang and the expected increase in South
Korean investment would positively affect the North's economy. In its
preliminary report, the South Korean bank said that the North's economy turned
around in 1999 for the first time since 1990, helped by growth in almost all
sectors.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Lakers Beat Pacers 116-111, Win NBA Championship
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- In an exciting fourth quarter that ended Larry Bird's
coaching career, Shaquille O'Neal and Kobe Bryant led the Lakers to a 116-111
victory in Game 6 of the NBA Finals for the franchise's first title since 1988.
O'Neal scored 41 points, marking the third time he scored 40 or more in this
series, and Bryant had 26 including four free throws that clinched it in the
final 13 seconds.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Report Criticizes Child Farmworking
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Hundreds of thousands of children are laboring under
dangerous conditions in U.S. agriculture, Human Rights Watch charged in a report
issued Tuesday. The report, ''Fingers to the Bone: United States Failure to
Protect Child Farmworkers,'' charges that many young people ages 13 to 16 work
70 to 80 hours a week and risk pesticide poisoning, heat illness, injuries and
lifelong disabilities. The report said these abuses are possible because the
laws governing child labor in agriculture are much less stringent than those for
other types of work.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
114 Reported Killed in Jakarta Violence
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- Armed with homemade weapons, Christians and
Muslims battled on a remote eastern Indonesian island and 114 people were
killed, the official Antara news agency reported. The fighting broke out Monday
in the village of Duma, on Halmahera island about 1,600 miles northeast of
Jakarta, leaving at least 70 people wounded, the report said. The clash lasted
for about one hour. Antara said the dead were killed with homemade guns and
bombs as well as bows and arrows.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
House Votes To Bar Tobacco Suit Aid
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House voted Monday to bar the Justice Department from
accepting funds from another agency to help pay for the federal lawsuit against
the tobacco industry, even as Attorney General Janet Reno warned that such steps
would force her to drop the multibillion-dollar litigation. By a 207-197 vote,
the House stood behind language in a spending bill that would force the
Department of Veterans Affairs to abandon its plans to give the Justice
Department $4 million to help it pay for the huge lawsuit. The legal action
seeks to recover billions spent by Medicare and other federal programs to treat
illnesses caused by smoking.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Accusations Fly Over Fuel Costs
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Few left a congressional panel with much hope for a
resolution as to why drivers are paying more than $2 a gallon for gas in cities
such as Chicago and Milwaukee. Oil and ethanol industry executives blamed one
another for rising prices, with one oil industry spokesman blaming higher local
taxes, noting that Chicagoans are paying more than 50 cents in total taxes per
gallon.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gore Questions Oil Company Profits
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Toughening his stand on high gas prices, Vice President Al
Gore voiced suspicion Monday over oil companies' huge profits and called for an
investigation into collusion, antitrust violations and price gouging. Gore said
he just learned that the ''big oil companies'' saw a steep increase in profits
for the first quarter of the year. ''Now you put two and two together and look
at the huge price increases that they say they can't explain and look at the 500
percent increase in profits and look at the way they've been getting bigger,''
Gore told CNN.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Rise
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks rose Tuesday following an overnight rally on Wall
Street. The Nikkei gained 301.35 points, to 16,892.70 at the end of the morning
session.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by VINCENT K. WILLIS
