<HEADLINE> Lakers Fans Turn Violent After Win  </HEADLINE>
By TOM HARRIGAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The celebration of the Los Angeles Lakers'
first championship in 12 years turned violent Monday night as
revelers burned two police cars and destroyed at least two other
vehicles, including a TV news van.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 10,000 people had gathered around the Staples Center by
the time the game ended in a 116-111 Lakers' victory over the
Indiana Pacers, with nearly 20,000 more still inside. As violence
erupted outside the arena, fans were kept inside as a precaution.
</P>
<P>
   No injuries were immediately reported in the melee outside.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers also remained inside the arena 90 minutes after the
game, as authorities barred their bus from leaving. On the
sidewalks outside, police wielding batons cleared away fans and
guarded firefighters dousing a flaming police car.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd was mostly peaceful until nearly an hour after the
game when fans began throwing debris at limousines. The crowd then
smashed the windows on a white sport utility vehicle and the
television news van.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of men used boards and tree limbs to strike the vehicles,
while others looted fire extinguishers and other items from the
van.
</P>
<P>
   Lines of baton-carrying police, on foot and on horseback, moved
through the area in an effort to disperse the crowd. Thousands of
fans began running from the area, jamming downtown streets with
traffic and pedestrians.
</P>
<P>
   Several bonfires also were set in the area, including one at an
intersection two blocks from the arena that backed up traffic
before it was extinguished.
</P>
<P>
   City fire spokesman Brian Humphrey said the fires did not pose
any threat to people or property.
</P>
<P>
   ''The fires were fueled mostly by paper, trash and T-shirts from
the opposing team,'' Humphrey said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
