<DOCNO> APW20000620.0047 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 02:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Seeks More Medicare Spending  </HEADLINE>
By ALICE ANN LOVE
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Hospitals and other health care providers
would get $21 billion more from Medicare over the next five years,
under a proposal President Clinton is planning to send to Congress
soon.
</P>
<P>
   The initiative is likely to borrow from a range of legislation
that has been introduced by lawmakers from both political parties,
who have come under increasing pressure from hometown caregivers.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore also is calling for a boost in Medicare
payments as part of his presidential campaign platform.
</P>
<P>
   ''This has a tremendous level of support on a bipartisan
basis,'' said Joel Johnson, a senior adviser to the president.
</P>
<P>
   The request is expected to be among several items on a wish-list
the Clinton administration is expected to send Capitol Hill later
this month, along with new estimates that government surpluses
accumulating during the next decade will be more than twice as
large as previously predicted.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've been analyzing the effects of the balanced budget act
and a lot of other things that are happening, and our priority is
to ensure that there is high quality access to care for Medicare
beneficiaries,'' said Medicare Administrator Nancy-Ann DeParle.
</P>
<P>
   Hospitals, home health care agencies and nursing homes would
likely get much of the money under the administration proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Medicare legislation being developed by House
Republicans would give around $2 billion to HMOs, many of which
have pulled out of Medicare in recent years complaining payments
don't keep up with inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Curbs on fees from Medicare, the nation's health insurance
program for the elderly and disabled, were part of 1997 legislation
to balance the federal budget.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when private health plans have been imposing lower
prices as well, health care providers say Medicare is squeezing
them too tight. Many hospitals say they have cut back community
service work, for example, such as transportation programs or
satellite clinics.
</P>
<P>
   Overall Medicare spending declined for the first time in the
program's 35-year history in 1999, by about 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, Congress voted to restore $16 billion to health care
providers, but there is broad agreement that was not enough.
</P>
<P>
   The administration is expected to upgrade its prediction for
federal budget surpluses to up to $1.9 trillion over the next 10
years, well above past estimates of $746 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-20-00 0234 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000620.0048 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 02:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senator Helps Staffer Without Legs  </HEADLINE>
By JEFFREY McMURRAY
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Modern medicine and a pair of pants conceal
Daniel Johnson's life-altering injuries, but his optimism and the
example of Sen. Max Cleland help him live with them.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, an athletic-looking 24-year-old who was a junior
officer in the Navy, lost both legs below the knees and nearly died
last year while rescuing a sailor.
</P>
<P>
   Cleland, a Georgia Democrat who lost both legs and much of his
right arm in a grenade blast during the Vietnam War, heard about
Johnson's heroism and offered him a job on his defense policy team.
Johnson started work about a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''However bad you feel today, you're still alive, and that's a
good thing,'' Cleland said. ''That's a pretty sobering thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was injured last August. An ensign, he was standing
watch aboard the amphibious command ship USS Blue Ridge off Pusan,
South Korea, when seaman Steve Wright became tangled in a tugboat
line and was pulled across the deck. Johnson rushed to help and was
caught in the line, too. Wright, from Pine Bluff, Ark., lost a leg
and three fingers.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who received the Navy and Marine Corps Medal for his
heroism, said he quickly realized there were two ways to approach
his injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ''I could either be positive about it and try to go through it
quickly, or go negative and the route of self-pity,'' said Johnson,
from Hickory, N.C. ''To me, it's a lot easier to look at what
options I do have rather than what ones I don't.''
</P>
<P>
   To lift his spirits, someone gave Johnson an article about
Cleland's experience in Vietnam. Days later, he got a call from the
senator, who had read an article about Johnson. They quickly
developed a friendship, and Cleland asked Johnson if he would like
to work in his office.
</P>
<P>
   Cleland, who formerly headed the Department of Veterans Affairs,
said Johnson illustrates the kind of commitment military personnel
exhibit every day.
</P>
<P>
   ''While others were standing around, Daniel in effect went to
the fray, and it cost him,'' Cleland said. ''That's one of the
things about military work: It costs time, energy, blood, sweat and
toil, and sometimes life and limb.''
</P>
<P>
   Undergoing treatment at Washington's Walter Reed Hospital,
Johnson joined an informal network of amputees who helped each
other cope with the injuries. They went on outings, and now Johnson
sometimes calls other amputees to chat.
</P>
<P>
   Among the others was Dean Johnson, who was helping a motorist
start a car when a tractor-trailer hit him. Both legs had to be
amputated.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everybody said our cases were similar,'' said Dean Johnson,
who isn't related to Daniel. ''My spirits were always kind of high,
but it showed me what I could aspire for. Daniel and the senator
lead normal lives, so I guess I can, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleland marvels at Johnson's prostheses, which allow him to ski,
play softball and participate in other activities that were
unthinkable for amputees not too long ago.
</P>
<P>
   Cleland's legs were blown off above the knees in 1968, and he
needed to use a heavy waist harness and crutch to walk with
prosthetic limbs. He eventually decided a wheelchair was easier and
has been using it ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was more fortunate. His legs were amputated below the
knee.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you've gotta be a leg amputee, that's the way to do it,''
Cleland said. ''What Daniel has that I don't is that when he stands
up, he has balance.''
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 23, Johnson will celebrate his first ''Alive Day'' -- the
anniversary of the day he almost died. Cleland, who celebrates his
birthday the next day, will be visiting troops in South Korea, but
has promised to call Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://cleland.senate.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
