<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 02:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FDR's Arabian treasures from historic meeting displayed  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HYDE PARK, N.Y. (AP) - A jeweled sword, a dagger, and silk
clothing embroidered in gold are among the treasures from a
historic meeting now displayed publicly for the first time in 55
years.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit of Saudi Arabian gifts is displayed through Oct. 31
at the Franklin D. Roosevelt Presidential Library and Museum in
Hyde Park, 67 miles north of New York City.
</P>
<P>
   The priceless presents were given to President Roosevelt by King
Abdulaziz Al-Saud of Saudi Arabia during their meeting aboard the
USS Quincy on Feb. 14, 1945. The leaders met to discuss the major
political issues that would affect their countries in the
approaching post-war era.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting was a key foundation to the countries' strong
relationship that survives today.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition was conceived by officials of the U.S. Embassy in
Riyadh last year as part of the centennial celebration of Saudi
Arabia.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is a moving reminder of the role of their leadership,''
said Anna Roosevelt, president of the Franklin and Eleanor
Roosevelt Institute and granddaughter of the president.
</P>
<P>
   A ceremony to open the exhibit on Sunday included former crewmen
of the USS Quincy.
</P>
</TEXT>
