<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 09:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> At the Movies: 'Chicken Run'  </HEADLINE>
By MALCOLM RITTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   Imagine a tale of danger, courage, resourcefulness, faith,
redemption and thrilling escape from certain death.
</P>
<P>
   Now imagine it's about chickens.
</P>
<P>
   That's the scoop with ''Chicken Run,'' a delightful story told
with ingenious clay animation by the makers of the popular Wallace
&AMP; Gromit shorts.
</P>
<P>
   The movie makes plenty of fun of the contrast between its
dramatic themes and the largely hapless hens that act them out. But
before long, you begin to know and like these chickens. You start
rooting for them to succeed -- even as you enjoy the essentially
loony scenes they create.
</P>
<P>
   The story is set in England at Tweedy's Egg Farm, which looks
like a World War II-style POW camp for fowl. The chickens line up
for roll call each morning, and any hen whose egg production is
failing is plucked up and decapitated by the evil Mrs. Tweedy
(voiced by Miranda Richardson).
</P>
<P>
   It gets even grimmer when Mrs. Tweedy, tired of the farm's tiny
profits, decides to go into another business. She buys a huge
machine that swallows chickens and spits out pies. Now even good
egg-laying won't save a hen from death.
</P>
<P>
   The hens have a ringleader, Ginger (voiced by Julia Sawalha,
best known as Saffron in the BBC series ''Absolutely Fabulous.'')
Her escape plans fail time after time. But she finds hope when an
American rooster named Rocky (voiced by Mel Gibson) quite literally
lands in the farmyard one day. Teach us to fly out of here, she
begs.
</P>
<P>
   He's a cocky ''lone free ranger'' who enjoys the attention of
all these hens. He agrees to Ginger's request, without admitting
that he flies only when shot out of a cannon in a circus act.
</P>
<P>
   His flight training program is doomed, of course, though it's
plenty of fun to watch. In the end, it is Ginger who conceives of
her grandest, most preposterous escape plan yet. It works, but with
plenty of tension to the very end. Her final confrontation with
Mrs. Tweedy is riveting.
</P>
<P>
   ''Chicken Run,'' from DreamWorks Pictures, is rated G. It
includes cartoonish violence, and Mrs. Tweedy quite clearly kills
one hen offscreen. The 90-minute film is produced by Peter Lord,
David Sproxton and Nick Park, and directed by Lord and Park.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Motion Picture Association of America rating definitions:
</P>
<P>
   G -- General audiences. All ages admitted.
</P>
<P>
   PG -- Parental guidance suggested. Some material may not be
suitable for children.
</P>
<P>
   PG-13 -- Special parental guidance strongly suggested for
children under 13. Some material may be inappropriate for young
children.
</P>
<P>
   R -- Restricted. Under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult
guardian.
</P>
<P>
   NC-17 -- No one under 17 admitted.
</P>
</TEXT>
