<HEADLINE> U.N.: Traces Left of Cattle Disease  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME (AP) -- The United Nations expressed confidence Tuesday that
one of the world's deadliest cattle diseases can be eradicated in
10 years.
</P>
<P>
   The last traces of the rinderpest virus, which has destroyed
entire populations of cattle and buffalo, were detected in
southeastern Sudan, southern Somalia, Yemen, Pakistan and Iraq, the
Rome-based Food and Agriculture Organization reported.
</P>
<P>
   After cleaning up the remaining pockets of infection, the
agency's 10-year program includes ending the vaccination worldwide
by the year 2002 -- a move expected to save money and provide
evidence that the virus has been eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   A five-year verification process is scheduled to start in 2003,
experts said.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years rinderpest has caused widespread famine in
regions that depend on cattle for meat and milk products. In
Nigeria in the early 1980s, it caused losses estimated at $2
billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
