<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 10:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Resurrection: Rare Hispanic Drama  </HEADLINE>
By LYNN ELBER
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Part of the action in ''Resurrection Blvd.''
takes place in the boxing ring, but the real fight was getting the
drama on television.
</P>
<P>
   The new Showtime series about a close-knit Mexican-American
family runs counter to TV's tired habit of either snubbing Hispanic
characters or relegating them to supporting roles as hoodlums or
maids.
</P>
<P>
   It's about time, say the cast and creator of ''Resurrection
Blvd.,'' which debuts 10 p.m. EDT Monday (June 26) on the cable
channel.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's bittersweet that we're in the year 2000 and this is what
we're talking about for the first time,'' said series star Michael
DeLorenzo (''New York Undercover''). ''It doesn't make me spring
with joy because you think, 'Why has it taken so long for something
very simple, a family drama portraying Latinos?'''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't for lack of effort, said series creator and executive
producer Dennis E. Leoni. He had an established TV track record,
writing for series including ''Raven'' and ''The Commish,'' when he
first pitched a Hispanic family series to Hollywood studios.
</P>
<P>
   ''I had written a spec (speculative) pilot, 'La Reforma,' sort
of my 'Wonder Years,''' he said. The response: ''There's no way
you're going to get it done with an all-Latino cast,'' Leoni
recalled. ''I got laughed at.''
</P>
<P>
   Some five years later, he heard Showtime was interested in
developing Hispanic programming. His original idea was ''a soft,
sweet story,'' not quite right for the channel, which favors edgier
fare, but Showtime encouraged him to try a different approach.
</P>
<P>
   When Leoni flipped on the channel one night and saw boxers
slugging it out, the idea of combining family drama with the
intensity of competition in the ring ''just sort of clicked,'' he
said. Showtime has ordered a full season, 22 episodes.
</P>
<P>
   ''Resurrection Blvd.'' focuses on the Santiago family of East
Los Angeles, including patriarch and widower Roberto (Tony Plana),
his sister-in-law Bibi (Elizabeth Pena) and Roberto's five
children, including Carlos (DeLorenzo) and Miguel (Maurico
Mendoza).
</P>
<P>
   Boxing is part of the family's heritage, although the Santiago
hope of fielding a champion has been repeatedly dashed. Now it is
Carlos' turn for a shot at glory with the help of his driven
father, a Vietnam War veteran forced to settle for less in his own
life.
</P>
<P>
   The cast includes such proven standouts as Plana, whose film
credits include ''JFK,'' ''Salvador'' and ''Primal Fear,'' and Pena
(''Lone Star,'' ''Rush Hour''). The series also represents a chance
for newcomers like Nicholas Gonzalez, who makes his TV series debut
as the youngest Santiago son, Alex, a pre-med student at UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   Behind-the-camera roles are largely filled by Hispanics,
including writers, directors, costume designers and crew members.
</P>
<P>
   There was no shortage of actors eager to be part of the landmark
series, said casting director Bob Morones, a 28-year industry
veteran. Some even left photos and resumes on the windshield of
Morones' car.
</P>
<P>
   In the series' production office on the Paramount lot, he points
to the thousands of actors' ''head shots'' filling shelf after
shelf.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now we have a talent pool,'' he said. ''Before, we were
scraping corners, trying to find talent. But in the last five years
there's been a major influx of (Latino) actors coming out of
universities and acting schools in the United States and South
America.''
</P>
<P>
   Their dreams are fueled, he said, by the success of music stars
like Gloria Estefan, Ricky Martin and the late Selena, and
actresses like Jennifer Lopez, Morones said.
</P>
<P>
   But the increasing prominence of Hispanic artists has not
translated into changes in television, especially at the broadcast
networks. The one Hispanic pilot under consideration for the fall
season, ''American Family,'' was rejected by CBS.
</P>
<P>
   Very few series about Hispanics have ever made it to air or
gained longevity. ''A.K.A. Pablo,'' about a young Hispanic comedian
and his extended family, ran briefly in 1984. ''Trial and Error,''
a comedy about two buddies from the East Los Angeles barrio, was a
blip on the screen in March 1988. Most successful was NBC's ''Chico
and the Man,'' which ran four seasons.
</P>
<P>
   (Cable TV is proving more responsive: Among upcoming series are
Nickelodeon's ''The Brothers Garcia,'' about a Mexican-American
family in San Antonio, ''Taina,'' focusing on a Hispanic girl in
New York, and an animated series with a Hispanic lead figure.)
</P>
<P>
   But there's no broadcast bandwagon for Latino shows, said Leoni:
''Hopefully, 'Resurrection Blvd.' will get the car rolling.''
</P>
<P>
   Key to its success will be proving that the series has broad
appeal -- to the diverse Hispanic American community, which includes
those of Puerto Rican, Cuban and Mexican descent, and to
non-Hispanics, Leoni said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm really grateful for all the attention the Latino thing
brings. I understand this is important and there's a lot of people
depending on me and the show to prove we can do something like
this.
</P>
<P>
   ''But at some point I want to stop focusing on the Latino thing
and start focusing on the quality of the show,'' he said. ''I'm
hoping people will look beyond (ethnicity) and say it's about
family, it's about an American family.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in television ....
</P>
<P>
   HAPPY BIRTHDAY, MR. WILDER: American Movie Classics toasts
filmmaker Billy Wilder's birthday Thursday with a double feature of
his superlative work. ''Stalag 17,'' the World War II POW drama
directed and co-written by Wilder, shows at 10:30 p.m. EDT,
followed by the Wilder-directed ''Sunset Boulevard'' at 12:35 a.m.
EDT. Wilder turns 94.
</P>
