<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Composite Index Breaks 4,000  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The Nasdaq composite index rose past 4,000
Tuesday for the first time since April, continuing a gradual
recovery from the steep selloff that knocked it as much as 37
percent below its record high.
</P>
<P>
   In morning trading on Wall Street, the technology-focused Nasdaq
composite was up 46.06 at 4,035.89. The index hasn't traded above
4,000 since April 12, when it ultimately plunged 286.27 points.
Even though it has recovered lost ground since then, it still is
20.5 percent below the all-time high of 5,048.62 set March 10.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average was down 48.43 at 10,509.41 and
the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was off 3.51 at 1,482.49.
</P>
<P>
   Investors who had grown leery of technology stocks are now
seeking out some of the biggest names in the sector on the
expectation that those companies will show the strongest profit
growth.
</P>
<P>
   Many technology stocks remain very highly priced relative to
their earnings. But now that rising interest rates have begun
forcing a modest economic slowdown, threatening corporate profits,
investors are focusing on companies whose earnings are growing
rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Nasdaq has been stuck in a very tight range while
investors have debated whether a slowdown was positive or whether
it would weigh on earnings,'' said William Meehan, chief market
analyst for Cantor Fitzgerald. ''Once people decided that tech
companies will continue to do very well, they broke out of that
trading range and have been gathering some nice momentum.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Intel rose $2.625 to $139.125 and PMC-Sierra, a
semiconductor component maker, rose $9.75 to $202.75. Yahoo! rose
$7.438 to $146.50.
</P>
<P>
   Dow component Honeywell International continued paying a price
for its announcement Monday that second-quarter earnings will miss
analysts' expectations. Honeywell said it is struggling with high
interest rates and higher-than-expected raw material prices in its
performance materials unit.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, its shares fell $3.375 to $36.875.
</P>
<P>
   Seagram fell $4.375 to $59.375 after French utilities and media
conglomerate Vivendi said it will buy the company for $34 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 4-to-3 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 310.40 million shares
in late morning, ahead of Monday's quiet pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 3.23 to 526.02.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
