<HEADLINE> France Inaugurates Opera House  </HEADLINE>
By MARILYN AUGUST
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- France on Tuesday inaugurated the gleaming facade
of the Paris Opera, returned to its 19th-century splendor by a bold
renovation project that had experts tracking down precious
materials across two continents.
</P>
<P>
   Workers using state-of-the-art technology labored for more than
a year to remove grime that had accumulated since 1867, when the
opera house was built to the greater glory of Emperor Napoleon III.
</P>
<P>
   ''After years of grayness, the Palais Garnier has come to life,
its exterior in full harmony with the passion and light of its
interior,'' Culture Minister Catherine Tasca.
</P>
<P>
   Today the landmark is home to the Paris Opera Ballet company,
while opera performances are held at the Opera-Bastille in eastern
Paris.
</P>
<P>
   ''The French have a saying that an architect creates a work, and
time perfects it,'' chief architect Alain-Charles Perrot said.
''But this is not the case of the Palais Garnier.''
</P>
<P>
   Air pollution and acid rain had darkened the chiseled limestone,
dimmed the luster of rooftop sculpture and corroded the colorful
mosaics and marbled floors of the elegant balcony overlooking the
square below.
</P>
<P>
   Once a fashionable perch to see and be seen during intermission,
a rooftop gallery had been off-limits to audiences since the late
1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ''Heads, arms and legs had fallen off statues, pieces of mosaic
were falling on people's heads, and the floor was ripped up,''
Perrot said.
</P>
<P>
   The restoration, which cost $7.7 million, marks the second phase
of renovations that are scheduled to end in 2007.
</P>
<P>
   One of the greatest challenges was remaining true to the spirit
of architect Charles Garnier, Perrot said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We wanted to remain faithful to the original design, and that
meant repairing or recreating pieces using the same or similar
materials to the ones Garnier chose a century ago,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't easy. The extravagant Garnier had crisscrossed
Europe and North Africa seeking the finest building materials. The
facade itself required six types of stone cut from different
quarries, while 10 kinds of marble were used for decorative columns
and elaborate flooring.
</P>
<P>
   ''Some mosaics had pieces missing, and we were able to fill them
in after we located the company in Italy that had furnished them
133 years ago,'' Perrot said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-20-00 1154 </TRAILER>
