<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 14:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmakers Have Part in FEMA Fights  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The El Dorado Irrigation District in
Placerville, Calif., had already lost two appeals in its quest for
more federal disaster aid, so for its third attempt, the agency
enlisted the help of two members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The irrigation district still didn't get the assistance, but the
case shows the willingness of lawmakers to intervene with the
Federal Emergency Management Agency.
</P>
<P>
   A sampling of lawmakers' letters, provided by FEMA, shows
different approaches -- ranging from passing on a constituent's
letter to urging the federal officials to reverse an earlier
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ''We understand that because FEMA has denied (the irrigation
district's) second appeal, FEMA considers this matter closed,''
said a Nov. 17, 1999 letter from Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif and
Rep. John Doolittle, R-Calif. to FEMA Director James Lee Witt.
</P>
<P>
   The letter nonetheless argued that agency ''inaccuracies'' in
the appeal ''should serve as a basis for FEMA to reconsider.'' The
agency refused.
</P>
<P>
   Other examples of congressional intervention:
</P>
<P>
   --Sen. John Breaux, D-La., on behalf of the Beau Chene Homeowners
Association in Mandeville, La., sought funds for debris removal
from privately owned roads after Hurricane Georges in 1998. FEMA
rejected the request.
</P>
<P>
   --Sen. John Edwards, D-N.C., wrote to President Clinton last
September, asking ''that you direct federal agencies to do all
within their power to expedite the rebuilding of N.C. Highway 12''
after Hurricane Dennis in August-September, 1999. FEMA responded
that it was a matter for the U.S. Department of Transportation.
</P>
<P>
   --Rep. Steven R. Rothman, D-N.J., wrote Witt last March in a
successful request to accelerate assistance grants to northern New
Jersey municipalities ravaged by Hurricane Floyd last September.
</P>
<P>
   --Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, passed on a request last year from
Galveston County Judge James D. Yarborough to divert funds from
Hurricane Floyd to repair beach erosion caused by Tropical Storm
Frances in 1998. FEMA funds cannot be diverted from one disaster to
another.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-20-00 1414 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000620.0076 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 14:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Examples of FEMA Audit Results  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY MARGASAK
<TEXT>
<P>
   Examples of disaster relief payments questioned by the Federal
Emergency Management Agency over the last decade during inspector
general's audits:
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Auditors questioned nearly $900,000 claimed by the California
Highway Patrol during the Los Angeles riots in April 1992 sparked
by the acquittal of four white officers in the beating of black
motorist Rodney King.
</P>
<P>
   The auditors said personnel and vehicle mileage costs were
claimed for work outside the riot area.
</P>
<P>
   The issue remains unsettled.
</P>
<P>
   ''If they want to pursue the matter, we want to appeal it,''
said CHP Commissioner Dwight Helmick. ''At that point, it was
completely legitimate; we still think it is.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The Pennsylvania Department of Transportation, after snow
removal from a January 1996 blizzard, claimed $34,757 for ''standby
equipment and labor,'' an audit showed.
</P>
<P>
   ''We question these charges because they did not contribute to
the removal of snow and represent idle time that is unallowable,''
the audit said.
</P>
<P>
   Pennsylvania officials argued FEMA seemed to change rules in
midstream.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's like shooting at a moving target,'' said Gary L. Hoffman,
chief engineer for the Pennsylvania Department of Transportation.
''You have your field people and it gets up to division and
division will change, and it gets up to headquarters and they'll
change opinions that were handed down at the division office.''
</P>
<P>
   The case remains open.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The Municipality of San Lorenzo, Puerto Rico, was cited for two
instances of receiving double payment in disaster aid.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, the city got more than $75,000 in insurance
proceeds for damages to the Municipal Cemetery and sports
recreational facilities after Hurricane Hortense in 1996. FEMA
funded the same projects.
</P>
<P>
   Auditors also found federal and state agencies covered more than
$42,000 of the cost to repair sidewalks, curbs, gutters and asphalt
while FEMA paid nearly $59,000 for the same work
</P>
<P>
   While no money has been recovered, auditors said municipal
officials concurred with the findings.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   DeKalb County, Ga. claimed $51,000 in FEMA aid for use of its
landfill to dispose of debris from Hurricane Opal in 1995. The
county did not have records to support the claim, and a county
official acknowledged the hurricane debris ''may have been mulched
rather than disposed of at the landfill.'' FEMA reclaimed more than
$40,000.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The City of Monroe, Ga. claimed more than $6,500 in federal aid
for replacing the contents of its fire station after a February
1993 tornado but actually incurred costs of only $425, auditors
said. For this and other ineligible claims, FEMA recovered more
than $32,000.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   After Hurricane Fran in 1996, the North Carolina Department of
Transportation claimed more than $770,000 in payments for debris
removal work by employees termed temporary. Auditors found
employees hired under temporary appointments often were
continuously employed for 11 months, released for a short period
and then rehired.
</P>
<P>
   Regular pay for permanent workers is not eligible for FEMA
funding.
</P>
<P>
   No funds have been recovered.
</P>
<P>
   FEMA is still negotiating a settlement with the state. North
Carolina officials admitted the temporary workers were hired before
the storm, but said releasing and rehiring them would have resulted
in unnecessary costs and work delays.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The South Dakota Department of Transportation, in a similar
case, claimed $304,228 in salaries and fringe benefits for workers
who removed snow after blizzards in early 1997.
</P>
<P>
   While state officials said these were not permanent employees,
FEMA concluded they worked for the department every year during the
winter months and already were on the payroll when the initial
disaster was declared.
</P>
<P>
   There has been no recovery yet from the audit, just completed
April 25.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Mercer, press secretary for Gov. Bill Janklow, said the
state is providing additional information to FEMA and believes
''the costs will be allowed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-20-00 1415 </TRAILER>
