<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Conservatives To Pick Leader  </HEADLINE>
By TOM COHEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- An attempt to unify Canadian conservatives into a
movement capable of winning the next federal election faces a
crucial decision Saturday -- the election of its leader.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadian Alliance, which seeks to combine the former Reform
Party based in western Canada with disgruntled Conservative Party
supporters elsewhere, will hold a nationwide vote of its members to
choose among four major contenders. If no candidate wins more than
50 percent, a runoff would take place July 8.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever wins will become the opposition leader in Canada's
parliament, and in all likelihood the main challenger for Prime
Minister Jean Chretien's job in national elections expected next
year.
</P>
<P>
   After starting three months ago with a core support of just over
70,000 members when the Reform Party joined, the Alliance now says
200,000 people have paid the $6.50 fee to be eligible to vote
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   If accurate, that would make the Alliance the largest party in
Canada. But questions persist about the potential cohesiveness of
Canada's political right, which appears split on abortion, gay
rights and capital punishment -- divisions that reflect the
diversity of Canada, with a population of 30 million spread across
the world's second-largest country.
</P>
<P>
   Little common ideological ground exists among farmers in the
plains, urban dwellers who are part of the high-tech economy and
large immigrant communities that benefit from liberal social
policies.
</P>
<P>
   The backbone of the Canadian Alliance is the old Reform Party,
which began in the 1980s to challenge the domination and perceived
ideological betrayal by the Conservative Party government under
Brian Mulroney.
</P>
<P>
   Reform Party growth cost the Conservative Party the 1993
election, with Chretien's Liberal Party taking over. Reform
continued to grow, becoming the official opposition party in
parliament four years later despite failing to win a seat east of
Manitoba.
</P>
<P>
   Realizing he needed support in Ontario and points east to win a
national election, Reform leader Preston Manning then fostered the
creation of the Canadian Alliance as a way to embrace the
Conservative Party he had battled and undermined.
</P>
<P>
   The Alliance was formally created in March, setting off a
leadership campaign by Manning, former Alberta Treasurer Stockwell
Day, Ontario political strategist Tom Long and British Columbia
politician Keith Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Manning, 57, is the son of longtime Alberta Premier Ernest
Manning, and doubled as a politician and preacher like his father.
He has worked in recent years to soften his nasal twang and dress
more stylishly. But opponents and even some supporters fear Manning
can never break away from the Reform reputation as a Western party
with anti-gay, anti-immigrant tendencies, and a Manning victory
would bolster a perception that the Alliance is just the Reform
Party under a different name.
</P>
<P>
   Day, a 49-year-old former preacher known for blunt
pronouncements of conservative views, is a charismatic speaker who
did the best job of distinguishing himself from the other
candidates. He declared himself strongly anti-abortion and
campaigned hard to emphasize his ties to different regions,
especially his ability to speak French in Francophone Quebec.
</P>
<P>
   Day is considered Manning's closest challenger, with a runoff
between the two likely.
</P>
<P>
   Long, 42, was a back-room strategist in Ontario's Conservative
Party. An architect of the 1995 Conservative victory in Ontario's
provincial election, he has employed U.S.-style campaign tactics
such as phone banks to seek new Alliance members.
</P>
<P>
   His speeches hammered home the theme that he is the only
candidate who can draw support in Ontario that the Alliance needs
to defeat the Liberals.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, a 39-year-old physician, made health care reform his
main message. But he lacks the name recognition of Manning and the
financial backing of Day or Long.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-20-00 1507 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
