<HEADLINE> French Halt Auschwitz Doctor Case  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- A French court Tuesday dismissed criminal charges
against a former German doctor at the Auschwitz death camp, ruling
that at age 89, he was too old for a trial on inciting racial
hatred.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor had asked for a conviction on principle against
Hans Muench.
</P>
<P>
   Several organizations representing French Resistance members and
Holocaust survivors filed suit against Muench for an interview he
gave to France-Inter Radio on Oct. 26 and Nov. 3, 1998, in which he
spoke ill of Gypsies. He also praised the work conditions at the
camp as well as his boss, Josef Mengele, the so-called ''Angel of
Death.''
</P>
<P>
   Three German doctors said that Muench was demented and unable to
stand trial. Although the French court found the German report
incoherent, it accepted its judgment that Muench was not fit to
appear in court. Muench suffers from Alzheimer's disease.
</P>
<P>
   Muench served as a doctor in Auschwitz from 1943 to 1945. He was
acquitted of war crimes in 1947 after former inmates he had worked
with in the Auschwitz lab testified he had helped save their lives.
He lives in Bavaria where he practiced medicine after the war.
</P>
<P>
   From 1940 to 1945, about 1.5 million people, mostly Jews, died
at Auschwitz in German-occupied Poland from starvation, disease and
forced labor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-20-00 1511 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000620.0087 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 15:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pro-UK Group: We'll End Cease-Fire  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) -- In a new threat to Northern
Ireland's tenuous peace, the province's largest pro-British
paramilitary group threatened Tuesday to break its cease-fire,
accusing Catholic groups of attacking Protestant homes.
</P>
<P>
   The outlawed Ulster Freedom Fighters, whose October 1994
cease-fire was vital to the negotiation of the province's peace
accord two years ago, said Roman Catholic nationalist groups are
conducting a campaign of intimidation against Protestants in two
areas of Belfast.
</P>
<P>
   ''This ethnic cleansing of north and west Belfast cannot and
will not be allowed to happen,'' the Ulster Freedom Fighters
statement said.
</P>
<P>
   It threatened to break the cease-fire as of midnight (7 p.m.
EDT). From that time, it said, the Ulster Freedom Fighters
''reserves the right to shoot any person seen to be attacking
Protestant homes.''
</P>
<P>
   ''This will be in direct contradiction to our cease-fire, which
we have steadfastly adhered to despite intense provocation, but
enough is enough,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   The Ulster Freedom Fighters has more than 2,000 members in
working-class Protestant neighborhoods. Its threat comes more than
six weeks after the Irish Republican Army -- the largest
pro-Catholic outlawed paramilitary group -- made a historic
commitment to begin disarming.
</P>
<P>
   The IRA's move allowed the British government to return some
self-governing powers to Northern Ireland's Protestant-Catholic
administration, which is trying to establish itself as a viable
local government after 28 years of direct rule from Britain.
</P>
<P>
   The British government, the IRA-allied Sinn Fein party and the
Ulster Freedom Fighters' own political ally, the Ulster Democratic
Party, quickly criticized the group for its threat.
</P>
<P>
   Ulster Democrat leader Gary McMichael said he understands ''the
concerns and frustration that have been building because of
anti-Protestant intimidation'' in some areas. But, he said, ''I
feel that this course of action would be a major mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   McMichael also called on police to control the alleged attacks
on Protestant homes.
</P>
<P>
   Sinn Fein said the threat was a matter of ''grave concern.''
Party chairman Mitchel McLaughlin said the threat was part of an
internal, territorial struggle among the pro-British groups.
</P>
<P>
   But he also claimed it was an attempt to heighten tensions
during the summer season of marches by the Orange Order, the
province's largest Protestant fraternal group. The march routes
often go through Catholic nationalist neighborhoods, where they are
seen as inflammatory and offensive. Over the weekend, dozens of
protesters trying to stop an Orange Order parade in the town of
Lurgan attacked security officers with firebombs.
</P>
<P>
   In London, British Prime Minister Tony Blair's office said the
people of Northern Ireland do not want a return to violence.
</P>
<P>
   ''No one is pretending every problem has been solved, but the
place for these to be sorted out is through the political
process,'' an official in the president's office said.
</P>
<P>
   A Downing Street spokesman also played down the discovery Monday
night of a small explosive device in the grounds of Hillsborough
Castle, the residence of the British government's top official in
the province.
</P>
<P>
   The official, Northern Ireland Secretary Peter Mandelson, was in
London when the device was found. He was due back at the castle, 12
miles outside Belfast, later this week.
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate claim of responsibility, but suspicion
fell on IRA dissidents opposed to the new Protestant-Catholic
administration in Belfast.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-20-00 1515 </TRAILER>
