<HEADLINE> Clinton Seeks More Medicare Spending  </HEADLINE>
By ALICE ANN LOVE
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton proposed a $21 billion boost
in Medicare payments over five years for hospitals and other health
care providers Tuesday, saying, ''Medicare patients are at risk''
because of insufficient spending.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have to face the challenge of making sure we pay the
Medicare providers enough so they can give our seniors the
high-quality care they deserve,'' the president said. ''Payments
are too low in important areas.''
</P>
<P>
   He also embraced Vice President Al Gore's proposal to put aside
the money in the Medicare trust fund so that it could not be used
for other purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Over 10 years, the president's plan for higher Medicare spending
would cost $40 billion. He said the nation could afford to increase
Medicare payments and, at the same time, add a prescription drug
benefit. ''Because of our prosperity I believe we can do both.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Clinton's proposal failed to satisfy some groups. ''I
think that the proposal that's being announced today falls far
short of what's needed,'' said Karen Ignagni, president of the
American Association of Health Plans, an HMO industry group.
</P>
<P>
   But Joel Johnson, a senior adviser to the president, said,
''This has a tremendous level of support on a bipartisan basis.''
</P>
<P>
   The request is expected to be among several items on a wish-list
the Clinton administration is expected to send Capitol Hill later
this month, along with new estimates that government surpluses
accumulating during the next decade will be more than twice as
large as previously predicted.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've been analyzing the effects of the balanced budget act
and a lot of other things that are happening, and our priority is
to ensure that there is high-quality access to care for Medicare
beneficiaries,'' said Medicare Administrator Nancy-Ann DeParle.
</P>
<P>
   Hospitals, home health care agencies and nursing homes would
likely get much of the money under the administration proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Medicare legislation being developed by House
Republicans would give around $2 billion to HMOs, many of which
have pulled out of Medicare in recent years complaining payments
don't keep up with inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Curbs on fees from Medicare, the nation's health insurance
program for the elderly and disabled, were part of 1997 legislation
to balance the federal budget.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when private health plans have been imposing lower
prices as well, health care providers say Medicare is squeezing
them too tight. Many hospitals say they have cut back community
service work, for example, such as transportation programs or
satellite clinics.
</P>
<P>
   Overall Medicare spending declined for the first time in the
program's 35-year history in 1999, by about 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, Congress voted to restore $16 billion to health care
providers, but there is broad agreement that was not enough.
</P>
<P>
   The administration is expected to upgrade its prediction for
federal budget surpluses to up to $1.9 trillion over the next 10
years, well above past estimates of $746 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-20-00 1516 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
