<DOCNO> APW20000620.0089 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 15:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Flirts With 4,000  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The Nasdaq composite index was flirting with the
4,000 mark Tuesday, a level it has not breached in more than two
months, as investors balanced hopes for strong profit growth with
some scattered warnings about technology companies' earnings.
</P>
<P>
   With an hour remaining in Wall Street's regular session, the
technology-focused Nasdaq composite was up 16.74 at 4,006.57. The
index was trading above 4,000 for the first time since April,
continuing its gradual recovery from the steep selloff that knocked
it as much as 37 percent below its record high.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the session, the index had risen as much as 60
points. The Nasdaq remains 21 percent below the all-time high of
5,048.62 set March 10.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average was down 124.80 at 10,433.04
and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was off 13.58 at 1,472.42.
</P>
<P>
   Investors who had grown leery of technology stocks are now
seeking out some of the biggest names in the sector on the
expectation that those companies will show the strongest profit
growth.
</P>
<P>
   Many technology stocks remain very highly priced relative to
their earnings. But now that rising interest rates have begun
forcing a modest economic slowdown, threatening corporate profits,
investors are focusing on companies whose earnings are growing
rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Intel rose $2.313 to $138.813 and PMC-Sierra, a
semiconductor component maker, rose $8.125 to $201.125. Yahoo! rose
$9.813 to $148.875.
</P>
<P>
   Yet a handful of Nasdaq components sustained sharp losses after
warning that their earnings in the current quarter will miss
analysts' expectations. Gadzoox Networks Inc., a maker of hardware
and software for storage area networks, fell $7.063 to $13.25, a 35
percent drop.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're settling into a two-tiered market,'' said William
Meehan, chief market analyst at Cantor Fitzgerald. ''Technology
will do very well, but look out for any disappointments.''
</P>
<P>
   Meehan added that many of the younger, less-proven companies on
the Nasdaq have not recovered from the springtime selloff, and
aren't likely to do so as investors apply tougher standards to the
technology sector.
</P>
<P>
   ''The selloff showed us that there are some junk companies, and
they are pretty much remaining junk,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dow component Honeywell International continued paying a price
for its announcement Monday that second-quarter earnings will miss
analysts' expectations. Honeywell said it is struggling with high
interest rates and higher-than-expected raw material prices in its
performance materials unit.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, its shares fell $4.375 to $35.875.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors fell $2.25 to $62.625, adding to the Dow's
declines. North American chief Ronald Zarrella told journalists and
financial analysts Tuesday that profit margins this year will not
reach GM's goal of 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Seagram fell $6.375 to $57.375 after French utilities and media
conglomerate Vivendi said it will buy the company in an all-stock
transaction that initially valued Seagram at $77.35 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Shoe company Steve Madden Ltd. fell $1.938 to $11.188 on the
Nasdaq. Owner Steven Madden was arrested Tuesday on charges that he
conspired to manipulate the value of his company during its initial
public offering in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 3-to-2 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 783.01 million shares
in late afternoon, ahead of Monday's quiet pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 1.24 from
Monday's revised close to 524.03.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
