<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 15:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Unsure of Mideast Summit Date  </HEADLINE>
By PAULINE JELINEK
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The United States said Tuesday it will not
decide the timing of an Israeli-Palestinian summit until after
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright visits the Middle East next
week.
</P>
<P>
   Danny Yatom, chief policy adviser to Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak, said Monday ''the situation is ripe for a summit,'' and one
should be held in the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   After seven years of talks, Yatom said, each side knows the
other's positions, and now decisions must be made by the leaders.
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman Richard Boucher said Albright will
try to figure out next week whether more work needs to be done
first.
</P>
<P>
   ''The president, two or three days ago, said that at this
juncture we would say that a basis does not exist'' for a summit,
Boucher said.
</P>
<P>
   ''But the point is to see next week, when the secretary goes
out, if there is such a basis, or if we need to continue,'' he
said. ''The president's made quite clear that we're prepared to go
forward with a summit at the appropriate time, and (when) we think
the necessary basis exist.''
</P>
<P>
   Yatom said the summit must take place in the next few weeks to
avoid conflicting with the political calendar in the United States,
where party conventions are set for the end of July.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians assumed the summit would be the last stage of
negotiating an accord. The Israelis have said the results could be
more modest.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian Economics and Planning Minister Nabil Shaath says
the Palestinians do not want a summit unless it is properly
prepared, meaning that an accord is all but ready for signature.
There are few signs that the two sides were close to agreement on
any of the main issues.
</P>
</TEXT>
