<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 15:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Aide Criticizes Helms' Tone  </HEADLINE>
By RON KAMPEAS
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- In a rare shouting match between the closest of
allies, a top deputy to Prime Minister Ehud Barak on Tuesday
accused Jesse Helms of taking a ''patronizing tone'' with Israel
when the powerful U.S. senator suggested Barak fire the deputy.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Defense Minister Ephraim Sneh was reacting to the latest
congressional broadside against his suggestion last week that any
cut in U.S. military aid to Israel should be matched by a
comparable reduction in Israeli defense procurements from U.S.
manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   ''What is worrisome is the harsh, patronizing tone of an
important senator like Jesse Helms,'' Sneh told Israel radio.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative lawmakers in both U.S. houses are considering a
$250 million cut to Israel to match the sale price of an
Israeli-made advanced airborne early warning system to China. The
concern is that the PHALCON system would increase the Chinese
threat to U.S.-backed Taiwan, and could one day be used to track
U.S. planes.
</P>
<P>
   Sneh suggested to parliament last week that if the cut goes
through, the Israeli army would do well to spend an equivalent
amount on ''low tech'' army supplies -- boots, automatic rifles, and
other items -- in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   He suggested that Israel had only purchased the items as a favor
to the United States, and had deprived some of the poorest sectors
of Israeli society employment in the process.
</P>
<P>
   Israel plows most of the $1.9 billion a year it receives in U.S.
military aid back into the U.S. economy in defense purchases.
</P>
<P>
   Sneh's comments angered Helms, the chairman of the Senate
Foreign Relations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Sneh would ''do well to bear in mind that the American
businesses he intends to punish pay the taxes that make possible
the foreign aid that his country receives from the U.S.
taxpayers,'' Helms said in a statement published Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sneh's threat is an insult to all Americans, including this
senator who has been a longtime friend of Israel,'' said the North
Carolina Republican. ''Frankly, I feel that Prime Minister Barak
may want to dismiss Mr. Sneh.''
</P>
<P>
   Sneh told The Associated Press that the outrage voiced by Helms
and by Rep. Sonny Callahan, an Alabama Republican who heads the
House Appropriations foreign operations subcommittee, were based on
a distorted understanding of his remarks.
</P>
<P>
   ''All I said was that if military aid to Israel is cut by $250
million, we would have no choice but to give up the procurement of
low-tech items in order to keep the procurement of (U.S.-made)
high-tech systems,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sneh said he believed that his remarks were distorted by people
with ''evil intentions.'' He would not specify whom, but Israel
radio and the daily Yediot Ahronot both quoted unidentified Israeli
defense officials as saying that leading U.S. defense manufacturers
were seeking ways of limiting Israel's expanding defense sales --
reportedly now reaching $2 billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of Israeli defense products that contain U.S. components
are subject to U.S. review. In the wake of the PHALCON controversy,
the Pentagon recently pressed Israel to extend U.S. review to all
Israeli military sales. Israel has resisted the request, and
Israeli defense industry officials are reportedly concerned that
such reviews would facilitate industrial espionage by their U.S.
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Sneh said a threat to Israel's defense exports was a threat to
Israeli security.
</P>
<P>
   ''Thanks to the defense exports, we can also conduct research
and development for Israel security, and this is the secret of our
qualitative superiority,'' he told Israel radio.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration is negotiating quietly with Israel to
limit its exports to China, and administration officials have asked
Congress to back off the threats.
</P>
<P>
   ''Helms' letter significantly contradicts the friendly,
constructive spirit in which Israel and the United States are
trying to resolve the issue of the sale of the PHALCON to China,''
Sneh said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-20-00 1524 </TRAILER>
