<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 15:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Greets King of Morocco  </HEADLINE>
By TERENCE HUNT
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- With Chelsea Clinton standing in for her
mother, President Clinton welcomed King Mohammed VI of Morocco to
the White House on Tuesday, saying he has distinguished himself by
his courage and conviction.
</P>
<P>
   The 36-year-old leader of the North African nation was greeted
with drum rolls, trumpet fanfare and a 21-gun salute on a bright,
sunny day on the South Lawn.
</P>
<P>
   ''Morocco is a sterling example of Islamic tolerance, a force
for peace rooted in the common values of humanity,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The young king took power in July on the death of his father,
King Hassan II, who ruled Morocco for 38 years. Clinton and his
wife, Hillary, cut short a trip to fly to Morocco for the funeral,
a gesture that Mohammed VI said he would always remember.
</P>
<P>
   With the first lady on the campaign trail in New York, Chelsea
Clinton, home from college, took her mother's place at the formal
welcoming ceremony. It was the first time that Chelsea, 20, has
played the stand-in at a state arrival. She seemed poised and
confident as she shook hands with the king and touched cheeks with
his sister, Princess Lalla Meryem.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton was to return to the White House in time for the
traditional state dinner.
</P>
<P>
   The president and the king celebrated the strong ties between
the United States and Morocco.
</P>
<P>
   ''America will never forget that in 1777, the first nation in
the world to recognize the United States was the kingdom of
Morocco,'' Clinton said. ''Ten years later our two countries
approved a treaty of peace and friendship, which today remains the
longest unbroken treaty of its kind in all history.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton noted that Mohammed VI first visited the White House as
crown prince with his father 22 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''Providence called upon you to be one of the voices of a new
generation of Arab leaders,'' Clinton said. ''And you have
responded with courage and conviction, healing old wounds,
promoting democracy, lifting those left behind, touching the hearts
of your people.''
</P>
<P>
   Dubbed the ''king of the poor'' by the Moroccan media, Mohammed
VI has made social policy a priority in a country where more than
20 percent of the population is officially unemployed and about
half, mainly women, are illiterate.
</P>
<P>
   He has broken with his father by firing senior security
officials and showing more tolerance to Islamic opponents of the
late king.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in English, the young king said his country has been a
champion of human rights and democracy.
</P>
<P>
   He said Morocco is a nation ''fervently wishing to raise our
economic relations to the level of our political dialogue.'' He
also said his country is implementing economic reforms and offering
foreign investors ''the best guarantees of security and profit.''
</P>
<P>
   The king said there is ''an imperative need'' for wealthy
nations to help the struggling countries in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ''The unbearable sufferings witnessed in many African countries
make it a moral obligation for us to put this stricken continent
back on the road to peace and progress,'' the king said.
</P>
<P>
   At midday, Mohammed VI had lunch at the State Department with
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, who praised him for
''honoring the legacy of his father by continuing to play a
positive role'' in support of the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
   The king spoke on the need for U.S. investment in Morocco and of
the thorny issue of the Western Sahara, saying he favors efforts by
the U.N. mission and special envoy James Baker to resolve it.
</P>
<P>
   War broke out in 1976 after Spain abandoned the territory and
Morocco annexed it. Baker is planning to convene a second round of
face-to-face talks between Morocco and the Polisario Front rebels
next week to try to salvage plans for an independence referendum in
the Western Sahara -- or consider an alternative.
</P>
<P>
   While calling the area, Morocco's ''southern province,'' the
king said he seeks a ''just and lasting solution'' to the problem.
</P>
</TEXT>
