<HEADLINE> House Moves To Honor Apollo 11 Crew  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House voted Tuesday to award the
Congressional Gold Medal to the crew of Apollo 11 to honor their
pioneering flight to the moon in July 1969.
</P>
<P>
   The medal, the highest civilian honor given by Congress,
recognizes Neil Armstrong, Buzz Aldrin and Michael Collins for
their ''monumental and unprecedented feat of space exploration.''
</P>
<P>
   ''This is about 30 years too late,'' said Rep. James Rogan,
R-Calif., the sponsor. The first astronauts to travel to the moon
''are Columbus, Galileo and Lindbergh all rolled into three.''
</P>
<P>
   Others considered for gold medals this year have been the late
Peanuts comic strip creator Charles Schulz, the late Cardinal John
O'Connor and Pope John Paul II.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which authorizes the president to present the medals
on behalf of Congress, still needs to clear the Senate. The House
approved it on a voice vote.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The bill is H.R. 2815.
</P>
