<HEADLINE> Museum Giants Sign Russia Deal  </HEADLINE>
By THOMAS RYMER
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Russia (AP) -- Two titans in world art, the
Guggenheim and the Hermitage, signed a long-term agreement Tuesday
in St. Petersburg to develop an international network of museums
and share some of their vast collections.
</P>
<P>
   The Solomon R. Guggenheim Foundation operates art museums and
exhibition spaces in New York, Venice, Berlin and Bilbao, Spain,
and possesses a collection specializing in contemporary art.
</P>
<P>
   Owning more than 3 million works of art, the Hermitage in St.
Petersburg is one of the world's largest museums, with a collection
heavy in more traditional works by artists such as Da Vinci,
Michelangelo and Rembrandt. But the state-funded Hermitage is
strapped for funds and has been seeking foreign sponsors and
collaboration deals like the one signed Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''When you look at the match between what the Guggenheim has and
needs and what the Hermitage has and needs, it's an almost ideal
match,'' Guggenheim Foundation director Thomas Krens told The
Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   The Hermitage hopes to use the partnership to revitalize its
activities with the aid of the American museum's experience in
exhibiting modern art.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Guggenheim's expertise in the field of museum design and
development, and its collections and expertise in modern and
contemporary art will be valuable assets for us to draw upon,''
said Michael Piotrovski, director at the Hermitage Museum.
</P>
<P>
   They plan to develop new display space in St. Petersburg in the
General Staff Building, which is located across the enormous Palace
Square from the Hermitage.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times reported that the General Staff renovations
would cost $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   Catherine the Great began the Hermitage collection in the 18th
century, and the museum opened to the public in 1852.
</P>
<P>
   The Hermitage is planning, as one of the exhibits in the newly
developed space, a section for 20th-century art. Russia's modernist
art movement was one of the world's strongest leading up to and
just after the 1917 revolution, but it was squeezed out by more
traditionalist forms prescribed by Soviet dictator Josef Stalin in
the late 1920s.
</P>
<P>
   For the Guggenheim, which was established in 1937, the
collaboration is an opportunity to expand its scope by allowing it
to display pieces from the Hermitage's collection of old master,
Impressionist and post-Impressionist works, antiquities and
decorative arts.
</P>
<P>
   The Hermitage would have a presence at the proposed new
Guggenheim museum at Wall Street on the East River in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are some great opportunities for architecture over
here,'' Krens said. ''There are five big interior courtyards at the
General Staff Building. Let's just say -- pure hypothesis -- that you
decided to get the three greatest contemporary architects to build
three new buildings there. It would be like a Russian Easter egg.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-20-00 1615 </TRAILER>
