<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hospitals Urged on Stroke Centers  </HEADLINE>
By LAURAN NEERGAARD
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Not enough hospitals muster the proper
emergency response for stroke victims, say new recommendations that
urge creation of hospital ''stroke centers'' for rapid care, like
the trauma centers that have revolutionized care of accident
victims.
</P>
<P>
   Time is crucial: A clot-busting drug called TPA can stop a
stroke, helping patients recover with little disability, but only
if patients receive it within three hours of the first symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   Yet only 2 percent to 3 percent of stroke patients get TPA,
something a group of stroke organizations called the Brain Attack
Coalition hopes to improve with the new recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   Stroke centers, modeled after the trauma centers that treat
critically injured patients, can help, the coalition concluded.
</P>
<P>
   To establish them, hospitals need a specially trained ''stroke
team'' available 24 hours a day who can get to a patient's bedside
within minutes, say the recommendations, published in Wednesday's
Journal of the American Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   ''The sooner a patient with stroke receives proper care, the
better their chances of having a good recovery,'' said Dr. Mark
Alberts of Duke University.
</P>
<P>
   Alberts is a consultant to TPA manufacturer Genentech Inc. and
lead author of the JAMA article. But the Brain Attack Coalition,
which includes the American Heart Association and other health
groups, developed the recommendations, and joined the National
Institutes of Health in announcing them Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Stroke strikes 700,000 Americans a year, and is the nation's
third leading cause of death.
</P>
<P>
   For years, doctors had little to offer. But in the mid-1990s,
with the advent of TPA, experts began pushing patients to seek
emergency care at the first symptom: Sudden numbness or weakness,
especially on one side; confusion or trouble speaking; sudden
trouble seeing or walking; a sudden severe headache.
</P>
<P>
   Yet some hospitals still don't triage and diagnose rapidly
enough, Alberts said. Careful diagnosis is important because not
all strokes are caused by clots -- some are burst blood vessels that
require different treatment, not TPA.
</P>
<P>
   Several dozen U.S. hospitals, mostly large teaching hospitals
such as Duke, already have stroke centers. Studies show stroke
centers can significantly reduce patients' risk of death or winding
up in a nursing home, Dr. H.J.M. Barnett of Canada's University of
Western Ontario wrote in an accompanying JAMA editorial.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to a 24-hour stroke team, the recommendations urge
that hospitals:
</P>
<P>
   --Be able to perform a CT scan or a brain MRI within 25 minutes
of a doctor's order.
</P>
<P>
   --Have written procedures for triaging suspected stroke patients,
and trained emergency room workers to recognize symptoms and start
the process. Also, a community's ambulance service should be
integrated with the stroke center to ensure patients are
transported rapidly and that paramedics notify hospitals a possible
stroke is coming in.
</P>
<P>
   The recommendations could spark development of at least several
hundred stroke centers in smaller or rural hospitals, Alberts said.
Most hospitals already have CT scanners and just need to establish
procedures and line up workers, costing anywhere from $8,000 to
$200,000, he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.stroke-site.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-20-00 1620 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000620.0108 </DOCNO>
