<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 16:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak: Shas Has My Final Offer  </HEADLINE>
By DINA KRAFT
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Prime Minister Ehud Barak shifted the spotlight
back to the religious Shas party Tuesday by saying he has made Shas
a final offer aimed at keeping the party from bolting his fractious
coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Barak's offer came just hours after four Shas members of the
Israeli Cabinet resigned in an effort to press Barak to release
more state funds for Shas schools and legalize pirate radio
stations affiliated with the party.
</P>
<P>
   The resignations do not take effect until Thursday, which gives
Shas time to press its case.
</P>
<P>
   The crisis has seriously weakened Barak and undermined his
efforts to conclude a peace deal with the Palestinians by year's
end.
</P>
<P>
   Barak said Tuesday he had met ''90 percent'' of the demands of
the religious party, and that he has done all he can.
</P>
<P>
   ''My colleagues and I ... made a supreme effort to keep Shas in
the coalition,'' he told reporters. ''What stands before us at this
hour is the norms of governance in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   ''They know our offers, and we are waiting for their answer,''
Barak said.
</P>
<P>
   But he did not sound optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ''We do want to see Shas in government, but we will respect the
decision they make,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For Barak to continue governing without Shas would likely
require a minority government supported from the outside by Arab
legislators. Barak's mentor, Yitzhak Rabin, governed under similar
circumstances, and made considerable peace strides -- but his narrow
government drew much rancor from the nationalist opposition and
ended when he was assassinated by an ultranationalist Jew in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute centers on Shas demands that their nemesis,
Education Minister Yossi Sarid, release $6 million in funds to
their ailing religious school system. Sarid, an ardent secularist,
refuses to do so until Shas demonstrates that the funds will not be
mismanaged. In 16 years of the party's existence, Shas-run
ministries have been plagued with reports of incompetence and
corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Barak said Tuesday that he offered Shas the money upfront, to be
supervised by a ministerial committee chaired by himself. Shas has
demanded total control of the funds' disbursement, saying that is a
matter of ''honor.''
</P>
<P>
   Shas also wants its five pirate radio stations legalized. Barak
offered to incorporate the stations into an existing commercially
run network that hews to government guidelines. Again, Shas, which
views the radio stations as a powerful election-time propaganda
tool, is loath to accept outside interference.
</P>
<P>
   Three deputy ministers from Shas did not hand in letters of
resignation, a signal that the party is leaving its options open.
Resignations of deputy ministers take effect immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Shas officials said the next two days could be used to salvage
the coalition.
</P>
<P>
   ''Anything could happen, it's all on the table. They know what
we want,'' said Shas Infrastructures Minister Eli Suissa.
</P>
<P>
   In his terse letter of resignation, Labor Minister Eli Ishai,
the Shas chairman, said the decision to leave the government was
made by Shas' spiritual advisers, a group of rabbis. ''Those who
take advice from the elderly don't fail,'' Ishai wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Barak had pushed hard to keep Shas in his 11-month-old
government. Barak's One Israel alignment has only 26 seats in
parliament. Shas, with 17 seats, holds the balance of power between
hawkish and dovish factions and can hold Barak hostage to its
demands.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
