<DOCNO> APW20000620.0110 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 16:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton, citing Central Park attacks, calls for protection  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOLTON LANDING, N.Y. (AP) - Senate candidate Hillary Rodham
Clinton criticized some members of the news media on Tuesday for
broadcasting pictures of women recently attacked in Central Park,
using that to call for a new push to provide Americans with more
privacy.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe it was wrong to show the faces of those women being
assaulted without getting their permission first,'' the first lady
told the annual conference of the New York State Broadcasters
Association.
</P>
<P>
   ''The information age and the 24-hour news cycle should not turn
acts of abuse and disrespect into a spectator sport,'' she said at
the Sagamore Resort overlooking Lake George.
</P>
<P>
   The attacks against the women in Central Park came earlier this
month after the Puerto Rican Day parade that Clinton and her
Republican opponent, Rep. Rick Lazio, had both marched in. While
pictures of the women were broadcast, many stations concealed their
identity by blurring the faces. Some did not.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton used the incident to tell the broadcasters that it was
time to mount a campaign to protect Americans' privacy.
</P>
<P>
   ''When you enter public life, you give up a lot of your privacy.
I know that all too well,'' Clinton said. ''But I don't believe you
should give up your privacy when you visit your doctor, take a trip
to the video store or buy a book on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   As things stand now, Clinton said, ''There is greater protection
for your video rental receipts than for your most intimate medical
information.''
</P>
<P>
   The first lady said that if elected to the Senate, she would
make protecting personal privacy a top priority.
</P>
<P>
   In a more than one-hour appearance before the broadcasters,
Clinton also said the Senate race has ''obviously changed to some
extent'' with Lazio replacing Mayor Rudolph Giuliani as the GOP
candidate. The New York City mayor withdrew on May 19 to deal with
prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ''On many issues, the mayor and I were much closer together than
I am with my new opponent,'' Clinton said. ''He agreed with me on
lots of issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton cited she and the mayor's strong advocacy for gun
licensing laws and abortion rights as areas where they were more in
agreement than she is with Lazio. The contrast allowed Clinton,
without saying so to the broadcasters, to again suggest that Lazio
is more conservative than Giuliani. A main theme of her campaign is
that Lazio is too conservative for New York.
</P>
<P>
   And, in a lengthy explanation of why she ran for the Senate in
what was certain to be a tough race, the first lady said one of the
factors was an encounter she had with a young female athlete in
Chelsea in New York City last year as they promoted a television
documentary on women athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that at one point after the program, the young
woman leaned over to her and whispered in her ear, ''Dare to
compete, Mrs. Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   The appearance before the broadcasters came as yet another poll
showed the race with Lazio to be a squeeker
</P>
<P>
   The latest poll, from Marist College's Institute for Public
Opinion, had each favored by 42 percent of voters and with the
congressman from Long Island leading her 2-1 among key suburban
voters.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think this is a close race. As I've said for many weeks and
months now, it's a close race,'' Clinton said. ''There's a lot at
stake in the race and it's going to be a hard fought, close
election.''
</P>
<P>
   Later Tuesday, she toured an afterschool program in the Bronx
before heading back to Washington, D.C., to attend a state dinner
at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio addressed the broadcasters conference by telephone on
Monday night from Washington where he was working on House
business. Clinton had criticized him last week for missing votes in
Congress to campaign.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
