<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> At almost $30 million, 42nd Street studios serve nonprofit artists  </HEADLINE>
By VERENA DOBNIK
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - They have talent, some Tonys and no money - but
on Tuesday they arrived on 42nd Street.
</P>
<P>
   Some of America's best performing artists inaugurated a
10-story, $29.6 million building of rehearsal studios for nonprofit
arts companies - the first of its type in the country, said Cora
Cahan, president of The New 42nd Street Inc., which spearheaded the
effort.
</P>
<P>
   Nestled amid renovated commercial theaters that ousted porn
shops, The New 42nd Street Studios are ''a lagoon in the cacophony,
the Walden Pond on 42nd where people can work and think,'' said
Cahan. ''This is purely about creativity, about taking away the
anxiety by offering a place that's clean and affordable.''
</P>
<P>
   The studios, flooded with sunlight streaming through an
all-glass facade, are equipped with grand pianos and wooden dance
barres that stretch against the Manhattan skyline, overlookingTimes
Square.
</P>
<P>
   The subsidized space is a dream-come-true for Sheila Kay Davis,
founder of the New Professional Theatre, which premieres new plays
with a black perspective.
</P>
<P>
   The troupe rents rehearsal space for $40 an hour, or 25 percent
below market rates, and an office for only $407 a month, or about
half the commercial rate. The subsidy money comes from renting the
same studios for commercial use, at market rates.
</P>
<P>
   ''I couldn't rent a closet for that,'' said Davis, whose actors
until recently used run-down rooms on the old 42nd Street,
surrounded by porn shops and boarding houses ''where Gypsy Rose Lee
did her burlesque.''
</P>
<P>
   About four years ago, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani harnessed a
private-public team of developers to start cleaning up Times
Square, bringing in shiny, neon-lighted hotels, theme stores and
restaurants that are the core of the area's renaissance.
</P>
<P>
   As workers put finishing touches on the studio building on
Tuesday, Davis watched her actors rehearsing ''The In-Gathering,''
about an emancipated slave in search of his wife after the Civil
War. In September, the musical is the first public performance
scheduled for the 199-seat Duke theater on the building's ground
floor ; its funding came from the estate of the late Doris Duke.
</P>
<P>
   ''My company has everything - talent and actors who have worked
in plays that won Tonys. We have everything but money,'' she said.
''This was a blessing.''
</P>
<P>
   The studios are across the street from a high-rent theater
currently offering the Broadway hit musical, ''The Lion King.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a venue the Parsons Dance Company could never afford.
</P>
<P>
   But on the seventh floor of their new home, they're sweating
under the 13-foot ceilings - through steps that will cross the
ocean next week, for a performance at the Spoleto Festival in
Italy.
</P>
<P>
   The nonprofit dance company is in the process of moving from a
cramped, windowless space at City Center on West 55th Street whose
700 square feet ''was like working in a bullpen'' to the new studio
with 1,400 square feet, said Frank Sonntag, the company's executive
director.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a new concept,'' Sonntag said. ''The space crunch is so
great in New York that the non-profits are constantly moving,
scrambling to find affordable space.''
</P>
<P>
   The New 42nd Street Inc. got a kick-start from the city and
state in 1990 as an independent, nonprofit organization charged
with revitalizing seven historic theaters, including The New
Victory. The organization now relies mostly on commercial tenants
and fundraisers.
</P>
<P>
   All but $1.7 million of the $29.6 million cost of the studio
building has been raised through a combination of public and
private funds, said Cahan.
</P>
<P>
   Construction costs were high, she explained, because the floors
were specially built to be resilient, the walls are soundproof, and
the large spaces have no columns. In addition, each mirrored room
has separate climate-control for varying needs, and there are
dressing rooms and lockers for performers.
</P>
<P>
   Designed by the firm of Platt Byard Dovell Architects, the
building is illuminated by multicolored computer-programmed lights
that play across its glass facade at night.
</P>
<P>
   As the first building to provide studio space for nonprofit
artists, ''we lend counterpoint to the rest of the street,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   On the block where Gypsy Rose Lee once entertained, 42nd Street
is swinging again.
</P>
<P>
   And it's a class act.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
