<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panel: Cut Clinton's Land Proposals  </HEADLINE>
By MATT KELLEY
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Senate panel considering President Clinton's
proposals to buy more park land, enhance services for American
Indians and expand arts funding attempted Tuesday to avoid a veto
showdown by endorsing more modest cuts than the House had made.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Appropriations Interior Subcommittee approved a $15.5
billion spending plan for the Interior Department, Forest Service,
arts and cultural programs, and several related agencies. The
package is nearly $1 billion less than Clinton requested but $628
million more than this year's budget.
</P>
<P>
   House Democrats had warned of a possible veto last week when the
House approved a plan totaling only $14.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ''My goal is to get a bill that is going to be signed with
relatively little controversy,'' said the subcommittee's chairman,
Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate measure includes increases in several areas sought by
Clinton, such as rebuilding Indian reservation schools, increasing
funding the National Endowment for the Arts and buying state and
federal park land.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate plan also is free of several controversial amendments
offered in the House, such as a rejected proposal to cut off
funding for the eight national monuments Clinton declared in the
West this year.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had asked for $470 million to buy new federal and state
park land. The Senate plan cut that by more than half to $221
million, but that still was more than the House plan included.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate plan also includes $105 million for the NEA, a $7.4
million increase over this year's budget but $45 million less than
Clinton's request. The House version would not give the NEA an
increase.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate plan would increase spending on Indian school
construction by $143 million. That's enough to build the six
schools the Bureau of Indian Affairs deems most necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had asked for an increase of $167 million for Indian
school construction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
