<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Capitol Visitors' Center Planned  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID HO
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Congressional leaders broke ground Tuesday for
a visitors' center at the U.S. Capitol, taking a small ceremonial
step toward the largest capitol project since the 1850s.
</P>
<P>
   ''Today we begin the process of constructing a facility that
will enable us to better take care of the visitors to the people's
house,'' said House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., co-chair of the
Capitol Preservation Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The center, which will cost an estimated $265 million, is
expected to open sometime in 2005 to provide tourists with
historical displays, restrooms and food while they wait to enter
the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   For a decade, Congress has considered having an underground
center on the east side of the Capitol to give as many as 18,000
tourists a day waiting in long tour lines respite from the winter
cold and summer heat.
</P>
<P>
   Republican opposition to the cost put the plan on hold in 1991.
It was revived only after a gunman shot his way into the building
two years ago, killing two police officers. The center would help
security by moving the screening of visitors away from the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 federal budget included $100 million for planning,
engineering, designing and constructing the center, and the sale of
two commemorative coin series has created a fund worth another $28
million.
</P>
<P>
   Private donations will pay the remaining cost, and the Pew
Charitable Trusts, which established a nonprofit foundation
committed to raising $100 million, has already received $35 million
in pledges, Hastert said.
</P>
<P>
   The preservation commission still must approve a final design
for the center, but current plans foresee a three-level underground
structure of 558,000 square feet set into the east side of the
Capitol, across the street from the Supreme Court and the Library
of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The Architect of the Capitol is studying a proposal to link the
Library of Congress to the visitors' center with an underground
tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   Pre-construction activities, including testing the soil for
hazardous materials and items of archaeological value, will begin
Wednesday, said Genevieve Erny, a commission spokeswoman. Actual
construction should begin within 12 months to 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Strom Thurmond, commission co-chair and the longest-serving
senator in American history, said he was honored to participate in
the ground breaking, but for him it wasn't the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ''I stood on the east front of the Capitol 41 years ago to break
ground for the extension of our national capitol,'' said Thurmond,
R-S.C., who was first elected to the Senate in 1954.
</P>
<P>
   Senate and House leaders joined Hastert and Thurmond at the
site.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the net: The Architect of the Capitol: http://www.aoc.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
