<HEADLINE> Clinton puts Rochester-based company in Syracuse  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BOLTON LANDING, N.Y. (AP) - It looks as if Hillary Rodham
Clinton still has some boning up to do on her adopted state.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady, who is running for the U.S. Senate from New York
and has made much of learning about the state she had never lived
in before January, was discussing New York's economy Tuesday before
the New York State Broadcasters Association's annual conference in
Bolton Landing.
</P>
<P>
   Ticking off a list of famous New York companies, including
Eastman Kodak and Bausch &AMP; Lomb, Clinton noted, ''We've got
Paychex, one of the biggest sort of information tech companies in
the country, in Syracuse.''
</P>
<P>
   It was at that point Clinton probably could have benefitted from
an interruption from ''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' host Regis
Philbin with his trademark query: ''Is that your final answer?''
</P>
<P>
   Paychex, a national leader in payroll check processing, is
headquartered in Rochester.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Clinton met in Rochester last year with Paychex chief
B. Thomas Golisano when she was courting the possible support of
the Independence Party, the New York arm of the national Reform
Party. Multi-millionaire Golisano put the party on the electoral
map in New York when he ran unsuccessfully for governor in 1994 and
again in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Golisano didn't seem miffed when told about Clinton's gaffe.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a very simple mistake to make,'' the company founder
said. ''We have offices all across the state.''
</P>
<P>
   One of those Paychex offices is in Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   Philbin was honored by at Tuesday's conference with a
''Broadcaster of the Year'' award.
</P>
</TEXT>
