<DOCNO> APW20000620.0130 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House Passes Debt Reduction Bill  </HEADLINE>
By CURT ANDERSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Seeking to emphasize debt payment over
government spending, House Republicans engineered easy passage
Tuesday of legislation requiring that at least $16 billion in
unforeseen surplus money go directly to retire the public debt.
</P>
<P>
   The House also passed a second bill to ensure that surplus
payroll taxes earmarked for Medicare aren't diverted for spending
or tax cuts -- a measure that Vice President Al Gore called during a
visit to the Capitol a ''strong signal ... that Medicare is not
fair game to be used as a piggybank.''
</P>
<P>
   The debt bill, passed by a 419-5 vote, would require that any
non-Social Security surplus money for fiscal 2000 above the $24.4
billion projected earlier this year be deposited in a new Treasury
Department account created specifically to pay off debt. Sponsors
said upcoming summer estimates are likely to add at least $16
billion in unforeseen surplus revenue.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we don't take that money off the table, somebody's going to
spend it,'' said House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill.
</P>
<P>
   The national debt now stands at $5.7 trillion, with $3.6
trillion owed to the public and $2.1 trillion owed to Social
Security and other trust funds. The bill would also reduce the
government's borrowing limit, currently $5.95 trillion, by whatever
amount is deposited into the new account.
</P>
<P>
   Although Congress could easily pass another law if lawmakers
decided to spend some of that money, Rep. Ernie Fletcher, R-Ky.,
said the House vote would make it politically more difficult to do
so.
</P>
<P>
   ''It will be very hard to go home and say 'I voted against
appropriating money to pay down the debt,''' said Fletcher, the
bill's chief sponsor. ''If you're serious about it, this is the way
to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats also supported the bill, but many pointed out that
debt is automatically paid down if nothing is done with surplus tax
revenue. Rep. Robert Matsui, D-Calif., said Republicans did not
want the measure to go beyond fiscal 2000 because they want future
surpluses to go for huge tax cuts if Texas Gov. George W. Bush is
elected president.
</P>
<P>
   ''The reality is, this is a political act, not a substantive
act,'' Matsui said. ''It won't hurt, but it doesn't really help,
either.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration opposes the bill for its provision to
reduce the government debt ceiling, but the president has stopped
short of threatening a veto. There is no companion measure in the
Senate, but GOP leaders there said interest was growing in passing
a similar measure.
</P>
<P>
   The Medicare ''lockbox'' bill, passed 420-2, would ensure that
an estimated $126 billion surplus payroll taxes deposited in the
Medicare account isn't borrowed for spending or tax cuts. A similar
''lockbox'' for Social Security passed the House last year -- it
remains bottled up in the Senate -- and Gore has called for a
similar Medicare plan.
</P>
<P>
   Gore told reporters that the House action would impose ''a moral
obligation'' to keep Medicare off-limits -- but said it should be
made permanent.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're passing a bill that is a lot weaker than it could be,''
said Rep. John Spratt, D-S.C.
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   The debt bill is H.R. 4601.
</P>
<P>
   The Medicare bill is H.R. 3859.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Congress: http://thomas.loc.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
