<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 17:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SUNY board approves $1.7 billion state university budget  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - The State University of New York board
approved a budget Tuesday calling for its 64 campuses to spend $1.7
billion in the next year, and projecting that enrollment will climb
by 3,000 students.
</P>
<P>
   The budget contains a state funding increase of $80 million
allocated by Gov. George Pataki and the state Legislature as part
of the 2000-01 state budget they agreed to in May.
</P>
<P>
   Among the larger funding increases planned in the next year are
$23.6 million for raises for faculty members, $12 million for
community colleges and $5 million to improve academic quality by
studying campuses' educational missions.
</P>
<P>
   SUNY trustees said 372,443 students were enrolled at SUNY
campuses in the 1999-2000 school year and expect that number to
climb to about 375,500 in 2000-01.
</P>
<P>
   The budget also concludes a three-year phase-in of a plan to
allow campuses in the system to retain all revenues they generate.
That plan, designed to make campuses more innovative and
self-sufficient, will mean $16.8 million more in tuition dollars
for campuses, according to SUNY Chancellor Robert King.
</P>
<P>
   The president of the union representing SUNY faculty, William
Scheuerman of United University Professions, continued Tuesday to
oppose the system's adoption of the system of letting campuses
retain the revenues they generate.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say that will make weak campuses weaker and bring the
stronger, more popular campuses in direct competition with others
in the same system for students.
</P>
<P>
   ''Under the university's budget system, which has been renamed
for the third year in a row, the result remains the same as before:
Most SUNY campuses are left underfunded and shortchanged,''
Scheuerman said.
</P>
<P>
   The union had proposed putting an additional $9.3 million into
funding at the system's campuses.
</P>
<P>
   King fired back that the union's critique of the SUNY budget is
''simply a rehash of arguments lost years ago about campus
budgeting.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The UUP proposal would recreate the old system which
discouraged excellence,'' King said.
</P>
<P>
   Scheuerman also complained that the SUNY board failed to adopt a
plan to erase a $116 million shortfall at its teaching hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   The SUNY trustees approved the financial plan Tuesday at a
meeting at the College at Old Westbury on Long Island.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
