<HEADLINE> Taiwan Looks To Korea on Relations  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The United States repeated its support for
Taiwan-China talks without commenting directly on a new appeal for
a summit by President Chen Shui-bian in Taipei.
</P>
<P>
   At his first news conference since his inauguration a month ago,
Chen said Tuesday that the time was right for a first-ever summit
with the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Koreans have made a historic stride forward,'' Chen said,
referring to a historic summit last week between the peninsula's
Communist North and Democratic south. ''We can also make changes
and create history.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked later Tuesday whether the United States would endorse a
summit, State Department spokesman Richard A. Boucher said: ''Our
view, as we've said before, and I'll say it again now, is that we
strongly support a resumption of the cross-strait dialogue.''
</P>
<P>
   Boucher said the United States is ''committed to promoting
peace, stability and prosperity'' in the region.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is up to Beijing and Taipei to determine the basis for the
dialogue and the modalities for the dialogue.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Secretary of State Madeleine Albright will encourage a
summit when she goes to Beijing later this week, Boucher said
''she'll discuss cross-strait development certainly ... and
reiterate our view that the sides should resume their direct
dialogue.''
</P>
</TEXT>
