<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 17:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawmakers promise to push for lower prescription prices  </HEADLINE>
By ADAM GORLICK
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - Lawmakers who pushed a bill through the
General Assembly expanding the state's prescription drug program
say they're still fighting to lower drug prices.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're engaged in a different kind of drug war,'' Rep.
Christopher Donovan, D-Meriden, said Tuesday. ''People here are
committed to making sure that the senior citizens and every citizen
has the ability to receive the medication they need when the time
is needed.''
</P>
<P>
   A bill passed Monday by the House and Senate would allow about
100,000 low-income people to join a prescription program called
ConnPACE B. The original ConnPace program now covers about 30,000
people.
</P>
<P>
   The ConnPACE program is available only to individuals making
less than $14,200 or couples earning up to $17,100. Under the new
legislation, couples earning about $40,000 would be allowed to
enroll in ConnPACE B.
</P>
<P>
   Those people would have to pay an enrollment fee, but would save
up to 30 percent off the cost of prescription drugs. The enrollment
fee and discount rates still have to be set, and there would be no
co-payment requirements.
</P>
<P>
   While ConnPACE B passed the Legislature, a measure to expand
eligibility for people in the original ConnPACE program was
defeated.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. James Amann, D-Milford, said he and other lawmakers will
try next year to get more people enrolled in the first ConnPACE
program, which charges a $25 joining fee and a $12 co-payment for
prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are people who should be in that program but don't
qualify now because of their income level,'' Amann said. ''We want
to increase eligibility by raising the income caps.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Edith Prague, D-Columbia, said she and others lawmakers
plan to introduce legislation next year which would force
pharmaceutical companies to sell medication to the state at a
deeper discount or face price controls. The proposal will be
modeled after a similar law in Maine, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are people in this state who simply cannot afford to buy
prescription drugs anymore,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   While Prague said pharmaceutical companies are entitled to make
a profit, she also said they have a ''social responsibility'' to
charge reasonable prices.
</P>
<P>
   But the companies say price control will only hurt the people
who need medication, and insist rising drug prices should be
reigned in under federal law instead of state statutes.
</P>
<P>
   ''Price control laws don't take into account the rapid surge in
cost of research and development,'' said Jeff Trewhitt, a spokesman
with the Washington, D.C.-based Pharmaceutical Research and
Manufacturers of America, which represents Pfizer and some other
Connecticut drug producers.
</P>
<P>
   ''The federal government needs to expand its drug coverage
instead of having states set price controls,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-20-00 1740 </TRAILER>
