<DOCNO> APW20000620.0146 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Government proposes plan to combat predatory lending  </HEADLINE>
By MARCY GORDON
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) - The government, citing growing abuses by some
mortgage lenders, is proposing that companies making high-cost
loans be required to give borrowers more accurate data on costs and
terms.
</P>
<P>
   A report on so-called predatory lending released Tuesday by the
departments of Treasury and Housing and Urban Development also
recommends legislation to ban practices such as loan ''flipping''
and to restrict prepayment penalties. In flipping, lenders
constantly refinance mortgage loans to generate fees for brokers,
with little benefit to the borrower.
</P>
<P>
   The report warned that predatory lending, in which companies
seek low-income and minority borrowers and charge them what are
considered unfairly high interest rates and fees, jeopardizes
recent gains in revitalizing neighborhoods and expanding home
ownership.
</P>
<P>
   ''For millions of Americans, a home is the sole financial
asset,'' said Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers, who appeared
with HUD Secretary Andrew Cuomo at a news conference. ''Predatory
lending ... blights our nation's cities and rural areas.''
</P>
<P>
   A task force of the two agencies ''learned about some practices
that are clearly abusive'' during recent public hearings across the
country, the report says.
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, the consequences for the borrowers - especially
losing their homes in foreclosure - have been ''disastrous,'' it
says.
</P>
<P>
   ''In many neighborhoods, these abusive practices threaten to
erode the enormous progress that has been made over the past
several years in revitalizing neighborhoods and expanding home
ownership,'' the report says.
</P>
<P>
   The report also recommends:
</P>
<P>
   -Lenders should be required to recommend home mortgage
counseling to people applying for high-cost loans.
</P>
<P>
   -Mortgage brokers should be required to demonstrate the
appropriateness of a loan for an applicant.
</P>
<P>
   -Lump-sum credit life insurance should be banned on all mortgage
loans.
</P>
<P>
   The high-cost mortgage loans, while legal, have increasingly
drawn criticism. Democratic lawmakers in April proposed legislation
aimed at curbing predatory lending by limiting to 3 percent of a
loan the total amount of points, fees and prepayment penalties.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has endorsed the proposal, but a lack
of Republican support weakens its prospects for passage by the
GOP-controlled Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The task force heard many complaints from consumer advocates and
individuals about ''aggressive door-to-door solicitation that
prompts some borrowers who never would have sought loans on their
own initiative'' to agree to mortgages with ''oppressive'' terms,
the report says.
</P>
<P>
   An example of such terms is the case of an 84-year-old widow
from Rochester, N.Y., who was persuaded by salesmen to buy more
than $20,000 in new windows. Under the loan, she would have to pay
more than $72,000 over 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   The financing deal, secured by a mortgage on her $50,000 home,
was signed at the hospital where she was medicated and recovering
from a stroke and breast cancer. Her home is in foreclosure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-20-00 1749 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000620.0148 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Environmentalists, shippers at odds over Delaware River project  </HEADLINE>
By BRENDAN SCHURR
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) - On the surface, it seems like the most
boring of issues - river muck. But a plan to deepen the Delaware
River has emotions running high because it's really about health,
the environment, jobs and money.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Army Corps of Engineers, with the backing of the
Delaware River Port Authority, plans to deepen 108 miles of the
river to 45 feet, from its current depth of 40 feet. That will
allow ships to carry more cargo - from fruit to paper products to
oil - to the Port of Camden and Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   The port authority and shippers say this is crucial to keep the
East coast's largest port open and to continue to attract ships.
But environmentalists say the project is unnecessary, wasteful and
dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   Several congressmen from New Jersey have asked the federal
government's General Accounting Office to investigate the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Many cargo ships, when fully loaded, draw too much water to
enter the Delaware River. They stop in the Delaware Bay and unload
some of their cargo onto smaller vessels, which bring it up the
river.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we have a deeper river, we dramatically decrease that,''
said Joe Diemer, spokesman for the Delaware River Port Authority.
</P>
<P>
   The project would deepen the river from its mouth at the
Delaware Bay to Camden and Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Diemer said shipping companies are demanding that they be able
to send full ship loads up the river.
</P>
<P>
   The shipping companies, as they have at other ports, have
threatened to take their cargo elsewhere if the river isn't
deepened, which would affect the 54,000 jobs that are related to
the port, Diemer said.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are more jobs associated with the port here than in
other port areas because so much of what moves in and out of here
moves on trucks,'' he said. ''When a fruit ship comes in, there are
hundreds of trucks lined up to take the fruit and get it to
supermarkets. The same with steel and other cargoes.''
</P>
<P>
   Similar threats were made by shippers using the ports of Newark
and Elizabeth. A project is under way to deepen the Kill Van Kull
and Newark Bay channels, which lead to the ports.
</P>
<P>
   But a coalition of environmental groups, led by the Delaware
Riverkeeper Network, has been working to stop the Delaware River
project.
</P>
<P>
   The groups maintain that the deepening project would not benefit
shippers because new container ships being built to carry more
cargo require a depth of at least 50 feet.
</P>
<P>
   ''Going to 45 feet gets you nothing,'' said Maya van Rossum,
executive director of the Riverkeeper Network.
</P>
<P>
   But Rich DeGennaro, chairman of the board of the Maritime
Exchange for the Delaware River and Bay, which represents shippers
and terminal operators, said the ''super-modern'' ships that draw
50 feet will not be ''calling on the Port of Philadelphia anytime
soon.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We think 45 feet is a realistic goal for us at this time. It
will accommodate more of the modern ships than 40 feet will, but
not necessarily the super-modern ships,'' DeGennaro said.
</P>
<P>
   The environmental network also says that in order for the six
oil companies on the Delaware to accommodate the more deeply loaded
ships that could navigate a 45-foot deep channel, they would have
to deepen their own berths. Only two have committed to doing that.
</P>
<P>
   DeGennaro said that's not a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ''We feel that when the channel is deepened, that they will all
ultimately find that the economics are compelling to deepen their
berths,'' he said, adding that they've been ''reluctant to commit
funds when it's still not clear that the deepening of the channel
is going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The Riverkeeper Network also says that by stirring up sediment,
toxins at the river bottom will be disturbed and could harm sea
life and groundwater.
</P>
<P>
   ''We might be getting ourselves into real trouble, threatening
peoples' drinking water supplies, threatening the recovering oyster
population and reintroducing toxins into the food chain,'' said van
Rossum.
</P>
<P>
   The Army Corps says levels of toxins in the river sediment are
not high enough to damage the environment.
</P>
<P>
   The Port Authority, Diemer said, won't do anything that will
cause environmental harm. ''That's an absolute given,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Also at issue is what to do with the 22 million cubic yards of
sediment that would be dredged. Plans call for it to be used to
restore beaches along the river and Delaware Bay in Delaware and
New Jersey, Diemer said.
</P>
<P>
   The Port Authority also is negotiating with companies that want
the material, which can be used for highway fill and construction
projects, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Port Authority also is exploring using the material to fill
some abandoned mines in Pennsylvania, Diemer said.
</P>
<P>
   The Army Corps will store any contaminated material in a secure
landfill, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Army Corps of Engineers can begin the project, it
must sign a financial agreement with the Port Authority. Ed Voigt,
spokesman for the Army Corps in the Philadelphia district, said
negotiations are in the final phase.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposal, the federal government would fund about
two-thirds of the $311 million project and the Port Authority would
pay about one-third, with contributions from New Jersey,
Pennsylvania and Delaware.
</P>
<P>
   The bill that provides a portion of the funding has been
approved by the House of Representatives and must be considered by
the Senate, said Rich McGrath, spokesman for Sen. Robert
Torricelli.
</P>
<P>
   The Army Corps also needs an environmental permit from the state
of Delaware before it can proceed.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Rob Andrews and Torricelli, both D-N.J., have asked
the Government Accounting Office to investigate the project. Reps.
Jim Saxton and Frank LoBiondo, both R-N.J., support the probe.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Sagnip, spokesman for Saxton, said the accounting office
has not decided whether it will study the plan.
</P>
<P>
   A New Jersey Senate committee has held back a $13 million
funding bill that would have contributed to the deepening project.
Senators said they were concerned about releasing state money as
congressional support for an investigation into the project
increased.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the Port Authority and shippers are steadfast in
their support of it.
</P>
<P>
   Said Diemer: ''We can't compete in the 21st century with a
shipping channel that dates back to World War II.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: www.nap.usace.army.mil
</P>
<P>
   www.delawareriverkeeper.org
</P>
<P>
   www.drpa.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
