<HEADLINE> No verdict after first full day of deliberations  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) - The jurors considering the federal tax
case against Albert Pirro, husband of the Westchester district
attorney, spent Tuesday closeted with a mountain of evidence,
emerging only when they announced they were done for the day.
</P>
<P>
   In their first full day of deliberations, the jurors offered few
clues about their thinking. They asked for extra copies of the
indictment and for help finding Albert Pirro's appointment
calendars and some tax returns among the thousands of documents at
their disposal.
</P>
<P>
   Pirro and his brother Anthony, who was his accountant, are
accused of cheating on Albert Pirro's taxes by hiding income and
taking improper business deductions for personal items, ranging
from veterinarian bills to a $123,000 Ferrari. Tax agents used the
appointment calendars to help decide whether expenses were
business-related.
</P>
<P>
   The jury issued one note at about 4:45 p.m., which brought the
defendants, their lawyers and their wives - including District
Attorney Jeanine Pirro - scurrying into the courtroom. But it
amounted to a request to be dismissed for the day, which Judge
Barrington Parker granted.
</P>
<P>
   Jeanine Pirro said afterward that the wait for the verdict was
not nerve-racking because ''My work keeps me busy.''
</P>
<P>
   Albert Pirro, too, said the wait is ''not going to be the
greatest challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I've got my family, I've got God and I've got my friends,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Deliberations are scheduled to resume at 9 a.m. Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
