<HEADLINE> ABC Slips in Ratings  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID BAUDER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- ''Survivor'' continues to build as the
television event of the summer, but there were enough NBA
basketball fans to give NBC a weekly win in the prime-time ratings
race.
</P>
<P>
   The two NBA Finals games between the Los Angeles Lakers and
Indiana Pacers were among the 10 most popular shows last week,
Nielsen Media Research said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   For the second week in a row, ''Survivor'' was the most-watched
program among viewers aged 18-to-34, normally an audience the
older-skewing CBS has a lot of trouble reaching.
</P>
<P>
   Viewership for the reality show with strangers marooned on a
tropical island has grown each of the three weeks it has been on
the air. Without competition from either ''Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire'' or the NBA Finals this week, the numbers are expected
to increase again.
</P>
<P>
   ''Survivor'' also had its own ratings ''halo effect.'' The CBS
movie that followed it on the air June 14, ''Addicted to Love,''
finished among the week's top 10 shows.
</P>
<P>
   The reality TV genre is also doing well in a completely
unexpected place. PBS said preliminary ratings for ''The 1900
House'' during its first two weeks on the air were double what the
public broadcasting system normally gets in prime-time. The show
follows a British family that volunteered to live in a house
equipped only with appliances from a century ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''The 1900 House'' drew an average of 6 million viewers for its
two airings, PBS said.
</P>
<P>
   For the week, NBC had an average of 10.47 million viewers in
prime-time (7.3 rating, 13 share). CBS had 10.41 million viewers
(7.2, 13), ABC had 9.7 million viewers (6.6, 12) and Fox had 5.9
million viewers (4.0, 7).
</P>
<P>
   UPN, buoyed by the continued strong performance of professional
wrestling, had 3.5 million viewers (2.3 rating, 4 share), the WB
had 2.1 million viewers (1.5, 3) and Pax TV had 1.1 million viewers
(0.9, 2).
</P>
<P>
   NBC's ''Nightly News'' won the evening news ratings race with
9.4 million viewers (7.0 rating, 16 share). ABC's ''World News
Tonight'' had 8.6 million viewers (6.5, 15), while the improving
''CBS Evening News'' had 7.8 million viewers (6.0, 13).
</P>
<P>
   A rating point represents 1,008,000 households, or 1 percent of
the nation's estimated 100.8 million TV homes. The share is the
percentage of in-use televisions tuned to a given show.
</P>
<P>
   For the week of June 12-18, the top 10 shows, their networks and
ratings were:
</P>
<P>
   ''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' (Tuesday), ABC, 16.3; ''Who
Wants to Be a Millionaire'' (Sunday), ABC, 15.1; ''Survivor,'' CBS,
14.6; ''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' (Thursday), ABC, 14.5;
''NBA Finals Game 4: L.A. Lakers at Indiana,'' NBC, 13.1; ''48
Hours'' (Monday), CBS, 10.6; ''NBA Finals Game 5: L.A. Lakers at
Indiana,'' NBC, 10.0; ''NBA Finals Tip-Off,'' NBC, 9.0; ''CBS
Wednesday Movie: Addicted to Love,'' CBS, 8.9; ''The Practice,''
ABC, 8.8.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.nielsenmedia.com
</P>
</TEXT>
