<HEADLINE> Key Lockerbie Witness Testifies  </HEADLINE>
By ANTHONY DEUTSCH
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMP ZEIST, Netherlands (AP) -- A key witness in the Lockerbie
bombing trial said Tuesday that he manufactured electronic timers
for the Libya's secret service that were similar to the one used to
blow up Pam Am flight 103.
</P>
<P>
   During seven hours of intense questioning before a special
Scottish court in the Netherlands, Swiss businessman Edwin Bollier
of MEBO AG said his company delivered to Libya at least 20 timers,
called the MST13, prior to Dec. 21, 1988, the date of the plane
bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say the custom-designed piece of electronic
equipment detonated an explosive that blasted a small hole in the
side of the New York-bound jetliner. The plane plunged six miles,
spreading debris over the town of Lockerbie. All 259 passengers and
11 people on the ground were killed.
</P>
<P>
   At the prosecution's request, Bollier peered through a
magnifying glass at a fragment of electronic circuit board used for
timers that was found among the rubble after the crash.
</P>
<P>
   ''It looks like our timer ... but I can't be 100 percent sure,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   His testimony came in the case against Libyans Abdel Basset Ali
al-Megrahi and Lamen Khalifa Fhimah, who have been charged with
mass murder for the crash.
</P>
<P>
   Bollier first suggested that another company had stolen the
blueprints for the MST13, but later agreed that it was improbable.
</P>
<P>
   Bollier said he personally delivered timers to the Libyan
embassy in former East Germany and gave others to the East German
secret service, the Stasi.
</P>
<P>
   He said he had frequently visited Libya in the mid-1980s, where
he met with one of the accused.
</P>
<P>
   He identified al-Megrahi, describing him as a ''high-ranking
official'' in the Libyan military. ''It's the one without the
glasses,'' he said, pointing to him.
</P>
<P>
   Bollier said he had spent three days with other high-ranking
military officials testing the timers at an isolated military camp
in the Libyan desert near Shiba.
</P>
<P>
   ''I saw what these timers were being used for,'' he said. They
were intended for bombs to be dropped from military aircraft and
mechanisms used to destroy abandoned military bases, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bollier suggested that the evidence he was shown by prosecutors
on Tuesday had been tampered with since he gave written testimony
to police investigators after the crash.
</P>
<P>
   ''They have been modified,'' he said, viewing the piece of
circuit board and an electronic chip found in the wreckage that was
blown across more than 800 square miles of Scotland. ''I swear they
have been modified.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
