<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France May Cut Presidential Term  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- French lawmakers on Tuesday overwhelmingly adopted
a proposed reform that would cut the presidential term from seven
to five years, the most significant constitutional change in nearly
three decades.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal would diminish the political weight of France's
most powerful office, but the public seemed unfazed.
</P>
<P>
   Voters, who in recent years have adopted their own way of
neutralizing presidential power, have shown very little interest in
the issue. By contrast, the proposed move has aroused political
passions among both leftists and conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   The National Assembly vote was 466 for the proposal and 28
opposed.
</P>
<P>
   Deputies from the Communist Party, which has complained that the
issue was not adequately debated, abstained.
</P>
<P>
   The bill will go before the Senate in late September. President
Jacques Chirac then must decide whether to hold a referendum on
changing the constitution or convene a special Congress of both
legislative branches to approve the reform.
</P>
<P>
   Chirac's own party is divided on how to approve the change. Some
party members favor a referendum. Others say a Congress would be
the quickest, surest way to approve the measure.
</P>
<P>
   ''Your vote allows one to hope that this important reform will
take place,'' Justice Minister Elisabeth Guigou said in
congratulating parliament for adopting the measure.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents say the reform could upset the balance that currently
often results in a president of one party serving at the same time
as a government of another. Those in favor of the measure say it
will make for more efficient governing.
</P>
<P>
   French presidents can serve two consecutive terms, or 14 years,
which reform advocates say is too long.
</P>
<P>
   Under the current system, presidents are elected every seven
years, the parliament every five. In recent years, voters have
tended to sanction sitting presidents by electing a parliament of
the opposing party.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called ''cohabitation'' serves as a check to the
president's vast powers by requiring him to serve alongside a
government from the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Opinion polls show that French easily would approve the change
in a referendum.
</P>
<P>
   The measure has wide support among the Socialists, who hold a
comfortable majority in parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Chirac had opposed the measure, but recently also came out in
favor of it.
</P>
<P>
   If approved, the new presidential term would take effect
following presidential elections in 2002.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-20-00 1825 </TRAILER>
