<HEADLINE> ABC News Out of Campaign Pool  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID BAUDER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- ABC News has pulled out of a pool arrangement
where three networks had shared camera coverage of Vice President
Al Gore and Texas Gov. George W. Bush, citing cost concerns.
</P>
<P>
   The network, whose executives outlined political plans at a news
conference Tuesday, said the withdrawal did not indicate the
commitment to follow the campaign had lessened.
</P>
<P>
   ABC had joined with CBS and Fox News Channel to share camera
coverage of the campaign. But with interest in the candidates at an
ebb now and relatively few public appearances, ABC found it wasn't
worth the expense, spokeswoman Su-Lin Nichols said.
</P>
<P>
   ABC is using its own cameras to cover some events and relying on
affiliate stations for others, she said. The network currently has
just one producer, without a correspondent or camera crew,
traveling full-time with each candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Withdrawing from the pool means ABC could miss a breaking news
event. It was unclear whether the network would rejoin the pool
later in the campaign or rely on its own resources, Nichols said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's by no means a lack of commitment to cover the campaign,''
said Marc Burstein, ABC executive producer. ''It's an increase in
the commitment to cover the campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   ABC said Tuesday it has invited Gore and Bush to participate in
a one-on-one televised conversation shortly after Labor Day. The
network said it wanted as little participation as possible from a
moderator so the event doesn't look like a formal debate.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the probable Democratic and Republican presidential
candidates have only agreed to participate in three fall debates
sponsored by the Commission on Presidential Debates. ABC News
President David Westin said he hoped ABC's unusual idea would
appeal to them.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you can have them talk to each other directly, it will
become less adversarial and less debate-like,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Campaigns keep such tight control on all aspects of personal
appearances that Westin's idea might be a tough sell, ABC anchor
Peter Jennings said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think they would accept an empty room with merely them
in it,'' Jennings said. Still, he said ''there are ways to do that
where the facilitator can be a shadow rather than a player.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Texas governor said Bush, who debated 12
times during his primary campaign, will likely debate Gore but
nothing has been set. Ari Fleischer noted many organizations have
submitted proposals, and ABC also has asked for a debate to be
televised on ''This Week''
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign did not immediately return a call for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Westin also said the network may legally challenge
the Federal Communications Commission if it is not permitted to run
lengthy profiles of Bush and Gore this fall without offering equal
time to minor party candidates for president.
</P>
<P>
   The network wants to run prime-time profiles modeled somewhat
after A&AMP;E's ''Biography'' series. But Westin said its lawyers are
worried that the FCC will argue that ABC should do the same for Pat
Buchanan, Ralph Nader and other candidates.
</P>
<P>
   FCC spokesman Bobby Baker said the commission has given
television networks several exemptions to the equal time rules to
fit their formats. By coincidence, on Tuesday the FCC ruled that
''Biography'' would not be subject to the rules.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-20-00 1835 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000620.0158 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prescription Bill Caught in Politics  </HEADLINE>
by 
V0399-----
r w *1153AP-Prescription-Po     06-20 0864
*1153 AP-Prescription-Politics,0863   
Prescription Bill Caught in Politics   
An AP News Analysis
By DAVID ESPO
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Partisan maneuvering is ascendant in Congress'
struggle over prescription drug insurance for Medicare recipients,
clouding prospects for a compromise that could reach President
Clinton's desk in the current campaign season.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is imperative that Republicans hang together on this issue
and pass a bill,'' pollster Glen Bolger recently advised the House
GOP rank and file. ''It is helpful if we can be bipartisan in our
approach,'' according to his script, a copy of which has circulated
widely in the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   By Bolger's accounting, the issue is a critical one for swing
groups in the fall elections, including rural residents and several
categories of women voters.
</P>
<P>
   ''Message: I care, (but say it better than that)'' Bolger
instructed Republicans last week. ''It is more important to
communicate that you have a plan as it is to communicate what is in
the plan.''
</P>
<P>
   As if on cue, Republicans are following the script. They've
drafted legislation, enlisted two conservative Democrats to join
them, and declared the result to be a ''House Bipartisan
Prescription Drug Plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Passage in the narrowly divided House remains a challenge, and
the GOP leadership's timetable for a vote on the House floor in 10
days is ambitious. There's scattered grumbling about the $40
billion price tag and also about a provision that makes the
government the insurer of last resort in a plan that otherwise
relies on private insurance companies to offer insurance to
Medicare recipients.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the GOP leadership can round up the votes for the House
bill, progress in the Senate is unclear. But House Republican
officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, say they will have
accomplished a primary political goal: pushing a bill through the
House, and thus permitting the rank and file to tell the voters
they did what they could.
</P>
<P>
   Not if House Democrats can help it.
</P>
<P>
   Eager to regain control of the House for the first time since
they lost it in 1994, they are matching the Republicans move for
move. For them, it's a matter of holding onto their historic
partisan advantage on Medicare -- an edge in the range of 20
percentage points in recent polling.
</P>
<P>
   ''We can understand the Republican proposal if we remember their
attitude towards Medicare,'' House Democratic Leader Dick Gephardt
said in a statement last week. ''They hate it.
</P>
<P>
   ''They fought its creation and have been trying to do away with
it ever since,'' the Missouri Democrat added, previewing rhetoric
likely to reemerge when the bill comes up for debate.
</P>
<P>
   When Republicans sought bipartisan support for their bill,
Gephardt sought to discourage it, in keeping with his strategic
plan of denying the GOP legislative accomplishments wherever
possible.
</P>
<P>
   Several Democratic sources, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said that in a series of private conversations and meetings, the
party leader stressed the need to hang together behind a different
approach for making drug coverage available to Medicare recipients.
</P>
<P>
   This time -- unlike a bill last month to repeal the estate tax,
where dozens of Democrats defected -- only Reps. Collin Peterson of
Minnesota and Ralph Hall of Texas have joined forces with the
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Gephardt and Senate Democratic Leader Tom Daschle
journeyed to the White House to join President Clinton in
criticizing the Republican approach. House Democrats have helped
arrange a string of public events, all designed to raise doubts
about the GOP effort.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent came Tuesday, when Public Citizen accused the
pharmaceutical industry of setting up a ''front group'' to air
commercials critical of Clinton's plan to offer prescription drug
insurance as a new benefit under Medicare. Despite the name,
Citizens For Better Medicare, ''they are not citizens and they are
not for better Medicare,'' said Rep. Tom Allen, D-Maine.
</P>
<P>
   And when Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., made a public statement
recently supporting the Republican bill, Democrats pointed out that
his remarks bore an uncanny resemblance to wording proposed by
Bolger, the Republican pollster.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is unsettled in the Senate, Majority Leader Trent
Lott, R-Miss., told reporters on Tuesday, although lawmakers in
both parties say legislation could yet emerge in the final days of
the congressional session.
</P>
<P>
   But there, too, political imperatives are at work.
</P>
<P>
   Several sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, say
Democrats are eager to bring the issue up quickly -- possibly as an
amendment on unrelated legislation. That would allow them the
chance to place their stamp on a politically important issue.
</P>
<P>
   Bipartisan efforts persist, including one involving Sen. Ron
Wyden, D-Ore., who says a compromise is readily available.
</P>
<P>
   But he, too, received a call recently from Gephardt. The
message, Wyden said, was ''set the bar high,'' and avoid
compromising too easily.
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   Eds: David Espo is AP's chief congressional correspondent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
