<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New tests all negative for mosquito viruses  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - The latest tests of Connecticut's
mosquitoes and dead birds showed no trace of the West Nile-like
strain of the encephalitis virus, state environmental officials
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The mosquitoes also tested negative for Eastern Equine
Encephalitis, the Department of Environmental Protection reported.
</P>
<P>
   For the week of June 20, 3,995 mosquitoes have been tested from
43 sites statewide. As of June 16, 45 birds tested negative for the
West Nile-like strain of encephalitis.
</P>
<P>
   Mosquito traps placed by the Connecticut Agricultural Experiment
Station in 73 locations will be collected on a 10-day rotation.
Trapping began June 1 and will continue through early fall.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, New York announced that two crows tested
positive for the West Nile-like strain of the virus. Another crow
tested positive for the virus in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The virus has not caused any human illness in Connecticut, but
last year infected 72 people in New York, killing seven.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
