<HEADLINE> Mass. man charged with fraud for allegedly impersonating Sioux heir </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BOSTON (AP) - A Massachusetts man bilked people out of more than
$200,000 by falsely claiming he was the descendent of a Sioux chief
with access to an enormous trust fund, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Hacker, 34, formerly of Watertown, Newton and Wakefield
was arrested in New York on June 8. An indictment alleging fraud
and other charges was unsealed Tuesday in Boston, U.S. Attorney
Donald K. Stern said.
</P>
<P>
   Hacker allegedly defrauded a Boston area investment adviser, a
travel agent and Charles Schwab &AMP; Co. by saying he was incredibly
wealthy but had a short-term cash flow problem.
</P>
<P>
   Hacker told his victims he was the beneficiary of a family trust
worth hundreds of millions of dollars set up in the 1860s by an
ancestor, a former Sioux chief, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   He told his victims he was in the process of gaining access to
the trust and he needed loans for day-to-day expenses, Stern said.
He lured them with counterfeit checks worth millions of dollars
made out to organizations with which the victims were affiliated,
Stern said.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities allege Hacker used the money to pay for an
extravagant lifestyle that included limousine rides and stays at
the best hotels in Boston and New York.
</P>
<P>
   He also deposited more than $400,000 in personal checks into a
trading account with Charles Schwab, prosecutors said. The company
executed trades on the account before discovering the checks were
worthless.
</P>
<P>
   Hacker faces mail and wire fraud charges that carry a maximum
sentence of five years in prison and a $250,000 fine. He also faces
false check and counterfeit securities charges that carry a maximum
penalty of 10 years in prison and a $250,000 fine.
</P>
</TEXT>
