<HEADLINE> New owner gives up on USBL's Atlantic City Seagulls, citing attendance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) - A plastic surgeon who bought the
Atlantic City Seagulls basketball team last year is throwing in the
towel after one season, citing poor attendance and lack of
community support.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Ira Trocki planned to sell or move the team after its final
game Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''The team is not going to be in Atlantic City,'' he told The
Press of Atlantic City. ''It's final. Obviously, the community
doesn't care. The community is going to lose the team. You're not
going to have family entertainment.''
</P>
<P>
   Trocki bought the United States Basketball League team from
owner Ken Gross last November, hoping a move and a new marketing
program would help improve attendance, which averaged 989 per game
last year.
</P>
<P>
   The team opened the season playing at Convention Hall, on the
Boardwalk, drawing 836 on opening night. But poor attendance
prompted Trocki to move the games back to Atlantic City High
School. Recently, attendance has dropped under 100 people a game.
</P>
<P>
   ''We thought 800 people for the opener was bad, but 100 people?
That's an embarrassment. In this community, the USBL is a
failure,'' Trocki said.
</P>
</TEXT>
