<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House Panel Nixes Foreign Aid Change  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A House panel decided Tuesday against changing
the formula for dispersing foreign aid to Israel to protest
Israel's plans to sell China a spy plane.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the House Appropriations subcommittee on foreign
operations approved by voice vote a $13.3 billion foreign aid bill
for the fiscal year that begins on Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The bill permits the full $2.8 billion in foreign aid to go to
Israel, and to be dispersed early, as is the practice.
</P>
<P>
   Some congressional conservatives have suggested a $250 million
cut to Israel to match the sale price of an Israeli-made advanced
airborne early warning system to China.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the House panel, Rep. Sonny Callahan, R-Ala.,
had offered an initial version of the legislation that would not
have allowed any of the $2.8 billion for Israel to be dispersed
early.
</P>
<P>
   Callahan protested both the sale of the AWACS-like spy plane,
and the tradition under which Israel -- the largest single recipient
of American foreign aid -- gets its share up front at the start of
each fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   Other countries must wait longer to get the money.
</P>
<P>
   ''Israel ought to be ashamed of themselves for doing this, or
putting us in this position,'' Callahan said.
</P>
<P>
   But a proposal by Reps. David Obey, D-Wis., and Jack Kingston,
R-Ga, providing early disbursement for the entire amount passed by
voice vote.
</P>
<P>
   That came after an amendment by Callahan was defeated 9 to 6
that would have allowed all of it but $250 million to go to Israel
early.
</P>
<P>
   The bill next goes to the full House Appropriations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate, meanwhile, also took up its version of the foreign
aid bill late Tuesday, but held no votes. The Senate was to resume
debate on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate bill in its current from does not seek to penalize
Israel for the proposed radar-system sale to Israel. But some
conservatives, including Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., chairman of the
Foreign Relations Committee, have proposed that the fund be
withheld.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Eds: The Senate foreign aid appropriations bill is S 2522. The
House version does not yet have a number.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
