<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Jersey beats FEMA audit  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - New Jersey beat its lone Federal Emergency
Management Agency audit over a $183,000 underwater cable.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey Transit had requested a total of $4.8 million to
repair buildings and damaged equipment after a December 1992
nor'easter.
</P>
<P>
   Part of that included an underwater signal cable near the Jersey
coast that state officials said was damaged by the storm's high
tides.
</P>
<P>
   The cable was used to operate warning signals for train
crossings over a Monmouth County drawbridge.
</P>
<P>
   But FEMA officials contended that the cable was not damaged
during the storm. Agency officials said evidence showed that it was
malfunctioning before the storm. They cited two incidents in July
and August 1992 when the signal failed to work properly.
</P>
<P>
   ''In our opinion the broken wires did not result from the storm,
but instead from a lack of flexibility of the cable,'' FEMA
officials wrote in their audit.
</P>
<P>
   The state appealed the audit and won, according to Michael
Klufas, NJ Transit spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the end, what they said was that we were correct in saying
it was storm-related damage,'' said Klufas. ''They withdrew the
audit. We owe them nothing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
