<HEADLINE> Peru Opposition Leader Demands Vote  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru (AP) -- Unsuccessful presidential candidate Alejandro
Toledo reiterated his demand for new elections Tuesday after
meeting with a delegation from the Organization of American States.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo said he stressed the opposition's position for ''the need
to convene new free, clean elections, supervised by the OAS.''
</P>
<P>
   Toledo boycotted the May 28 presidential runoff, claiming it was
rigged in favor of President Alberto Fujimori, who won an
unprecedented third five-year term.
</P>
<P>
   The delegation, led by Peter Boehm, Canada's permanent
representative to the OAS, arrived here Monday to lay the
groundwork for a visit next week by OAS Secretary General Cesar
Gaviria and Canadian Foreign Affairs Minister Lloyd Axworthy.
</P>
<P>
   An OAS election mission refused to monitor last month's runoff
vote, saying the election was ''far from what could be considered
free or fair.''
</P>
<P>
   But the 34-member nations later rejected calls from the United
States to question Fujimori's win or consider collective sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the OAS is sending Gaviria and Axworthy on June 27 to
work with the government and the opposition to strengthen
democratic institutions.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: http://csd.queensu.ca/peru2000/
</P>
