<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chechen Rebels Kill Russian Soldier  </HEADLINE>
By LYOMA TURPALOV
<TEXT>
<P>
   GUDERMES, Russia (AP) -- Rebels bands tried to storm a key
Russian administration center here, pouring in from surrounding
hills overnight Tuesday and drawing federal troops into scattered
battles, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Fighting erupted in half a dozen spots on the outskirts of
Gudermes, the city that houses the Russian administration in
Chechnya, as rebels apparently tried to break into the city center
and seize government offices, said officials with the Russian
administration.
</P>
<P>
   Russian troops were forced to fire artillery guns to repel the
insurgents, the officials said on condition of anonymity. However,
the fighting appeared confined to the outskirts and central
Gudermes remained quiet. There was no word on casualties.
</P>
<P>
   The raids emphasized how weak the Russians' hold is over the
two-thirds of Chechnya they claim to control. The two sides have
been at a standoff for weeks, apparently unwilling to risk a major
confrontation. But small groups of rebels have faced little
resistance penetrating Russian lines and ambushing federal troops
and pro-Russian Chechen officials.
</P>
<P>
   The overnight clashes came hours before the man Moscow recently
installed as Chechnya's top civilian official, Islamic leader Mufti
Akhmad Kadyrov, arrived in Gudermes to begin work.
</P>
<P>
   Kadyrov's appointment, announced June 12, was resented by both
Kremlin supporters and rebel leaders in Chechnya. Many Chechens
consider Kadyrov, who fought on the rebels' side during the 1994-96
Chechen war and now cooperates with the Kremlin, a turncoat.
</P>
<P>
   But Russia's top spokesman on Chechnya, Sergei Yastrzhembsky,
said Tuesday that Moscow would not reconsider the appointment.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after Kadyrov was officially introduced to his staff
Tuesday, 43 administrative officials resigned in protest, the
Interfax news agency reported. Many of them had threatened
resignation earlier in response to Kadyrov's appointment.
</P>
<P>
   In another of several attacks across Chechnya, rebels killed a
Russian soldier and wounded two others in an ambush Monday night on
a checkpoint in the capital Grozny, Interior Ministry officials
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Russian troops on Tuesday continued shelling suspected rebel
positions in Chechnya's southern mountains. But rain and fog
grounded Russian jets, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians have been depending on their overwhelming firepower
to battle the rebels, while the insurgents have favored hit-and-run
attacks.
</P>
<P>
   The conflict has forced more than 200,000 of Chechen civilians
to flee their homes, most of them seeking shelter in the
neighboring Russian region of Ingushetia.
</P>
<P>
   Russia lost control of Chechnya after independence fighters
expelled Russian forces in 1996. The troops re-entered last
September after Islamic militants based there seized several
villages in the neighboring Russian region of Dagestan, and after
about 300 people died in apartment bombings the government blames
on Chechens.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-20-00 2008 </TRAILER>
