<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Whitman's sixth Supreme Court appointee sworn in  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Two governors praised him. So did attorneys
general past and present.
</P>
<P>
   During his turn at the podium Tuesday, James R. Zazzali said the
time had come to end the high talk.
</P>
<P>
   ''The first thing I have to do here is put aside the nice things
said today and recognize I have a responsibility here,'' the newest
member of the New Jersey Supreme Court said.
</P>
<P>
   That duty is to do justice for the people of New Jersey, Zazzali
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''To render a right and fair decision,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After his swearing in ceremony at Trenton's War Memorial,
Zazzali became Gov. Christie Whitman's sixth appointee and the
third former attorney general she has named to the state Supreme
Court.
</P>
<P>
   At 63, the Rumson resident is also Whitman's oldest appointee.
He will likely retire before his seven-year term expires. He
replaces Associate Justice Daniel O'Hern, who reached the mandatory
retirement age of 70 on May 23.
</P>
<P>
   Zazzali joins Chief Justice Deborah Poritz and Associate Justice
Peter G. Verniero, all former attorneys general nominated by
Whitman.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman's other appointments to the high court are associate
justices Virginia Long, Jaynee LaVecchia and James Coleman.
</P>
<P>
   For the third time this year, Poritz bid goodbye to a member of
her court before welcoming another.
</P>
<P>
   ''He taught us by example to speak with strength and dignity,''
Poritz said of O'Hern. ''He defined us at our best.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitman praised Zazzali for his intelligence and integrity as
well as for his humility and sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think he is ready for the challenge that now confronts
him,'' the governor said.
</P>
<P>
   Zazzali was an assistant prosecutor when former Gov. Brendan T.
Byrne was the Essex County prosecutor. Byrne later named Zazzali
his attorney general in 1981. Zazzali also served as general
counsel to the New Jersey Sports and Exposition Authority under
Byrne.
</P>
<P>
   ''Nobody needs testimonials for Jim Zazzali,'' Byrne said. ''He
is a student of the law. He is just the right person to join the
Supreme Court.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides the chief justice, the six associate justices are
supposed to be evenly split, three Republicans and three Democrats.
Because O'Hern is a Democrat, tradition holds that he be replaced
with someone from the same party.
</P>
<P>
   Zazzali was a commissioner on the State Commission of
Investigation from 1984 to 1994, including a period as chairman.
The SCI is an independent office created by the Legislature to
examine and issue written reports on corruption and policy
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman last year named Zazzali to a search committee to find
candidates for state police superintendent. He also headed a
coalition of six former state attorneys general who supported
former Attorney General Peter Verniero's hotly contested nomination
to the high court.
</P>
<P>
   Recently a partner in the Newark law firm Zazzali, Zazzali,
Fagella &AMP; Nowak with his brother, Andrew Zazzali, Zazzali graduated
from Georgetown University in 1958 and earned a law degree there in
1962.
</P>
<P>
   Zazzali said he would dedicate his years on the bench to his
parents. In 1950, Zazzali's father, who was close to President
Harry S. Truman, appeared headed for appointment as a federal
judge.
</P>
<P>
   But the nomination was torpedoed by partisan politics after
Zazzali, then 12 years old, told a reporter his father had Truman's
backing, Zazzali said.
</P>
<P>
   ''He never mentioned the incident to me for the rest of his
life,'' Zazzali said. ''Today represents the vindication of a
father and the redemption of a son.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-20-00 2010 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000620.0174 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fiji Crisis Heads Toward End  </HEADLINE>
By STEVEN GUTKIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUVA, Fiji (AP) -- Even if the political standoff in Fiji ends
peacefully, as now appears likely, the South Pacific nation may
still pay a high price for permitting an armed gang to topple a
democratically elected government by taking it hostage.
</P>
<P>
   The country's new military rulers and the gunmen holding the
former government hostage inside parliament entered their third
straight day of negotiations Tuesday to form an interim regime that
would presumably guide the country to elections within two years.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides insist the negotiations are going well, and that the
31 hostages -- including former Prime Minister Mahendra Chaudhry --
will likely be released within days.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the hostage takers, Jo Nata, told The Associated
Press on Wednesday that ''a preliminary accord has been drafted and
has been gone through by lawyers and all the parties, and could be
signed by this afternoon.''
</P>
<P>
   But Nata refused to give a time table for the hostages' release,
saying, ''the release of the hostages is not of importance to us.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision to sack both the prime minister and Fiji's 1997
constitution has caused alarm among those who see it as a triumph
for racism and coup-making.
</P>
<P>
   ''The power of the gun must not be allowed to dictate policy,''
said an editorial Tuesday by The Fiji Times newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Yet reinstating the deposed prime minister -- the first ethnic
Indian to hold that post in a nation where most people are
indigenous Fijian -- isn't even on the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Fiji's power brokers are haggling over how to implement
the demands of George Speight -- the man who, a year after being
fired by the Chaudhry government as a timber-industry
administrator, led the May 19 armed takeover of parliament amid
widespread looting and street violence.
</P>
<P>
   The most controversial of Speight's demands, that political
power be wrested from Fiji's relatively well-off Indian minority,
has been watered down somewhat. On Monday, Speight told reporters
he'd be willing to allow a few Indians in the interim government.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Fiji is already well on its way to pariah status in the
international community, no matter the makeup of a new government
whose legitimacy will likely be questioned from the outset.
</P>
<P>
   The military took control of Fiji and imposed martial law 10
days after Speight's raid. Military commander Commodore Frank
Bainimarama has announced a plan to restore civilian rule by
appointing an interim administration to oversee a recasting of the
constitution and hold elections within two years.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, Australia and New Zealand have said they will
slap sanctions on Fiji, a cluster of islands 2,250 miles northeast
of Sydney, Australia, if it does not return to full democracy.
</P>
<P>
   The country is already losing millions of dollars a day in lost
tourism revenue and the refusal by Australian unions to handle
cargo to and from Fiji -- cutting off the country's sizable garment
industry from its principal market.
</P>
<P>
   Just how Fiji, a supposedly idyllic island paradise, descended
into ethnic turmoil is a story of intrigue and intolerance.
</P>
<P>
   Speight and his followers said their armed takeover of
parliament was to restore dignity to the Fijian majority, whose
rights, they said, had been trampled upon by an arrogant Chaudhry
administration.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is the country's conflict has as much to do with power
and privilege as Fijian nationalism.
</P>
<P>
   Some say Speight is a front man for Fijians who lost their
ability to make sweetheart deals under Chaudhry, especially in the
country's lucrative timber and sugar industries.
</P>
<P>
   Most troubling to Chaudhry opponents was the former prime
minister's refusal to accept higher rents charged to Indian sugar
farmers on land communally owned by indigenous Fijians.
</P>
<P>
   Speight's coup might do more harm to the sugar industry than
anything Chaudhry could devise, however. The European Union is
reportedly considering canceling a trade agreement under which it
pays Fiji up to three times the market price for sugar.
</P>
<P>
   And sugar growers, many of whom are sympathetic to Chaudhry, are
boycotting this year's harvest until the hostages are released.
</P>
<P>
   Fiji's new public face -- military roadblocks, a dawn-to-dusk
curfew, burnt out and sacked buildings, a refugee camp full of
badgered Indians -- augurs poorly for a quick recovery of the
tourism industry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-20-00 2011 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000620.0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bond Denied for Former Army Colonel  </HEADLINE>
By PAT LEISNER
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. (AP) -- A former Army officer accused of spying for
the Soviet Union and Russia for 25 years was ordered held without
bond Tuesday after prosecutors disclosed details of videotaped
evidence against him.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said retired Army Reserve Col. George Trofimoff, who
was a civilian intelligence employee, was captured on one tape
putting his hand to his heart and telling an undercover agent
posing as a Russian agent: ''I'm not American in here.''
</P>
<P>
   Trofimoff, 73, the highest-ranking American military officer
ever charged with spying, could face life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Court-appointed attorney Daniel Hernandez argued for bail,
pointing out that Trofimoff has retired to Melbourne, Fla., and
works as grocery store bagger. He also said Trofimoff has no
passport and has suffered a mini-stroke in the past.
</P>
<P>
   But U.S. Magistrate Mark A. Pizzo said the government presented
overwhelming evidence and ordered Trofimoff held without bond.
Trofimoff's wife, Jutta, sat behind him at the two-hour hearing and
later refused to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Trofimoff, born in Germany to Russian emigres, became a
naturalized U.S. citizen in 1951, joined the Army in 1953 and was
honorably discharged three years later, although he rose to colonel
in the reserves. He was hired as a civilian in Army intelligence in
1959.
</P>
<P>
   From 1969 until 1994, Trofimoff was a civilian chief of an Army
installation in West Germany where refugees and defectors from the
Soviet bloc were interrogated.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutor Terry Furr said Trofimoff collected $300,000 for
photographing volumes of secret U.S. intelligence documents and
giving them to the KGB through a go-between, boyhood friend Igor
Vladimirovich Susemihl, a Russian Orthodox priest.
</P>
<P>
   Furr told the judge the government had a videotape of a six-hour
meeting at a Melbourne hotel in 1999 of an undercover agent and
Trofimoff discussing ''in great detail the entire scope of his work
for the Soviet Union.''
</P>
<P>
   Trofimoff allegedly said he would sometimes work overnight
photographing documents. ''He said 'If I had it, you got it,' and
he said it proudly,'' Furr said.
</P>
<P>
   Furr also said Trofimoff told the undercover agent that if he
were ever caught: ''I will swear on a stack of Bibles I didn't do
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Trofimoff was arrested last week after meeting in Tampa with an
undercover agent who supposedly was to deliver a long overdue
payment for spying during the Cold War.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-20-00 2012 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000620.0176 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Animal rights groups angry about diving mule  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LACKAWANNA, N.Y. (AP) - Animal rights activists are enraged over
plans to feature a diving mule at an annual summer festival here.
</P>
<P>
   ''The ARA hot line has received a barrage of phone calls from
local citizens embarrassed Lackawanna would choose this event in
the festival,'' said Lori Szewczyk of Animal Rights Advocates of
Western New York.
</P>
<P>
   Szewczyk said many such acts have been cited for poor treatment
of animals and insists the only way the animal would jump is out of
fear.
</P>
<P>
   City recreation director Angelo Iafallo, though, called the
diving mules ''a great attraction.''
</P>
<P>
   City officials said the Tim Rivers World Famous Diving Mule act
has never abused an animal. This year, it will also include a
diving dog and pony.
</P>
<P>
   Szewczyk said her group is considering a protest of the
festival.
</P>
<P>
   ''Mule diving is an unnatural act,'' she said. ''I don't find
that entertaining.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-20-00 2014 </TRAILER>
