<BODY>
<HEADLINE> E. coli Eyed in 4 More Deaths  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- Three elderly people and a young man may be the
latest victims of an E. coli outbreak that has killed at least
seven people and sickened hundreds, said health officials.
</P>
<P>
   Ontario chief coroner Dr. James Young said Tuesday the four
brought to 18 the number of deaths still under investigation as
being possibly caused by the E. coli outbreak in Walkerton, a rural
community of 5,000 people, located 90 miles west of Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   The four additional deaths included a 90-year-old man, an
86-year-old woman, a 96-year-old man and a 25-year-old man.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities have ruled that seven people -- six elderly adults
and a 2-year-old girl -- were killed by E. coli, an intestinal
bacteria usually spread by animal or human feces that causes
diarrhea, nausea, cramps, and in severe cases, kidney failure.
</P>
<P>
   The contamination was the worst known E. coli outbreaks in North
America, and officials have yet to determine what caused it.
</P>
<P>
   Walkerton officials have acknowledged that the town's water
utility knew the water was possibly contaminated several days
before a boil order was issued on May 21. An investigation into the
cause of the contamination continues, with officials focusing on
surface water that contained animal manure and might have entered
two town wells.
</P>
<P>
   One of the wells had a defective chlorinating system, officials
have said.
</P>
<P>
   A boil order for town water was likely to continue for at least
another month. The Ontario Clean Water Agency has assumed control
of the town's water system from the local utility.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
