<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil: $1.7B Plan To Curb Crime  </HEADLINE>
By STAN LEHMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) -- Brazil's government proposed a major
anti-crime package Tuesday that would severely limit gun sales,
hire 2,000 new federal agents, better train and equip police and
improve lighting in neighborhoods across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Aware that it could take months before the bill is approved, the
government decreed a nationwide, six-month ban on gun sales. Other
aspects of the plan require congressional approval.
</P>
<P>
   The 124-step National Security Law would cost Brazil $1.7
billion over three years, President Fernando Henrique Cardoso said
in Brasilia, the capital. He said the plan will not affect his
government's austerity policies, essential in keeping inflation
within current one digit level.
</P>
<P>
   The government proposal is a response to frustration among
Brazilians over rampant crime and recent violence. The murder rates
in the Rio de Janeiro and the nearby city of Vitoria are considered
to be among the highest in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ''Society is demanding from all of us a quicker response,''
Cardoso said. ''We could ask, who among us has not suffered because
of violence?''
</P>
<P>
   The plan would restrict possession of firearms to the armed
forces, police, private security personnel, collectors and gun
clubs. Everyone else would have 360 days to turn in their guns and
ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   According to government figures, Brazilians own an estimated 8
million guns, of which about 6 million are unregistered.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement came a week after a bus kidnapping that left a
20-year-old teacher and her kidnapper dead. The episode shocked
viewers across the nation who followed the incident on live
television for four hours.
</P>
<P>
   The plan was hailed by government supporters, but independent
lawyers expressed reservations about it.
</P>
<P>
   ''The government is giving priority to repression instead of
focusing on education and rehabilitation of young people,'' said
Reginaldo de Castro, president of the Brazilian Bar Association.
</P>
<P>
   The bill is expected to be approved in the Senate and then go to
the Chamber of Deputies. Altair Goncalves Soares, a committee
secretary, said the proposal still could be modified and would take
months before it becomes law.
</P>
<P>
   The plan is the most expensive and comprehensive in recent years
in Brazil, where a killing takes place every 13 minutes, according
to recent statistics. The country ranked fourth last year
kidnappings after Colombia, Mexico and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Another major measure requiring congressional approval makes it
legal for police to infiltrate drug-trafficking gangs as part of
anti-drug campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Other measures going immediately into effect include a
witness-protection plan to encourage victims and witnesses to help
police. Another major step assigns $55 million to expand the
prison's capacity with 8,500 new places and to construct new
federal prisons to host additional 500 inmates this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-20-00 2045 </TRAILER>
