<HEADLINE> Five indicted in Central Park attacks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - Five young men have been indicted for alleged
attacks last Sunday on dozens of women in Central Park, a
prosecutor said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant District Attorney Maxine Rosenthal said the five were
charged with first-degree sexual abuse and first-degree riot. The
defendants face up to seven years in prison if convicted on the
charges.
</P>
<P>
   Manhattan Criminal Court Judge Cynthia Kern kept the defendants
in jail and told their lawyers to apply for bail on July 10 when
the five are to be arraigned on the indictments in State Supreme
Court.
</P>
<P>
   The five who were indicted are Manuel Vargas, 18, the Bronx;
Imanuel Nunez, 18, the Bronx; Roberto Comacho, 16, Nassau County;
Steven Burt, 32, Jersey City; and Jensen Soto, 16, of Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   Another man arrested in the attacks, John Taylor, 24, of Queens,
was released without bail by Kern after Rosenthal told her the
grand jury had taken no action in his case. Charges against him
have not been dropped.
</P>
<P>
   However, Taylor's lawyer, Alan Kudisch, said prosecutors have
told him they are unlikely to present Taylor's case to the grand
jury or prosecute him further. Kudisch said Taylor is innocent of
the sex and riot charges.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the courtroom, Taylor went to each of the dozen family
members and friends and hugged them as everybody laughed happily.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm happy to be going home with my family,'' Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Tuesday, police announced the arrests of three more
suspects in connection with the park assaults, bringing to 20 the
number charged in the June 11 attacks on women by several packs of
men.
</P>
<P>
   Arrested were Dellon Evans, 17, of Queens; Alexander Eraide, 23,
of Queens; and a male 15-year-old whose identity was withheld.
Police said they arrested the suspects after culling their photos
from videos of the attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Police Commissioner Howard Safir said on Tuesday that police are
looking for at least 22 more men, identified by victims from
amateur videotapes.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of women have told police they were doused with water,
chased, stripped, molested or assaulted. On Monday, four more women
reported they were sexually abused, bringing the number of known
victims to 53.
</P>
<P>
   At least 14 of the women also said they were the victims of
robberies or attempted robberies, and at least four women have
declared that they intend to sue the city on the ground that police
failed to try to help them.
</P>
<P>
   Safir said an internal investigation into the allegations that
some officers ignored pleas for help is ongoing. He has warned that
police officers could be fired if the Police Department finds that
the allegations are true.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
