<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State demotes Greystone CEO  </HEADLINE>
By AMY WESTFELDT
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - The state replaced the embattled CEO of
Greystone Park Psychiatric Hospital Tuesday with an administrator
officials said was better suited to close down the troubled
facility.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Greenstein was named special assistant to the director
of the state Division of Mental Health Services and will be
replaced as head of the Parsippany hospital by Gregory Roberts,
chief executive officer of Ancora Psychiatric State Hospital in
Camden County, state officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The ouster of Greenstein had been sought for months by
politicians and employees who blamed him for the reports of patient
assaults, pregnancies, suicides and unsanitary conditions at the
state-run hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's obvious Michael Greenstein had lost control of Greystone
and deserved to get fired,'' said Senate Minority Leader Richard
Codey.
</P>
<P>
   Both Greenstein, who didn't return a telephone call on Tuesday,
and Roberts will get to keep their $95,000 annual salaries. Roberts
will take over July 17.
</P>
<P>
   ''Michael did many good things at Greystone,'' said State
Department of Human Services Commissioner Michele K. Guhl. ''But
closing a hospital requires a different set of skills and I felt at
this time we needed someone with Greg's specialized expertise.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christie Whitman said in April that the 124-year-old
Greystone hospital would close within a few years, after reports
that the hospital's 610 patients were crowded into bedrooms and
unsupervised, that employees had sexually assaulted patients and
that patients had become pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   Many patients will be moved to group homes and other
community-based centers over the next three years, while the
chronically ill patients likely will end up in a smaller hospital
the state will build on Greystone's grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Greenstein, 51, was hired four years ago to replace CEO George
Waters Jr., who was fired after several female patients claimed
they were sexually assaulted by employees and legislative hearings
were held.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts, 49, was formerly CEO of Marlboro Psychiatric Hospital
and oversaw the closing of that hospital from 1995 to 1998. Roberts
supervised the assessment and placement of 776 Marlboro patients
and 1,180 staff. He became CEO of Ancora two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   La Tanya Wood El, the section chief of Holly Hall at Ancora and
an 18-year hospital employee, will become acting Ancora CEO, the
state said.
</P>
<P>
   A scathing report on Greystone issued in March by a
court-appointed watchdog group concluded that patients were
sleeping on floors, had no access to toilet paper or soap, and get
hurt fighting each other.
</P>
<P>
   Federal inspectors in May gave the hospital failing grades for
safety and staffing, saying the hospital had been overcrowded for
15 years.
</P>
<P>
   Other troubles that have occurred at the hospital include:
</P>
<P>
   -A suicidal patient left unattended hanged himself by a bedsheet
in February.
</P>
<P>
   -A male patient was charged with sexually assaulting a mildly
retarded female patient in an elevator.
</P>
<P>
   -Four employees were charged with assaulting and illegally
restraining another patient with a bedsheet. The charges were
recently dropped when police didn't appear at a court hearing.
</P>
<P>
   -At least a dozen employees are under investigation for failing
to report a suicide attempt last year.
</P>
<P>
   -Officials say at least 12 mentally impaired patients have
become pregnant while being treated at Greystone since 1995,
despite a policy prohibiting them from having sex.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-20-00 2141 </TRAILER>
