<HEADLINE> Charles, Camilla Host Charity Dinner  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Prince Charles and his longtime love smiled and
looked relaxed Tuesday as they attended their first semiofficial
engagement together at a London warehouse.
</P>
<P>
   But they refused to give the waiting photographers the image
they craved -- a kiss.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of photographers were waiting for Charles and Camilla
Parker Bowles when their car pulled up outside the new headquarters
of the Prince's Foundation in east London for a charity
fund-raising dinner. The couple smiled but refused to pose for
pictures.
</P>
<P>
   ''My feet have a nervous twitch and I can't stop moving,''
Charles joked to one photographer, who asked the couple to stop and
pose inside.
</P>
<P>
   Photographers had no joy as the couple left the event shortly
after 11:30 p.m., either. The couple walked out together and got
into their green Bentley without pausing.
</P>
<P>
   Guests at the dinner said Parker Bowles had looked relaxed
throughout the evening.
</P>
<P>
   The by-invitation-only dinner, held in honor of the prince's
foundations in the United Kingdom and the United States, comes less
than three weeks after Queen Elizabeth II relented and met socially
with her eldest son's companion at a private party.
</P>
<P>
   The presence of Parker Bowles at the Tuesday dinner is another
landmark in an increasingly successful campaign by Charles, 51, and
his advisers to gain public acceptability for the woman who was
blamed by Charles' ex-wife, the late Princess Diana, for the
breakup of their marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, St. James's Palace has said that Parker Bowles, 52,
will not accompany the heir to the British throne on official
engagements. The palace has said the dinner was a private ''thank
you'' for the foundation's supporters.
</P>
</TEXT>
