<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Pushes for China Trade Bill  </HEADLINE>
By DEB RIECHMANN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate vote on a China trade bill is
likely to take place right after Congress returns from its Fourth
of July recess, Sen. Patrick Moynihan said Tuesday after a White
House strategy session on getting the measure passed.
</P>
<P>
   ''We hope to have it the first week we return from the July 4th
recess,'' Moynihan, the ranking Democrat on the Senate Finance
Committee, told reporters on the White House driveway. ''This is
not the most important vote this year. It may be the most important
vote this decade,'' he said. ''We don't want it to last on until
the (political) convention season.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, Senate Democratic Leader Tom Daschle expressed
worry that a vote might be put off until September, just before the
presidential election. But speaking to reporters earlier in the
day, Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott reiterated his belief that
the vote could be held next month, before the August recess, which
begins July 28.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have to get the bulk of these appropriations bills done
before we can go to the China trade bill,'' he said. ''Hopefully we
can get to that in July.''
</P>
<P>
   Eight senators met for about 45 minutes with Clinton, U.S. Trade
Representative Charlene Barshefsky, Agriculture Secretary Dan
Glickman and Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, who is
scheduled to visit Beijing later this week.
</P>
<P>
   ''The sooner we bring it up, the better off we are -- the less
chance for something to go wrong,'' Senate Finance Chairman William
Roth, R-Del., told reporters at the White House. ''The longer we
wait, the more danger there is of mischief.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill would end annual votes on China's trade status and
grant the nation permanent normal trading relations. The
legislation itself has wide support, but it has been the victim of
political maneuvering in the rush to clear the legislative decks
before this summer's political conventions. Democrats have blamed
Lott for playing politics with the bill to gain leverage on other
issues.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters also hope to keep the bill from being further amended
in the Senate, which would require another likely contentious vote
in the House. Amendments have been threatened by Sen. Jesse Helms,
R-N.C., and Paul Wellstone, D-Minn. And Sen. Fred Thompson,
R-Tenn., said he will push for an amendment if he can't get a
separate vote on his bill to impose sanctions on China for weapons
proliferation.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would hope that it would be done as an independent bill,''
Roth said. ''It's critically important that there be no amendments
to this legislation. We do not want to take it back to conference.
We do not want to have a second vote.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The bills are H.R. 4444 and S. 2277
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: White House site: http://www.chinapntr.gov
</P>
<P>
   AFL-CIO site: http://www.aflcio.org/publ/press2000/pr0222.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-20-00 2157 </TRAILER>
