<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Witnesses: Skakel admitted involvement in murder  </HEADLINE>
By DENISE LAVOIE
<TEXT>
<P>
   STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) - Kennedy cousin Michael Skakel confessed
to the 1975 murder of a teen-age neighbor telling a classmate,
''I'm gonna get away with murder. I'm a Kennedy,'' according to
testimony at a pretrial hearing Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Gregory Coleman was one of two students who said Skakel
confessed to them while they attended the Elan school, a
residential substance abuse treatment center for youths, in the
late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   They testified before a judge who will decide whether there is
enough evidence for a trial and, if so, whether the 39-year-old
Skakel is to be tried in juvenile court. The hearing is scheduled
to last several days.
</P>
<P>
   Skakel, 39, is charged as a juvenile in the October 1975 slaying
of Greenwich teen-ager Martha Moxley. Both Skakel and Moxley were
15 at the time of the killing.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman testified that he noticed that Skakel appeared to have
special privileges - including a stereo and records.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman said he commented to Skakel that it appeared he could
get away with murder.
</P>
<P>
   ''At which point he said to me, 'I'm gonna get away with murder.
I'm a Kennedy.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Coleman said Skakel told him he beat Moxley's skull in with a
golf club after she rejected his romantic advances.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman also said that he heard Skakel make an admission to the
murder during a ''primal scream therapy session'' in which
participants were urged to get in touch with their pain and then
scream ''I'm sorry'' over and over again.
</P>
<P>
   Under cross-examination by Skakel's lawyer, Michael Sherman,
Coleman acknowledged that he waited 20 years to come forward about
the purported confession, and only after seeing a segment on the
case on a television news program.
</P>
<P>
   Sherman asked Coleman why he did not call police. He said he
didn't know why.
</P>
<P>
   Sherman then ran through Coleman's criminal record, which
includes a 1983 conviction for robbery and a 1999 conviction for
criminal trespassing, for which he is now serving a 1-year prison
sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Sherman suggested that Coleman was looking for a deal from
prosecutors by agreeing to testify against Skakel.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman said although he did ask the state's attorney's office
for $1,200 when he learned his father was dying of cancer, he said
he told prosecutors he would testify regardless of whether they
helped him financially.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, John Higgins, another former Elan student, testified
that one night while he and Skakel were on ''night owl duty'' -
making sure no one ran away from the dormitory - a sobbing Skakel
discussed the Moxley murder.
</P>
<P>
   ''He related to me that he had been involved in a murder ... or
thought that he had been involved,'' Higgins said.
</P>
<P>
   Higgins said Skakel told him he remembered going through golf
clubs stored in the Skakel family garage, then running through the
woods and seeing pine trees, then blacking out and awakening the
next morning.
</P>
<P>
   Moxley was beaten to death with a 6-iron; the club was traced to
a set owned by the Skakel family.
</P>
<P>
   ''He said that he didn't know whether he did it and he couldn't
remember,'' Higgins said. ''He eventually said that he, in fact,
did it.''
</P>
<P>
   On cross-examination, Higgins admitted that he and Skakel were
never close friends, and that he had lied about Skakel's alleged
comments when contacted by an investigator in the state's
attorney's office many years later.
</P>
<P>
   ''I didn't want to talk to this guy - or anybody else - about
it, ever,'' Higgins said.
</P>
<P>
   Skakel's lawyer suggested Higgins had only come forward after he
heard about a reward. But Higgins said he did not try to claim the
reward, which later was withdrawn.
</P>
<P>
   Sherman asked Higgins if he would be surprised to learn there
was no garage on the Skakel property. Higgins replied that he could
only relate what Skakel had told him.
</P>
<P>
   Skakel became visibly upset during Higgins' testimony, tears
trickling down his face.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's just very upset about hearing this moron get up there and
lie,'' Sherman told reporters during a break.
</P>
<P>
   Moxley's brother, John, who was 17 when his sister was murdered,
said he thought Skakel's emotion was fear.
</P>
<P>
   ''They weren't tears of joy. I think the reality is starting to
tumble down around him,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Skakel's lawyer called Higgins' testimony ''baloney'' and
''devoid of character.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Greenwich police Chief Thomas Keegan, a captain in the
detective division at the time of the murder, testified that the
Skakels told police they often left golf clubs lying in the yard of
their estate in the wealthy enclave of Belle Haven.
</P>
<P>
   But he said police dismissed their original theory that the
slaying was committed by a stranger. The club used in the killing
broke into several pieces, and the handle was never recovered
despite an extensive search of the neighborhood, including draining
swimming pools and checking the Long Island Sound.
</P>
<P>
   ''My conclusion is that the person who killed Martha was aware
that that name was on the club,'' Keegan said.
</P>
<P>
   Under questioning from Skakel's attorney, Keegan acknowledged
that for years, police considered Thomas Skakel, Michael's older
brother, and Ken Littleton, a Skakel family tutor, as suspects.
</P>
<P>
   Under the law in effect at the time of the killing, Skakel could
face a maximum of only four years if he were convicted as a
juvenile. If he were convicted as an adult, he could get 25 years
to life.
</P>
<P>
   Martha's body was found under a tree on her family's estate. She
had been at the Skakel house the night before with a group of
friends, including Michael and Thomas Skakel, then 17.
</P>
<P>
   Rushton Skakel Sr., the father of Michael and Thomas Skakel, is
the brother of Sen. Robert F. Kennedy's widow, Ethel.
</P>
<P>
   State prosecutors said they expect to wrap up their case
Wednesday. Skakel's lawyers are expected to begin presenting their
defense on June 28.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-20-00 2207 </TRAILER>
