<HEADLINE> Shaq To Pay For L.A. Police Car  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Shaquille O'Neal, whose work in the community
has shown he's a man with a large social conscience, will pay to
replace one of two police cars torched by rowdy fans celebrating
the Los Angeles Lakers' NBA championship.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers and owner Jerry Buss will chip in with Staples Center
to replace the other police vehicle that was burned outside the
arena, Lakers spokesman John Black said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Fully equipped police vehicles can cost around $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal, the 7-foot-1, 330-pound center who capped his first
championship season by winning the NBA Finals MVP award, is very
active in the community, particularly in children's programs. He
participates in Shaq Paq, Wish Kids, Shaqsgiving and Shaq-a-Claus.
He also is a spokesman for Reading is Fundamental.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal, Buss and Staples executives all had their victory
celebrations put on hold after Monday's night's 116-111 clinching
victory over Indiana. They remained in the arena some two hours
before police deemed it safe to leave the building.
</P>
<P>
   Two TV news vans also were damaged or destroyed, and other auto
fires were reported in the general area of Staples. There were 11
arrests, but no major injuries were reported.
</P>
</TEXT>
