<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 22:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Haiti Results Favor Aristide Party  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL NORTON
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) -- Haiti's Elections Council on
Tuesday released more results from the May 21 elections, giving
former President Jean-Bertrand Aristide's party 26 seats in the
parliament's lower house. The party already won control of the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The council announcements came a day after violent protests
paralyzed Haiti's three biggest cities as demonstrators pressed for
results from the vote.
</P>
<P>
   In the lower Chamber of Deputies, Aristide's Lavalas Family
Party won the first round of voting with 26 seats in the 83-member
body. Results from another 11 seats are still being tabulated. For
the remaining 46 seats, no one won a majority so runoffs will be
held.
</P>
<P>
   The council said Monday that Aristide candidates won 16 of 17
Senate seats contested in the May 21 balloting.
</P>
<P>
   The election results have been challenged by the international
community and Elections Council President Leon Manus, who fled to
the United States over the weekend in fear of his life.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has demanded an honest count of ballots cast
in the elections, which are crucial to restoring some $500 million
in suspended international aid. The United Nations and Organization
of American States have also questioned the vote.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. government Tuesday urged Haitians to exercise
restraint. State Department spokesman Richard Boucher said
administration officials currently are Haiti for meetings related
to the election.
</P>
<P>
   The Elections Council also said it was postponing the second
round of elections scheduled for Sunday but gave no date.
Opposition leaders have threatened to boycott, charging the count
was fixed to give Aristide a victory that would set Haiti on the
road to a virtual one-party state.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Monday, Manus told a radio station from an undisclosed
location in the United States that he refused to give in to
pressure from President Rene Preval to sign off on incorrect
results giving Aristide candidates 16 Senate seats. Manus said
Aristide candidates won only seven seats, Radio Galaxie reported.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's Senate results were signed by six remaining council
members.
</P>
<P>
   Among new legislators who would join the Senate under the
disputed results are at least three whom opponents have linked to
Haiti's increasing traffic in cocaine headed for the United States.
Aristide's party says the allegations linking Aristide cronies to
drug dealing are political propaganda.
</P>
<P>
   Also becoming a senator is former police chief, Dany Toussaint.
A 1997 U.S. Senate vote to deny U.S. visas to Haitians implicated
in extrajudicial and political killings identified Toussaint among
''suspected murderers.'' Toussaint was detained in the United
States for three months that year in what he said was a successful
attempt to prevent him from running for Haiti's Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute over the results comes down to the method Haitian
officials used to count the votes.
</P>
<P>
   Under Haitian law, candidates must win a majority to avoid a
second round of voting. But officials counted the votes of only the
top four contenders and not the others who ran and may have gotten
a few votes. Those missing votes created an erroneous winning
percentage count, observers say, giving at least eight of 16 Senate
seats to Aristide candidates who otherwise would have to face a
second round.
</P>
<P>
   In Port-au-Prince on Monday, protesters stoned vehicles and set
tire barricades ablaze. They blocked the capital's main arteries
with hulks of vehicles, junked refrigerators and large rocks. Shops
and schools stayed shut.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters also reportedly paralyzed Cap-Haitien and Gonaives,
Haiti's second- and third-largest cities.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the U.S. Embassy in Port-au-Prince, demonstrators set a
large pile of debris on fire and chanted anti-American slogans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-20-00 2238 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000620.0208 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 22:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Venezuela Vote Simplification Sought  </HEADLINE>
By JORGE RUEDA
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- Electoral officials asked lawmakers
Tuesday to separate the country's upcoming general election into
two stages to simplify balloting.
</P>
<P>
   The National Electoral Council said Tuesday night it wants
voters to elect the president, governors and mayors on July 30,
with elections for regional and local councils sometime after Sept.
17.
</P>
<P>
   ''For the institutional health of the country ... it is
necessary to make the electoral event simpler,'' council president
Cesar Pena Vigas said in a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   All of the elections were originally scheduled for May 28, but
Venezuela's Supreme Court canceled them because of technical
problems including the omission of some candidates from a database
needed to count votes.
</P>
<P>
   More than 36,000 candidates are vying for 6,236 public offices.
The vote will cement a new constitution that President Hugo Chavez
has promised will better distribute power between rich and poor
Venezuelans.
</P>
<P>
   Venezuela's Legislative Commission will make the final decision
on the election dates. The Legislative Commission -- dominated by
Chavez allies -- was appointed by the Constitutional Assembly as a
temporary legislature after constitution-writers dissolved Congress
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Commission president Luis Miquilena said he wanted to meet this
week with opposition parties and civic groups to reach a consensus
on the election date, which has divided the parties.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition politicians want all of the elections on the same
date. They fear that if the presidential vote is held first, a win
by front-runner Chavez would give momentum to other candidates of
his party.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez's main opponent in the presidential race, Francisco
Arias, has accused Miquilena of ''manipulating'' the election
dates. He also warned that staging two elections would be costly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-20-00 2240 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000620.0209 </DOCNO>
