<HEADLINE> Notes From Tuesday's Baseball Games  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressAMERICAN LEAGUE:
Orioles-Athletics:
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE: Brady Anderson missed his second straight game with a
slight strain of his right quadriceps. Luis Matos took his spot in
center field for the second straight game and made a leaping catch
to rob Randy Velarde of a solo homer in the seventh. Anderson is
expected to be able to return for Wednesday's series finale. ...
The Orioles activated RHP Calvin Maduro from the disabled list and
optioned RHP Gabe Molina to Triple-A Rochester. Maduro had been
sidelined since mid-May with a strained ligament in his elbow.
Molina appeared in three games as a reliever, giving up three runs
in three innings.
</P>
<P>
   OAKLAND: The A's have spent 17 days with at least a share of the
AL West lead this season, after spending a combined 16 days in
first place over the previous five seasons. ... The A's will call
up RHP Ariel Prieto from Triple-A Sacramento in time for him to
start Wednesday's series finale against the Orioles. He will
replace Omar Olivares, who went on the DL last Saturday with a
strained right shoulder. Oakland had been debating whether to bring
up Prieto or LHP Barry Zito to replace Olivares. ''We definitely
took a long, hard look at (Zito), but the people down there thought
Ariel was doing better,'' manager Art Howe said. Howe added that
Prieto's performance Wednesday will determine whether he makes more
than just the one start. He was promoted for one start earlier this
season, and got shelled.
Yankees-Red Sox:
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK: RHP Roger Clemens (groin) reported improvement after
his third day of workouts and treatment at the team's player
development center in Tampa, Fla. There is no definite return date
for the five-time Cy Young Award, who has not yet resumed a regular
throwing schedule. ... Three of owner George Steinbrenner's special
advisers -- Al Rosen, Clyde King and Bob Kennedy -- were scheduled to
watch Triple-A Columbus on Tuesday night. The trio were at the
Class-A Tampa game Monday. ... Steinbrenner was in Boston, and he
spoke to manager Joe Torre by phone before the game. There were no
developments on trade talks, Torre said. ... Chuck Knoblauch, who
has had problems throwing accurately to first base, will come out
in the late innings for defensive purposes for the near future.
''Hopefully, by August, this doesn't happen. Right now, I think
it's best for everyone,'' Torre said. Knoblauch had assists on the
first two outs of the game, one to his right and one to his left,
and made two more plays flawlessly in the second. ... Derek Jeter
has reached base in 19 of 21 games since returning from the
disabled list on May 27.
</P>
<P>
   BOSTON: The Red Sox have scored only eight runs in Pedro
Martinez' previous four starts. ... Boston recalled pitcher Tim
Young from Triple-A Pawtucket to take Rob Stanifer's place on the
roster. Stanifer was sent down after allowing nine runs -- one
earned -- on seven hits and a walk in Boston's 22-1 loss to the New
York Yankees on Monday night.... Nomar Garciaparra extended his
hitting streak to 10 games with a first inning bloop single. ...
Martinez struck out six consecutive batters in innings 1-3. ...
Knoblauch was picked off first base in the fourth by Martinez, his
second pickoff of the season and the eighth for the Red Sox.
Tigers-Blue Jays:
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT: The Tigers purchased the contract of RHP Steve Sparks
from Triple-A Toledo. They designated LHP Allen McDill for
assignment. Sparks, a knuckleballer, was 5-11 with a 5.42 ERA with
Anaheim last season. ... 3B Dean Palmer, who sat out Sunday because
of a shoulder spasm, was in the lineup as DH.
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO: The Blue Jays won't know extent C Darren Fletcher's
shoulder injury until later in the week. Dr. James Andrews will
look at X-rays in the next couple of days. ... Rookie OF DeWayne
Wise had surgery on June 19 to remove a pin from his left big toe.
He was transferred to the 60-day disabled list.
Indians-White Sox:
</P>
<P>
   CLEVELAND: OF Manny Ramirez, sidelined since May 29 with a
strained left hamstring, was to see a doctor in Cleveland on
Tuesday because of hemorrhaging in his thigh. Ramirez will be out
at least another week. ''We miss his bat,'' manager Charlie Manuel
said. ''Manny's our RBI guy. We definitely miss him.'' ... RHP
Charles Nagy, who made his first rehab start Monday, rejoined the
team in Chicago Tuesday and will throw on the side Thursday. The
Indians will decide after the side day whether Nagy is ready to
rejoin the rotation. ''We want Charlie to be 100 percent,'' Manuel
said. ... Pitchers Paul Shuey and Sean DePaula, both on the
disabled list, will throw simulated games Wednesday in Chicago. If
all goes well, they will then begin rehab assignments. Shuey is out
with a torn labrum in his right hip while DePaula has tendinitis in
his right elbow.
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO: Manager Jerry Manuel said he'll probably stay with a
seven-man bullpen until the All-Star break. The White Sox lead the
AL in relief appearances. ... Manuel was impressed by the fans
standing ovation before the players took the field before Monday
night's game. ''Someone mentioned it was like coming home to a
hero's welcome,'' Manuel said. ... The White Sox have agreed to
terms with shortstop Tim Hummel and second baseman Tommy Nicholson,
the second- and 11th-round picks in the June draft. Both will
report to Class A Burlington.
Twins-Rangers:
</P>
<P>
   MINNESOTA: Struggling RHP Sean Bergman refused an assignment to
Triple-A Salt Lake City and was placed on waivers Tuesday by the
Twins. The right-hander, claimed on waivers from Atlanta last
October, was 4-5 in 14 starts for the Twins this season with a 9.66
ERA. He gave up 111 hits and 76 runs in 68 innings, with 36
strikeouts and 33 walks. ... SS Cristian Guzman leads the majors in
triples with 11. Going into Tuesday night's game, that put him on
pace for 25. The Twins club record is 16 by Rod Carew in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS: LHP Darren Oliver's scheduled start has been pushed back
from Thursday to Saturday to give the Rangers more time to evaluate
an MRI, a bone scan and a nerve test. Oliver (2-4 with a 6.66 ERA
in 13 starts) has had a recurring shoulder problem. Matt Perisho
(2-0, 5.40 ERA) will start Thursday. If Oliver isn't ready
Saturday, the Rangers will recall Ryan Glynn from Triple-A
Oklahoma. Glynn made a spot start earlier this season, and allowed
just two hits in eight shutout innings in a 2-0 victory over the
Dodgers and Kevin Brown. ... Even though the Rangers were in last
place after a 1-8 road trip, their worst in 14 years, GM Doug
Melvin doesn't foresee any major changes soon. ''We've already made
a lot of changes. We need more time to evaluate the situation.''
Melvin said he's also not ready to give up on the season and start
dealing potential free agents such as pitcher John Wetteland and
designated hitter David Segui.
Tampa Bay-Seattle:
</P>
<P>
   TAMPA BAY: Vinny Castilla, Jose Canseco and Greg Vaughn, who are
all currently on the disabled list, have played together for 31 of
the 68 games. ... The Devil Rays, at 28-40, at the same record
after 68 games as they had last season.
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE: If RHP Gil Meche isn't able to take his turn in the
rotation on Friday against Baltimore, RHP Brett Tomko will start in
his place. Meche has experienced a ''dead arm'' this season. He
left his last start after throwing 80 pitches on Sunday. Tomko is
eligible to come off the DL on Thursday. He has been sidelined with
tendinitis in his right shoulder.
Royals-Angels:
</P>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY: The Royals, who were outscored 39-11 by Oakland in
three game over the weekend, entered their series at Anaheim having
plummeted eight games in the AL Central standings in two weeks and
were 11 games off the pace. ... Jermaine Dye is leading AL
outfielders in the All-Star balloting, and could become the first
Kansas City player to get a starting nod since Bo Jackson in 1989.
... Jose Rosado, on the DL since May 1 because of tendinitis in his
left shoulder, is scheduled to undergo arthroscopic surgery Friday
in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ANAHEIM: The Angels invited No. 1 draft pick Joe Torres to
Edison Field to give him a taste of what he has to look forward to
-- if he earns it. ''It makes no difference if you're a first-round
pick or a 30th-round pick, as far as the attention he'll get in
development,'' said manager Mike Scioscia, who had a chance to meet
the left-hander before Torres leaves Sunday for Class-A Boise. ...
The Angels have already played seven games this season in which
they've homered at least four times. Last season they did it on
nine occasions. ... Jason Dickson, who is on the DL because of
tendinitis in his left hip and a sore right shoulder, will make a
rehab start on Wednesday night with Triple-A Edmonton. ... RHP Kent
Bottenfield threw a simulated game Tuesday and is expected to be
activated in time to start Saturday against Minnesota. ''He looked
great. His pitches were sharp and he felt very strong,'' Scioscia
said.
NATIONAL LEAGUE:
Pirates-Expos:
</P>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH: The Pirates, currently on a four-game losing streak,
have lost 11 of their last 16 -- including five of six -- since
fashioning a season-high four-game winning streak May 29-June 2.
Pittsburgh was a season-high 10 games under .500 heading into
Tuesday night's game. ... RHP Kris Benson, Tuesday's starter, had a
2.08 ERA in his previous 10 starts, allowing just 18 earned runs
over his last 78 innings. Benson has gone seven innings or more in
nine of those starts.
</P>
<P>
   MONTREAL: The Expos had four players with more than 45 RBIs
entering Tuesday night's game, including RF Vladimir Guerrero, who
leads the team with 60 RBIs. 1B Lee Stevens was next with 48,
followed by 2B Jose Vidro (47), and LF Rondell White (46). ...
White missed his second straight start in left due to a sore left
knee. White injured the knee Sunday while trying to beat out a
double play grounder in Chicago. X-Rays done on the knee Tuesday
came back negative. ... Wilton Guerrero started in left for the
second straight game.
Brewers-Marlins:
</P>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE: The Brewers signed RHP Heath McMurray, their
12th-round draft pick in this year's First-Year Players Draft.
McMurray attended Louisiana State and he'll report Ogden, the
Brewers' rookie affiliate in Utah.
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA: Preston Wilson entered Tuesday's game leading the
majors with 100 strikeouts and is on pace to break Bobby Bonds'
record of 189 set in 1970. His career ratio of one whiff every 2.88
at-bats is the highest. ... Marlins ailing pitchers are on the
mend. A.J. Burnett will begin a minor league rehab assignment on
July 1, but on June 29, the right-hander will pitch for Double-A
Portland against the Marlins in an exhibition game. ... Set-up man
Dan Miceli, out since May 31 with inflammation of his right
forearm, is scheduled to return before the All-Star break while RHP
Alex Fernandez, who has been out for five weeks with soreness in
his right elbow, isn't close to returning. ''I do think he'll be
back this season, knowing Alex,'' Marlins manager John Boles said.
Phillies-Mets:
</P>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA: The Phillies began their first series this season
at Shea Stadium, the only NL road venue in which they are over
.500. Philadelphia has also beaten New York at Veterans Stadium in
five of last six. ... SS Desi Relaford, who leads the majors with
19 errors, was not in the starting lineup for the second time in
four games. Relaford, the last NL starting shortstop to make an
error this season, has committed 13 in his last 22 games and three
in his last three starts. Alex Arias once again started in his
place. ... Several Phillies, including C Mike Lieberthal, got a
chuckle watching a scoreboard video showing Robin Ventura's
impersonation of Mike Piazza during a recent rain delay at Yankee
Stadium. Ventura took a comical trip around the puddle-filled tarp,
dressed in a Piazza jersey and fake mustache, sliding into second
base and home plate.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK: Tuesday's starter Mike Hampton finally got nice
weather in which to pitch. Hampton was limited to 47 pitches on
June 11 at Yankee Stadium in a game that was rained out in the
third inning. His next start in Chicago three days later was cut
short after one inning (32 pitches) because of a lengthy rain
delay. Manager Bobby Valentine said the left-hander, who also has
been dealing with a strained left groin, was completely fit to
pitch a full game. Tuesday's game-time temperature was 81 degrees
under sunny blue skies. ... OF Darryl Hamilton, who has not played
soince the first week of the season because of a sprained left
foot, took batting practice and ran Tuesday and might be ready to
be sent out on a rehab assignment by the weekend. ... SS Rey
Ordonez, who broke a bone in his arm last month, is almost free of
pain.
Rockies-Reds:
</P>
<P>
   COLORADO: Reliever Gabe White hasn't given up a run in his last
19 2-3 innings, two innings shy of the club record set by Curtis
Leskanic in 1998. ... Jeffrey Hammonds' 54 RBIs left him one shy of
his career high set in 1997 with Baltimore. ... Entering a
three-game series against the Reds, Todd Helton was 12-for-25
(.480) career at Cinergy Field.
</P>
<P>
   CINCINNATI: Starter Pete Harnisch threw 80 pitches in batting
practice. The Reds are hoping to pitch him next Thursday against
St. Louis. Harnisch, the Reds' top winner the last two seasons, has
been on the disabled list since May 6 with a weak shoulder. ...
Manager Jack McKeon said struggling starters Steve Parris and Rob
Bell will stay in the rotation for now because there are no other
options. Reds starters were 0-10 with a 7.34 ERA in the last 13
games.
Cubs-Braves:
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO: Entering Tuesday's game, Sammy Sosa needed five hits to
reach the 1,500 mark. ... SS Ricky Gutierrez began an injury rehab
assignment Monday with the Cubs' Daytona Class-A affiliate. He has
been on the DL since May 25 with a separated right shoulder. ...
The Cubs began their longest road trip of the season -- a two-week,
12-game, four-city excursion.
</P>
