<HEADLINE> Tuesday's Canada News Briefs  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressNote: All dollars are Canadian unless otherwise noted
Canada's Health System Ranks 30th in UN Assessment
<TEXT>
<P>
   OTTAWA (AP) -- The World Health Organization has ranked Canada's
health system a lackluster 30th in the world in results obtained
for money spent.
</P>
<P>
   Canada lags developing countries like Colombia, Cyprus, Oman and
Morocco in the first attempt to objectively compare health systems
of 191 UN member states.
</P>
<P>
   The assessment suggests that problems with Canadian medicare are
not simply due to lack of funding, but also to inefficiency.
</P>
<P>
   It appears to support Health Minister Allan Rock's view that
Canada's system needs reform, not just more money.
</P>
<P>
   Canada ranks 10th in the proportion of gross domestic product it
devotes to health, and seventh in health attainment as measured by
indicators such as average healthy life expectancy.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you compare Canada's level of attainment to what it should
be able to achieve given its resources, that's where Canada drops
to 30th,'' WHO spokesman Christopher Murray said in an interview.
------
Alliance Memberships Appear in Chaos
</P>
<P>
   OTTAWA (AP) -- The Quebec campaign of the Canadian Alliance
leadership race appeared to be in chaos Tuesday as organizers for
candidate Tom Long conceded they had found numerous bogus party
memberships in the Gaspe region.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Sauve, Long's principal organizer in Quebec, confirmed
Tuesday that an investigation of 1,656 membership names turned up
600 people who had no knowledge of signing up. Staff are still
working the phones to check on other numbers gathered by campaign
workers in the region, where it was earlier leaked there were 2,800
new members.
</P>
<P>
   The number -- in an area of separatist political leanings with no
Alliance presence -- brought widespread ridicule of the Long
campaign.
------
Two Sides Square Off in Halifax on Disputed Health Effects of
Perfume
</P>
<P>
   HALIFAX, Nova Scotia (AP) -- The two sides in a raging battle
over the right to bear scent took their fight to the media Tuesday,
although from separate floors of the same hotel.
</P>
<P>
   On one side, activists and researchers claimed a slew of
untested, carcinogenic chemicals are ending up in perfumes and
making people sick with asthma and other respiratory illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   On the other, officials from the perfume industry insisted their
scented products are safe and have been the victim of
misinformation.
</P>
<P>
   The two groups held separate news conferences in Halifax, a
small seaside city that has become ground zero for a dispute over
the rights of individuals to wear scents versus those who may have
sensitivities to them.
</P>
<P>
   Halifax has had a ''no-scent encouragement program'' in place
for four years. The policy, which isn't law, encourages people to
be aware of the possible sensitivities of others by not wearing
fragrances.
------
Hundreds Attend State Funeral of Grant MacEwan in Edmonton
</P>
<P>
   EDMONTON, Alberta (AP) -- Hundreds of Albertans gathered in the
provincial capital Tuesday to bid farewell to a man described as
the living, breathing spirit of Western Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think we'll have another Grant MacEwan,'' said former
Alberta premier Peter Lougheed, blinking back tears.
</P>
<P>
   MacEwan -- teacher, author, livestock judge, politician and
lieutenant-governor -- died last Thursday at the age of 97, two
years older than the province he served.
</P>
<P>
   Over his lengthy career, he taught at the University of
Saskatchewan for 18 years, served as a Calgary alderman for a
decade, led the Alberta Liberals in 1958-59 and was elected mayor
of Calgary in 1963. In 1965, he was appointed lieutenant-governor,
a post he held to wide acclaim for 8&AMP;frac12; years.
</P>
<P>
   About 500 people attended inside and outside Robertson-Wesley
United Church to say goodbye at the first state funeral in Alberta
since 1963.
</P>
</TEXT>
