<HEADLINE> Three hurt in lake shore accident  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   GORHAM, N.Y. (AP) - A platform fell off an elevator-style tram
used to carry people up the steep banks of Canandaigua Lake's
eastern shore, injuring three women who were tossed onto the narrow
beach or into the lake.
</P>
<P>
   As the women rode down to the lake around 5 p.m. Monday, a
pulley broke away from the tram's motor, sending the platform
streaking 75 to 100 feet down rickety-looking tracks and
catapulting the passengers into the lake, according to witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   The women were rescued by neighbors and passers-by in two boats.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the tram nor the tracks had been inspected, according to
Donna Stebbins, assessor for the town of Gorham, Ontario County.
Permits are not required for older trams like this one, though they
would be for new ones, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The most seriously injured was Denise Leary, 40, of Rochester,
who sustained fractures in both legs and a severe cut to the head.
She was in satisfactory condition at a hospital Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Sue Sage, 52, of Rochester, broke a leg and Kathryn Jackson, 40,
of Batavia, sustained bruises and cuts. They were hospitalized in
fair condition.
</P>
<P>
   Several homemade trams using pulleys and cables operate along
the lake's steep eastern shore, Barnes said. They connect the beach
to homes situated along the top of the banks.
</P>
</TEXT>
