<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 23:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Jersey spends the most in the nation on schools -- again  </HEADLINE>
o0273nyc--
r n BC-NJ--SchoolSpending     06-20 0624
BC-NJ--School Spending,590
New Jersey spends the most in the nation on schools - again
Eds: Story embargoed until 12:01 a.m. Wednesday
By NANCY PARELLO
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - New Jersey again spent more per pupil than
any other state in the U.S., according to a U.S. Census Bureau
report.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1996-97 school year, New Jersey schools, on average,
spent $9,461 per student. The national average is $5,873.
</P>
<P>
   New York was second at $8,467, followed by Alaska ($8,213) and
Connecticut ($7,998), according to the latest school-finance
figures from the Census Bureau, released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey has been the top spender since 1992 - with the
exception of 1994 when Washington, D.C., was first and New Jersey
was second, according to Sharon Meade, a Census Bureau analyst.
</P>
<P>
   State officials and school board representatives said New Jersey
spends more because it values education.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a reflection of the fact that New Jersey citizens and its
government value quality education,'' said John Crosbie, state
education department spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The money allocated to schools nationwide has increased 30
percent from 1991-92 to 1996-97, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
   Spending was $307.5 billion in the 1996-97 year, up from $236.3
billion in 1991-92, according to the bureau's analysis of local,
state and federal records.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the school-funding pie is essentially divided the same way
it was nearly a decade ago. The federal government's share on
average is about 7 percent. States contribute 49 percent and the
rest comes from local tax coffers.
</P>
<P>
   Most of New Jersey's school funding - $5,978 per student - comes
from local taxes, with the state ranking second in local dollars
spent, after Washington, D.C. Nationally, the average local share
is $3,021. State spending on education ranks ninth at $3,909,
compared to the national average of $3,288.
</P>
<P>
   Some policy-makers and educators say the state needs to boost
the amount it sends to local districts to reduce schools' heavy
reliance on property taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The state also ranks first in teacher salaries, with $4,226 per
student, compared to the national average of $2,641. It's also
first in spending on instruction costs, which include salaries, at
$5,788 per student, compared to the national average of $3,628.
</P>
<P>
   And New Jersey ranks second behind Maryland when it comes to
school administrative spending at $524 per pupil, compared to $342
nationally.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a combination of factors,'' said Frank Belluscio,
spokesman for the New Jersey School Boards Association. ''We do
have a strong commitment to public education in New Jersey. You
also have to weigh the fact that we're in a higher cost region.''
</P>
<P>
   The state is often criticized for spending more and getting
less.
</P>
<P>
   While average SAT test scores are inching up, New Jersey
students still lag behind the national average.
</P>
<P>
   High school students who graduated in 1999 scored an average of
498 on the verbal portion of the exam, below the national average
of 505. New Jersey's average math score was 510, just below the 511
national math average.
</P>
<P>
   State officials say that's because so many more students take
the SATs.
</P>
<P>
   In New Jersey, 80 percent of high school graduates took the SAT
exams, nearly twice the national average of 43 percent. Belluscio
said the state ranks second in math scores among states where 60
percent or more of students take the test.
</P>
<P>
   The state is taking steps to improve performance, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've put mechanisms in place to ensure that we are using the
money to effectively educate children,'' Belluscio said, citing the
state's education standards, which are being implemented in schools
around the state.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
