<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 23:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Martinique Mayor, Poet To End Tenure  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT-DE-FRANCE, Martinique (AP) -- Aime Cesaire, the poet and
philosopher who helped found the ''Negritude'' movement in Paris,
says he is ending his 55-year tenure as mayor of Martinique's
capital.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have accomplished the job I had to do,'' the 86-year-old
Cesaire was quoted as saying in the weekend edition of
Frances-Antilles newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   An icon of black pride, he has been mayor of Fort-de-France,
capital of the French Caribbean island, since 1945.
</P>
<P>
   Cesaire, who influenced writers such as Langston Hughes and Maya
Angelou, coined the word ''negritude'' to describe the black
identity and blacks' need to understand their history and the
history of race relations. His black awareness teachings and
vigorous criticism of colonialism helped spur the post-World War II
independence movement in Africa and his native Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   The Progressive Party of Martinique that Cesaire founded in 1958
will meet to find another candidate for mayor. Cesaire said he will
not present a protege.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am not a monarch. I have no heir, no successor,'' Cesaire
said. ''The choice will be made by the people of Martinique.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-20-00 2325 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
