<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 23:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Soldiers Face Charges  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   OTTAWA (AP) -- Criminal charges could be filed against Canadian
soldiers accused of poisoning an officer in Croatia in 1993, a
military official said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   An initial military investigation concluded last month it was
too late to file charges against soldiers who allegedly put
antifreeze, boot polish and other substances into coffee consumed
by Matt Stopford, a warrant officer.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators charge that the soldiers wanted to disable
Stopford because they feared he would lead them into danger. But
they said that because a three-year statute of limitations had
expired, no charges could be filed.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Canada's chief of defense staff, Gen. Maurice Baril,
said a special military panel that reviewed the case reached a
different conclusion. He said the case would be turned over to the
Ontario attorney general for consideration of criminal charges.
</P>
<P>
   Stopford, who is blind in one eye and suffers from unexplained
bleeding and joint problems, said Tuesday that only a public
inquiry could bring out the truth.
</P>
<P>
   Similar ailments among other peacekeepers raised accusations
that they were exposed to toxic waste or other hazardous material
in Croatia. A separate military inquiry found no hazardous material
in soil samples taken last summer from the areas in Croatia where
the Canadians served.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-20-00 2328 </TRAILER>
