<DOCNO> APW20000620.0229 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 23:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Attica guard stands by inmates  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) - Corrections officer Michael Smith
testified Tuesday that the state should own up to its role in the
September 1971 Attica prison uprising, the bloodiest in American
history.
</P>
<P>
   Smith was blindfolded and paraded atop the Attica prison catwalk
on Sept. 13, 1971. One inmate held a knife to his throat, another
had a spear and a third a ball-peen hammer. But the inmates never
hurt him, he said.
</P>
<P>
   When state troopers stormed the prison though, their bullets hit
him five times. Smith said there were ''deadly errors'' made the
day the state retook the prison.
</P>
<P>
   ''What I'm most frustrated by is I think we've probably got the
best system of justice in the world,'' Smith testified Tuesday in
U.S. District Court in Rochester. ''In this event it's been
politically manipulated. And that's beyond unfortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Michael Telesca allowed Smith, who never
returned to work at the prison after the riot, to testify in the
civil case brought by inmates who were at Attica during the riot.
The state has agreed to an $8 million settlement for the inmates in
the 25-year-old civil case; $4 million more will go to lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Attica stands as the nation's deadliest prison uprising. In all,
43 people died - 32 inmates and 11 prison employees. One guard,
William Quinn, was killed by inmates. The rest died in the gunfire
during the retaking.
</P>
<P>
   ''The public is still under the general misconception that
inmates killed hostages,'' said Smith, who lives in Bliss, Wyoming
County. ''With the exception of Bill Quinn, that did not happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-20-00 2348 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
