<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-20 23:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Second Quake in 4 Days Hits Iceland  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The second earthquake in four days hit Iceland
early Wednesday and was felt throughout the island nation, the U.S.
Geological Survey said. There were no immediate reports of damage
or injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The geological survey said the quake had a preliminary magnitude
of 6.6, the same as Saturday afternoon's shock, and struck 45 miles
east-southeast of Reykjavik, the capital, also like the last.
</P>
<P>
   The quake occurred 6.2 miles below ground, which scientists
characterized as ''very shallow.'' It hit at 12:51 a.m. local time.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's temblor caused some electrical and water outages.
Before the past two quakes, the last event of that size took place
in Iceland in 1910.
</P>
<P>
   Iceland, where there are many active volcanoes, frequently
experiences minor earthquakes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-20-00 2358 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
